<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Publishes Enlargement Cost Estimate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Disputes over enlargement cost
got a muffler today when the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
published its own estimate of enlargement cost today.
</P>
<P>
The Atlantic News, the organ of the 16-nation military
alliance, disclosed in today's issue that the minimal cost to be
added to NATO's common budget has been estimated at 1.3 billion to
1.5 billion U.S. dollars over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The cost estimate, approved by the 16 NATO member states last
Thursday by a tacit procedure that expired that day, will be borne
by the 19 countries that will be NATO members by a year from now,
according to the Atlantic News.
</P>
<P>
The NATO estimated supplementary costs are well below those
published earlier and are expected to further defuse rows over
enlargement cost in the coming meetings of NATO defense ministers
and foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
The current NATO common budget stood at around 1.8 billion
dollars for 1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic are expected to spend
3.5 billion dollars more over two years immediately after
accession in early 1999 to improve military capabilities and to
make them compatible with NATO standards.
</P>
<P>
The NATO estimate of enlargement cost came out of two rounds of
on--the-spot investigation in the three invitee countries and the
estimate, based on the investigation done by NATO's two main
military commands, is expected to be approved by the NATO defense
ministers who meet Tuesday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana said the supplementary
cost of enlargement would be minuscule compared to current NATO
allied defense spending which amounts to 440 billion dollars a
year.
</P>
<P>
NATO is considering spending 700 million, 266 million and 316
million dollars to extend its communications and air defense
networks in Poland, the Czech Republic and Hungary.
</P>
<P>
The amount was described as minimum required to ensure the air
defense and integration of these three countries into the NATO
military structure.
</P>
<P>
The cost of the infrastructure for new member countries are
lower than the original estimate, as the infrastructure is in
rather good shape, the Atlantic News said, though the new members
have to use their own resources to modernize their armed forces
and equipment.
</P>
<P>
The United States Department of Defense provided earlier this
year an estimate which put the 10-year enlargement procedure at
between 27 billion and 35 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the United States Congressional Budget Office put
out an even higher estimate of supplementary cost which ran from
60 billion to 125 billion dollars for the next decade.
</P>
<P>
The two U.S. estimates immediately became focus of criticism as
the European countries within the alliance, the three invitees and
the U.S. Congress aired their disagreement and disconsent.
</P>
<P>
The publication of the NATO estimate of enlargement cost is
expected to facilitate the ratification process slated for early
next year in the parliaments of the 16 NATO member countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
