<HEADLINE> EU to Boost SMEs Cooperation With Mercosur </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- More than 700 small and
medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) from Europe and South America are
to swap experience this week to boost cooperation.
</P>
<P>
European Commissioner Christos Papoutsis, responsible for
enterprise policy, will join Uruguayan President Julio Maria
Sanguinetti in co-chairing a three-day meeting in Montevideo from
Wednesday to Friday.
</P>
<P>
Participating countries include European Union member states
and Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay, Uruguay, Bolivia and Chile. The
South American free-trade zone of Mercosur include Argentina,
Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of the EU-Mercosur Partenariat will be the first
multi-sectorial event supported by the European Commission, the
executive agency of the 15-nation union, in the framework of its
AL-Invest program.
</P>
<P>
The program offers a range of instruments to promote
cooperation between SMEs in South America and the EU and to
encourage and facilitate investment and trade in and between both
regions.
</P>
<P>
The Montevideo meeting will serve as an important vehicle for
the European Commission's policy toward South America. The
commission seeks to create linkage in key industrial sectors.
</P>
<P>
A total of 250 companies were selected from the EU to attend
the Montevideo meeting and they range from agroindustry and food,
textile and clothing, metal and engineering, to plastic and
chemical products.
</P>
<P>
Some 500 companies were selected to participate from Argentina,
Brazil, Paraguay, Uruguay, Bolivia and Chile.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, a direct contact between executive decision
makers, is expected to provide opportunities for SMEs to meet and
explore possibilities for joint ventures and cooperation
agreements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
