<HEADLINE> US Again Rejects Iraq's Inspection Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The United States today
repeated its rejection to Iraq's offer that diplomats and experts
-- but not U.N. weapons inspectors -- be allowed to inspect
President Saddam Hussein's residential areas for U.S.-alleged
hiding weapons.
</P>
<P>
"We are not going to accept it," Bill Richardson, U.S.
ambassador to the United Nations, told ABC in an interview. "We
think it should be U.N. inspectors that are qualified, that know
what they're doing... not diplomats."
</P>
<P>
Iraq made the offer last week to expose "the lies and
falsification" of the United States, which alleged Iraq had hid
weapons of mass destructions in these presidential sites.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi leaders said they extend the invitation to diplomats and
experts of the nations involved in the U.N. weapons inspections
and the five permanent members of the Security Council, but reject
the entry of the U.N. weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
"We reject the idea of anyone who says that the inspection of
people's palaces is the duty of the U.N. Special Commission," Iraq
said in an statement last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
