<HEADLINE> Iran Calls for Broad-based Government in Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi today called for formation of a broad-based government
shared by all groups in Afghanistan, the Iranian official news
agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting of Afghan religious, political and
military figures in Iran's central city of Isfahan, Kharrazi
said that Iran supports any peace-seeking efforts in Afghanistan
by any regional or international body.
</P>
<P>
It was the time to take practical steps to restore a
lasting peace in Afghanistan, he said, adding that "the Afghan
nation, even the neighboring states believe that the crisis in
Afghanistan has no military solution."
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi stressed that foreign interference in Afghanistan
would get nowhere, voicing Iran's opposition to partitioning of
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
He said the Islamic Republic of Iran would use all possible
means at the forthcoming summit of the Organization of the
Islamic Conference (OIC) to be held in Tehran next week to
resolve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
He also proposed to raise fund at the OIC summit for the
homeless people of Afghanistan to ease their sufferings with
regards to the approach of winter season.
</P>
<P>
Afghan religious, political and military figures gathered in
Isfahan this morning to explore ways to end the civil war in
that country.
</P>
<P>
Afghan President Burhanuddin Rabbani, leader of Islamic Party
Gulbuddin Hekmatyar, Vice President Sadeq Parwani, leader of the
Islamic Movement Ayatollah Mohammad Asef Mohseni and hundreds of
other Afghan religious, political and military figures attended
the meeting to discuss ways to restore peace in their war-torn
country.
</P>
<P>
The Rabbani government was ousted from Afghan capital city of
Kabul by Muslim military group Taliban in September 1996. Then
most of the Afghan groups formed a coalition front to fight
against the Taliban forces.
</P>
<P>
The anti-Taliban coalition forces announced recently to form
a "broad-based" national transition government within one month
under the presidency of Rabbani based on understandings reached
among various Afghan political factions.
</P>
<P>
The new provisional government will rule the country only for
nine months until a permanent government was elected by the
people.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the meeting, Iran announced Sunday that it
recognizes the government of President Burhanuddin Rabbani as
the legal government of Afghanistan and there has been no change
in this policy.
</P>
<P>
IRNA today quoted Iran's special representative on Afghanistan
Alaeddin Boroujerdi as saying that Iran's policy is in line
with the international stand adopted by the United
Nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
