<HEADLINE> Survey Points to Inevitable Change in UK's NHS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Many British people are
reluctantly thinking that change in the National Health Service
(NHS) is inevitable and it is likely they will have to pay to use
the NHS in 10 years time, showed a survey which came out today.
</P>
<P>
The survey published today by the Social Market Foundation
found an "expectation gap" between what the public would like the
NHS to deliver and what they believe it will actually be capable
of providing.
</P>
<P>
A great number of the 2,000 adults surveyed expect fewer
treatments to be available on the NHS and anticipate having to buy
more health care in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
More than half of those surveyed think that within a decade
they will have to pay for ambulance services, hospital out-patient
treatment and intensive care.
</P>
<P>
Although 65 percent think the service should remain available
to all and free at point of use, only 13 percent consider that the
most likely outcome.
</P>
<P>
Despite the Labor government's commitment to "save" the almost
50-year-old and long-underfunded NHS in its existing form, the
survey indicated that few people believe this possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
