<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minister: Egypt Not to Increase Oil Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Egypt will not raise its crude
oil production despite a collective hike in the output ceiling of
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, Oil Minister
Hamdi el Banbi said today.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's oil yield, about 870,000 barrels per day (bpd), follows
a national strategy aimed at preserving reserves and finding new
deposits through attracting more international investments in
prospecting, Banbi told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The oil sector has to provide the local market with needed oil
products and at the same time to earn revenues to finance the
implementation of the fourth five-year social and economic plan
beginning July 1 this year, Banbi said.
</P>
<P>
The minister was commenting on an OPEC decision made in
Jakarta, Indonesia on Sunday to increase production quota by 10
percent to reach 27.5 million bpd over a six-month period starting
next January.
</P>
<P>
This was the first major production hike of the organization in
four years, setting off fears across the board that oil prices
might be depressed as a result.
</P>
<P>
But Banbi said Egypt supports the OPEC decision which is
"sound" and will not lead to an ease in crude prices in the world
market. The output rise came with the winter season, when
consumption jumps in Europe, the U.S. and Japan, he explained.
</P>
<P>
The oil minister hoped the OPEC members, which account for 40
percent of the world's total oil production, would abide by their
respective quotas in order to keep oil prices and avoid
jeopardizing oil earnings of other oil producers.
</P>
<P>
With proven crude reserves amounting to 3.9 billion barrels,
Egypt, a non-OPEC member state, is the fourth largest oil exporter
in Africa which sells about half its output on the international
market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
