<HEADLINE> AIDS Cases Down in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The number of AIDS-infected
people has declined in Cyprus which has one of the lowest
infection rates in the world, an official from Ministry of Health
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters on the occasion of the International
AIDS Day, Dr. Dora Papantoniou said efforts to combat AIDS will
continue, and the Ministry will keep up with its enlightenment
campaign, which focuses on the young generation and their sexual
behavior.
</P>
<P>
According to Papantoniou, from 1986 when starting to record
the AIDS cases, until today, 278 people were diagnosed as HIV
positive in Cyprus, of which 162 were Cypriots and the remaining
116 were foreigners. A total of 34 people have died of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the infected belong to the 20 to 40 age group.
</P>
<P>
The Health Ministry announced that no person was diagnosed as
HIV positive in November.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, there has been an increase in people
infected through sexual intercourse, the health official said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the number of Cypriot children infected, which is
this year's International AIDS Day theme, Papantoniou said there
are only two children diagnosed HIV positive on the island.
</P>
<P>
In a message to mark today's International AIDS Day, Health
Minister, Christos Solomis, stressed that it is everyone's duty
to protect children.
</P>
<P>
"It is the family's, the school's, society's, and above all
the state's duty to protect children and provide them with the
necessary knowledge to secure their future," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
