<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Commemorates 10th World AIDS Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) commemorated here today the World AIDS Day for the 10th
time.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the World AIDS Campaign, which was launched in
June, is "Children Living in a World with AIDS." The 1997 campaign
theme will overlap with that of the 1998 campaign, which will
focus on the concerns of young people (ages 15-24), WHO said in a
press release here today.
</P>
<P>
More than 8 million children under the age of 15 will have lost
their mothers or both parents to AIDS and approximately 1,600
children are infected with HIV every day, according to an
estimation by the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent report prepared by the Joint United
Nations Program on HIV/AIDS (UNAIDS), over 30 million adults and
children are now believed to be living with HIV infection. That
means one in 100 adults in the 15-49 age group are infected with
HIV.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that 2.3 million people died of AIDS in 1997, a
50 percent increase over 1996. Nearly half of those deaths were in
women, and 460,000 were in children under 15. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
