<HEADLINE> Zambia Calls for Eradication of Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government said
here today that corruption and undemocratic governance must be
eradicated if southern Africa is to achieve sustainable economic
development.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Education Minister Betram Mmembe said rampant
corruption and the absence of good governance undermines the
confidence citizens are supposed to have in their public
institutions.
</P>
<P>
He made the appeal when he opened the 20th southern African
universities social science conference on democracy, good
governance and economic development on the African continent.
</P>
<P>
He called for concerted efforts from all stakeholders in the
fight against corruption and undemocratic governance if Africa's
economic development is to become a reality.
</P>
<P>
Africa has vast potential to become an economic giant, but
this is not possible if the region is riddled with corruption and
bad governance, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also urged opposition parties and senior civil servants to
observe the code of conduct so as to stamp out corruption.
</P>
<P>
Good governance is critical to the democratic process southern
Africa has embarked on, he said.
</P>
<P>
Over 40 participants from universities in the region are
attending the five-day meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
