<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Government Won't Compromise on Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Lands and
Agriculture Minister Kumbirai Kangai today declared the
government would not compromise on the land acquisition program
to resettle the landless black majority.
</P>
<P>
The minister said at a press conference that the government's
program will compulsorily acquire five million hectares of land,
most of which is now owned by about 4,000 white commercial
farmers.
</P>
<P>
He said the land reform program is of national significance
which should not be allowed to fail.
</P>
<P>
"It is a program that is at the heart of Zimbabwe's national
and economic development process for which we cannot compromise
any further," he said, adding, "we achieve a smooth land
re-distribution program in a peaceful and coordinated manner."
</P>
<P>
He said those who objected to acquisition of their property
should lodge their complaints to his ministry, in writing by
December 28.
</P>
<P>
The minister said land acquisition must not be regarded as an
end in itself but must be seen as a means to improve the
efficiency of agriculture and contribute to increasing farm
incomes, the eradication of poverty and the promotion of an
economically, socially and environmentally sustainable path for
agricultural development in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
He said the designation of the 1,503 farms countrywide to be
compulsorily acquired was to rectify historically created
imbalances.
</P>
<P>
Asked when the current occupiers are expected to vacate the
designated farms, Kangai said the government would give farmers
enough time to harvest their crops.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that by July or August next year we will have
finished the legal processes and that after August we will start
the allocation," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
