<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Chief Urges Effective Ways to Save Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- James Gustave Speth,
administrator of the United Nations Development Program (UNDP),
today urged the international community to act quickly to find
effective and substantial ways and means to save future
generations form the epidemic AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the occasion of World AIDS Day, December 1, Speth
said the theme for this year's commemoration of World AIDS Day is
"Children Living in a World with AIDS." The epidemic has affected
children in complex and dynamic ways.
</P>
<P>
Speth said children may themselves be infected with HIV,
acquired before, during or after birth, or through later sexual
and other risk-related activity.
</P>
<P>
The administrator said most of the nearly 3 million children
under 15 who have infected since the beginning of the epidemic
have developed HIV-related illness, the majority of whom have
already died. Of the estimated 1 million children who are
currently living with HIV, more than 90 percent live in developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
He said HIV infection among family and community members may
have both immediate and long-term effects upon children. Children
may be withdrawn form school to assume economic or caring
responsibilities within the family, thereby diminishing long-term
employment prospects and, in turn, ultimately increasing
vulnerability to exploitation and abuse, and therefore to HIV
infection.
</P>
<P>
Speth stressed that in many places, the survival of community
is already threatened by the death of so many young adults and
children, and the elderly have been left without support.
</P>
<P>
He said a spectrum of response is urgently required: from
prevention to care, support and treatment, to programs of
assistance to those surviving the death of a family member, to
programs which address the broader social and economic
implications of the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
Speth said that if the international community do not act
quickly to find and support appropriate ways and means to respond
to this epidemic, the lives of many future generations will be
bleak, anguish and often brutal. The response must be based upon
hope and respect for human dignity, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
