<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Chief Stresses Different Democratic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Salim Ahmed Salim,
secretary general of the Organization of African Unity (OAU),
today underlined that "democratic experiences are different from
one continent to another, from one country to another and from
one community to another."
</P>
<P>
In his opening address at a conference on democracy, civil
society and governance in Africa here, Salim said that he
personally strongly believes that there are fundamental
democratic principles which are universal and are therefore
applicable to all including African societies.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out that "the democratic traditions of a
nation are deep-rooted in its history and social experience and
are different from those of another nation even if they are close
to each other."
</P>
<P>
"If France, Great Britain and the USA which do share common
democratic values have different political systems with different
democratic traditions and modalities, we should not expect
African countries to follow the same democratic arrangements."
Salim stressed.
</P>
<P>
He said "democracy is not a concept which is alien to our
societies," adding that "we will be blind to our history if we
think that the issue of democracy and good governance is new and
that it is a phenomenon which has emerged recently with the
demands of the donors and as a necessary condition for effective
implementation of programs of economic reforms in African
countries."
</P>
<P>
"The anti-colonial struggle of the African peoples for freedom
and dignity was basically a struggle for human and people's
right," Salim point out.
</P>
<P>
He added, "put differently, colonialism and racial oppression
was in theory and practice anti-democratic."
</P>
<P>
"The struggle for freedom and self determination was a
struggle for democracy and good governance as a prelude to
socio-economic development," Salim noted.
</P>
<P>
African politicians, civil servants, researchers and leaders
of professional associations, non-governmental organizations and
civil society groups are attending the four-day conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
