<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President Jiang Zemin Welcomed to Mexico City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang
Zemin was warmly greeted here today by his Mexican counterpart, E.
Zedillo, with both leaders pledging to further ties between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
A grand ceremony was held to welcome President Jiang at
downtown Campo Marte where red carpets were rolled down, the two
countries' national anthems played and the guard of honor was
reviewed.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang arrived here Sunday night after an overnight
stopover at Cancun, Mexico's southeastern coastal city. He came
over here from a four-day state visit to Canada.
</P>
<P>
He is returning a visit to the trip to China by President
Zedillo a year ago amid signs of closer relations between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
President Zedillo said at the ceremony that Jiang's visit has
provided an important opportunity for both sides to further
develop bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that my talks with President Jiang Zemin will
contribute to better economic and friendly relations between our
two countries," Zedillo said.
</P>
<P>
He added that Mexico and China share the idea of developing
economy and striving for better and closer ties.
</P>
<P>
On his part, President Jiang said that his current visit is
designed to deepen mutual understanding, promote friendship, look
forward to the future and develop cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He said he will discuss with President Zedillo bilateral
relations and major international issues in a joint effort to
establish ties of cooperation for the next century.
</P>
<P>
"Today both countries are facing the same task of safeguarding
sovereignty, developing national economy and striving for overall
social progress and country modernization," jiang stressed.
</P>
<P>
He added that this has laid a solid foundation for better
relations between the two governments and two peoples.
</P>
<P>
China and Mexico established diplomatic relations in 1972 and
bilateral trade grew to 539 million U.S. dollars in 1996 and is
expected to reach 700 million dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
Apart from high-level exchanges, cooperation in science and
technology, culture, law and the military have also born fruits
over the past 25 years and the two sides hold identical or similar
views on many major international issues, the Chinese president
said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief that his current visit will give a new
push to the development of cooperative relations.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents are scheduled to begin their formal meeting
this morning. They are also expected to attend a signing ceremony
at which four agreements on consulate affairs, sports, academic
exchange and agriculture will be inked today.
</P>
<P>
Jiang is expected to wind up his visit Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
