<HEADLINE> Botswana, Namibia Discuss Border Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Botswana and Namibian
officials today agreed to set up a joint commission to decide on
a controversial island between their countries.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached at a joint meeting held in Katima
Mulilo, capital town of Caprivi Province in Namibia, local press
reported.
</P>
<P>
This follows failure by the two sides to determine ownership
of Situngu Island in Namibia's Eastern Caprivi Province, which
borders Angola, Botswana, Zambia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The meeting brought together officials from the Caprivi
Regional Council and from Botswana's Kasane district.
</P>
<P>
The joint commission will work on boundaries of the tiny
island on the Chobe and Linyati rivers, said John Mabuku,
governor of Caprivi provincial government.
</P>
<P>
Ile said the two sides have also agreed the Botswana defense
force should stop patrolling Situngu and disturbing farmers
cultivating the land.
</P>
<P>
Namibian residents living along the Chobe river opposite the
island have also been asked to report any troop movements to the
Botswana authorities.
</P>
<P>
The 60-kilometer-long island is larger than Kasikili, which
both Botswana and Namibia claim. The case awaits a decision from
the International Court of Justice in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Last month, farmers from Singobeka in the Caprivi region, who
set up a cattle post and cultivated land on Situngu island, were
ordered to leave by members of the Botswana defense force.
</P>
</TEXT>
