<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat to Meet Jordanian PM in West Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat is to meet Jordanian
Prime Minister Abdul-Salam Majali in Ramallah Tuesday, a PNA
spokesman said today.
</P>
<P>
PNA's Secretary Tayeb Abdel Rahim said in Gaza today that
Arafat and Majali would discuss Palestinian-Jordanian relations
and the latest political developments of the Israeli-Palestinian
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Topping the agenda is their discussions on the decision made by
the Israeli government Sunday to defer its second-stage troop
redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Cabinet on Sunday approved in principle to carry
out the second-phrase redeployment, but would delay its
implementation until a ministerial panel draws up a map of Israeli
interests in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet also conditioned the redeployment on PNA's
fulfillment of commitments to fight terrorism, amend the
Palestinian Covenant and reduce the size of Palestinian police
force.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli decision has drawn criticism from the PNA, and
Arafat has dismissed it as an attempt to avoid implementing the
signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
Under the Hebron accord and its attachments, Israel should have
completed the first and second of the three-phase pullouts by
early September this year, but Israel has postponed the
redeployments due to the dispute over the scope.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel has begun a campaign to soliciting
international support to its decision on the redeployment, whose
extent and timetable will be determined by the ministerial
committee headed by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
As part of the campaign, Foreign Ministry's Director-General
Eitan Bentsur was dispatched to Cairo Sunday to brief Egyptian
leaders on Israel's decision on further redeployment. Cabinet
Secretary Danny Naveh and Netanyahu's diplomatic adviser Uzi Arad
also traveled to Cairo today to meet with Osama al-Baz, adviser to
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio today quoted Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
as criticizing the Israeli decision for "creating complications"
because it did not answer the Palestinian aspirations.
</P>
<P>
Like Egypt, Jordan has also been a major Arab mediator in the
Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations. Israel is also expected
to try hard to win Jordan's understanding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
