<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HIV Epidemic Far Worse Than Previously Thought: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- A new report released
jointly today by the United Nations Program on HIV/AIDS(UNAIDS)
and the World Health Organization (WHO) shows that infection with
HIV, the virus that causes AIDS, is far common than previously
thought.
</P>
<P>
The report said over 30 million adults and children are now
believed to be living with HIV infection -- one in every 100
sexually active adults worldwide -- and if the current
transmission rate holds steady, by the year 2000 the number of
people living with HIV/AIDS will soar to 40 million.
</P>
<P>
The UNAIDS and WHO now estimate that 5.8 million people were
infected in 1997, at a rate of 16,000 new infections every day.
This includes 590,000 new infections among children, bringing the
total number of children under the age of 15 currently living with
HIV/AIDS to 1.1 million.
</P>
<P>
Because 90 percent of people with HIV live in the developing
countries, where there are few facilities for voluntary testing
and counseling, the UNAIDS estimates conservatively that nine out
of 10 HIV-positive people have no idea they are infected.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that 2.3 million people died of AIDS in 1997, a
5 percent increase over 1996. Nearly half of those deaths were in
women, and 460,000 were in children under 15. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cote d'Ivorie to Impose Sanctions on UNITA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Cote d'Ivoire ambassador to
Angola Etyene Enzo said here today that his country will observe
the United Nations Security Council resolution on imposing
sanctions against the opposition UNITA in Angola.
</P>
<P>
He stated the position of the Cote d'Ivorie government at a
news conference after meeting the United Nations special envoy
based in Angola Blondin Beye.
</P>
<P>
Enzo said that the move of his country is mainly aimed at
adding pressure on the National Union for the Total Independence
of Angola (UNITA) to force it to continue implementing the Lusaka
peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Cote d'Ivoire ambassador said that he and Beye discussed
the Angolan peace process in their talks, adding that it will
succeed finally though it now faces many difficulties.
</P>
<P>
So far, besides Cote d'Ivoire, Zambia, South Africa,
Mozambique and other African countries have announced their
decision to observe the UN resolution passed on October 29 to
impose sanctions on the UNITA. 
</P>
