<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Begins Troop Pullout from Liberia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Roughly ten days after Liberia
said it wanted the west African peacekeeping force (ECOMOG) to
leave, Nigeria has moved to pull its troops out of that country.
</P>
<P>
About 1,400 Nigerian troops in Liberia are due back home this
week under a phased program to reduce the number of the west
African peacekeeping force (ECOMOG) as stipulated by the Abuja
peace accord, the ECOMOG chief said here today.
</P>
<P>
"A ship is already in Monrovia and it will be joined by
another vessel to bring back personnel and materials," said
ECOMOG force commander Major-general Victor Malu.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has some 6,000 troops in ECOMOG, currently estimated
at 11,000-strong from 10 of the 16 countries that make up the
Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS).
</P>
<P>
According to Malu, a ship has already brought back
non-essential materials of the Nigerian contingent ahead of this
week's pullout.
</P>
<P>
The Abuja accord, which ended Liberia's seven-year-old bloody
civil war, provides for gradual pullout of ECOMOG troops, first
sent to that country in August 1990 to help stop the conflict
started by former warlord Charles Taylor in December 1989.
</P>
<P>
The peace agreement also allows ECOMOG troops to stay in
Liberia for another six months after the elected government was
put in place to help restructure and train the armed forces of
the country.
</P>
<P>
On November 20, Taylor, who was sworn in as president last
August, announced his government intended to re-build the
post-war army by itself, warning that the government would expell
anyone in the high command of ECOMOG that attempted to challenge
or share the constitutional power of the president.
</P>
<P>
Taylor said he did not expect anyone in ECOMOG to overstep his
authority and remain in Liberia, adding: "there cannot and will
not be a parallel authority."
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated that he would not allow ECOMOG to use
Liberia's land as a base for attack the military junta in Sierra
Leone that seized power in the May 25 coup.
</P>
<P>
The disagreement between the Liberian government and ECOMOG
has called the attention of ECOWAS chairman, Nigeria's head of
state general Sani Abacha and other west African leaders.
</P>
<P>
The leaders have reportedly taken moves to seek reconciliation
between the two parties.
</P>
<P>
Last week, some 3,000 Nigerian residents in Liberia returned home,
allegedly to flee the harassment and humiliation from the Liberian
security personnel.
</P>
<P>
However, Malu said the thinning out of the Nigerian contingent
had nothing to do with the reported friction between ECOMOG and
Taylor.
</P>
<P>
"The troops' movement is in line with the ECOWAS peace plan on
Liberia," he stated.
</P>
<P>
According to Malu, Benin had also indicated its desire to draw
back its troops from Liberia before the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
Ghana has recently recalled some of its troops under a
rotation plan but sent less to join ECOMOG there.
</P>
<P>
But Malu did not explain why so many Nigerians went back from
Liberia at one time.
</P>
<P>
The ECONMOG commander is in Lagos on his way from Sierra Leone
where he joined the ECOWAS delegation in talks with the junta on
the restoration of ousted civilian government in April next year.
</P>
<P>
According to unconfirmed reports, the talks held last week
ended in deadlock.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
