<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Shares Up on Steady Asian Markets, Firmer Dow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Leading stock markets in Europe
extended their early gains today and finished sharply higher,
boosted by Asian markets' rise, Wall Street's opening rally and a
stronger dollar.
</P>
<P>
British shares in London ended sharply higher, sending the FTSE
100 index back above the 4,900-point level to end 90.00 points up
at 4,921.8.
</P>
<P>
Wall Street provided the main driving force as the Dow raced
ahead following a weaker-than-expected economic report.
</P>
<P>
The latest UK purchasing managers' poll showed that growth in
the manufacturing sector hit a seven-month high.
</P>
<P>
Economists said they would not expect a rate hike on the back
of the figures.
</P>
<P>
The DAX-30 index in Frankfurt also surged sharply, breaching
the key 4,000-point level which was last seen a month ago, to
close at 4,068.05, up 118.91 points or 3.01 percent, also boosted
by a firmer dollar, Wall Street gains and stability in Asian
markets.
</P>
<P>
On the Paris bourse, French shares finished the session with
strong gains, with the CAC-40 index ending up 59.29 points at
2,918.48.
</P>
<P>
The dollar's rise against the franc and relatively calm Asian
markets all cheered the market. The Bank of France left its key
intervention rate on hold at 3.30 percent, as expected.
</P>
</TEXT>
