<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hekmatyar Calls for Free Elections to End Afghan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Afghan ousted Prime Minister and
Islamic Party leader Golbuddin Hekmatyar today called for free
elections in Afghanistan to end the ongoing civil war.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a session of Afghan religious, political and
military figures in Iran's central city of Isfahan, Hekmatyar
said that the solution to the ongoing Afghan crisis lies in the
convention of free elections and formation of a non-coalition
government.
</P>
<P>
He said that such mechanisms as formation of a coalition
government, supreme council system and merger of northern and
southern fronts are not suitable strategies to the Afghan
intricacy, the Iranian official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
Hekmatyar noted that invitation of the factions to the
negotiation table, permanent halt of war, unconditional release of
all prisoners of war (POWs) and agreement on formation of a
temporary non-coalition government comprised of personalities
approved by all serve as preliminaries to arrangement of the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Afghanistan's neighbors can help solve the Afghan crisis
through organization of peace conferences and encouragement of the
groups under their influence to bow to holding talks instead of
involvement in war and prevent offering financial and military
assistance to them, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the 8th summit of the Organization of Islamic
Conference due to be held in Tehran on December 9-11 to seek a
practical solution to the ongoing war in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
However, head of the Afghan Ministry of Religious Guidance,
Endowment and the Hajj Khodadad Erfani announced last month that
the Afghan anti-Taliban coalition forces would form a
"broad-based" national transition government within one month
under the leadership of Afghan President Burhanuddin Rabbani.
</P>
<P>
He said that the new provisional government would rule only
for nine months until a permanent government was elected by
the people.
</P>
<P>
The Afghan capital of Kabul was captured by Taliban forces in
September last year, but the Taliban regime in Kabul has not
been recognized by the international community.
</P>
<P>
Iran, Afghanistan's neighbor, still consider Rabbani's
government as legal. Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi at
the session today also called for the formation of a "broad-based"
government in Afghanistan in order to restore peace in the
war-torn country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
