<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Stresses UN Firm Commitment in Supporting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- UN Secretary-General
Kofi Annan today reiterated the firm commitment of the United
Nations in supporting the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the occasion to commemorate the International Day
of Solidarity with the Palestinian People, November 29, Annan said
that since the General Assembly of the United Nations decided on
November 29, 1947 to partition Palestine, the United Nations has
been deeply involved in the search for an equitable and peaceful
settlement of this issue.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general said the resources of the entire United
Nations family has been mobilized to provide humanitarian and
development assistance, and he pledged to continue these efforts.
</P>
<P>
The UN chief said the commemorative event provides an
opportunity to remind the international community that the
question of Palestine, which lies at the center of the
Arab-Israeli conflict in the Middle East, remains unresolved
despite the many efforts over the years and the undeniable
achievements of the peace process which began at Madrid in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Annan said that with the signing of the historic Declaration of
Principles on September 13, 1993 and subsequent agreements known
as the Oslo process, Israelis and Palestinians embarked on the
road to mutual reconciliation and negotiated peace. Their courage
must be commended, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said it was reassuring that earlier this year, after a
lengthy delay, the protocol concerning the redeployment in Hebron
was signed. It is now of the utmost to prevent those achievements
from dissipating, and to build on them to fulfill the hopes of all
the peoples of the region for a future of peace, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Annan said that regrettably, developments since then have
sparked concern that the peace process is in jeopardy, thus he
appealed to the parties to intensify their efforts to overcome the
obstacles that stand in the way of a speedy return to the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
He said the recent deliberations in the Security Council and
the General Assembly have highlighted the fundamental importance
of respect for the provisions of international law and of full
implementation of the agreements already reached.
</P>
<P>
Annan stressed it is also an apparent and urgent need to make
tangible progress towards a comprehensive, just and lasting
settlement based on relevant Security Council resolutions. The
promotion of social and economic development and of cooperative
relationships throughout the region is essential to create an
environmental favorable to a lasting peace, he said.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general said the United Nations will continue to
attach the utmost importance to improving the living conditions in
the Palestinian territories as an essential accompaniment to the
peace negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopians Urged to Fight Againsy AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, Decemebr 1 (Xinhua)-- Ethiopians today were urged
to unite to fight against the killer disease AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting held here to observe this year's World
Aids campaign which falls on Decemebr 1, 1997, Aberra Kume, head
of Addis Ababa regional health bureau, said that AIDS most often
attacks young adults whose death in their most productive years
of life certainly affect the overall social and economic
development of a country.
</P>
<P>
"Although there is no known cure for AIDS, we can definitely
reduce the risk of contracting HIV infections through several
mechanisms which include, among others, avoiding sexual contact
with multiple partners and the promotion of condom use." he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Ethiopian ministry of health in
collaboration with other governmental organizations and
non-governmental organizations is exerting utmost efforts to
bring about behavioural change among the society particularly the
youth in the fight against the disease.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the occasion, Wedson Mwambazi, representative of
the World Health Organization (WHO) in Ethiopia, said that
"previously AIDS was thought to be the disease of adult men and
women." But he added that "nowadays it is also becoming a disease
of innocent infants."
</P>
<P>
Students drawn from various schools in the metropolis
presented songs, dramas and other literary works at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
This year's World AIDS campaign is observed throughout the
world under the theme "children living in the world with AIDS"
</P>
<P>
A total of 19.433 AIDS cases were reported in Ethiopia in July
1995. However, the actual number of AIDS patients was estimated
by the Ethiopian health ministry to be 350,000. In 1996, the
number of people infected with the HIV virus was estimated to be
1,17 million. Enditiem

=12011933

=12011932
NNNN
03:35 03:35 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
