<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Junta Can't Dictate to ECOWAS, Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- A Nigerian general today
rejected the call of Sierra Leone's military junta for the
exclusion of Nigerian troops from the west African peacekeeping
force (ECOMOG) in that country.
</P>
<P>
The junta cannot dictate to the Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) troops to be used for the implementation
of a peace plan on Sierra Leone, said ECOMOG force commander
Major-general Victor Malu.
</P>
<P>
Pressure, especially military pressure, would be tightened to
force the junta to see the situation with reason, he added.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG is mandated by ECOWAS to enforce a sub-regional
sanction against the junta, which has been endorsed by the United
Nations, to force it to hand over power to the civilian
government it overthrew in a coup on May 25 this year.
</P>
<P>
According to the peace plan signed in October in Conakry,
Guinea, the military regime agrees to step down in April 1998
under the supervision of ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
But the junta has kept demanding Nigerian troops be excluded
from the disarming of Sierra Leonean combatants and opposes to
the dominance of Nigerian soldiers in ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
In an official reaction, Malu said the demand was untenable.
</P>
<P>
"If you remove nigerian troops from ECOMOG, which country in
the sub-region will replace them?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has some 6,000 troops in ECOMOG, currently estimated
at 11,000-strong from 10 of the 16 countries that make up ECOWAS.
</P>
<P>
According to Malu, a similar demand was made by a Liberian
faction during the implementation of that country's peace plan by
ECOWAS, but eventually those behind the suggestion saw the
futility of their demand.
</P>
<P>
He said it was in the interest of the Freetown military
government for ECOWAS to implement the Conakry peace accord,
which provides for a ceasefire, disarmament and demobilization of
combatants ahead of reinstatement of the ousted government of
President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Special Envoy Advocates U.S.-African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. special envoy Jesse
Jackson today said that the new Africa-U.S. relationship is early
in the morning, that is, "a partnership, mutual beneficial trade
relations".
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held here this evening, Jackson, U.S.
President Bill Clinton's special envoy for democracy in Africa,
noted that "Africa is a strategic trade partner (of the United
States) for the future."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that U.S. Secretary of State Albright was
scheduled to visit some African countries this month and
disclosed that President Clinton would pay a visit to Africa in
some time of next year.
</P>
<P>
The special envoy said that his country is importing much oil
from African continent, slightly more than from the Middle East,
adding that Africa's potential as a trading partner and "a
strategic trade ally is enormous".
</P>
<P>
Referring to reforms carried out by Kenya in the past several
years, Jackson stated that "political and economic positive steps
are in the right direction".
</P>
<P>
"Reforms of last three months are heartening", said Jackson,
adding that freedom of assembly and freedom of protest are
hopeful in the east African country.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the December 29 General Election in Kenya, he
emphasized that Kenya needs "world-class elections in order to
restore its credibility and attract foreign investors."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that "if Kenya has a world-class election on
December 29 -- open, free, fair, visible ballot boxes, no
violence -- it will send a signal for the better."
</P>
<P>
Jackson pointed out that there is a deep interest and hope in
Kenya's General Election at the highest levels of the United
States government when he arrived here yesterday.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the U.S. had a growing confidence that Kenya
was on the path to full democracy, adding that "the U.S. has been
favorably impressed by the Inter-Parties Parliamentary Group
process."
</P>
<P>
"My government is pleased by the recent decision to register
parties such as Safina", Jackson said, "the move is a clear
indication that free association is a reality in Kenya."
</P>
<P>
Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi today held talks with Jackson
and the visiting U.S. special envoy also met with some leaders of
Kenya's opposition parties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
