<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No-Confidence Motion Against Netanyahu Rejected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Israel Knesset (Parliament)
today rejected a motion of no-confidence against Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu by a vote of 50 to 45.
</P>
<P>
The motion was tabled by the left wing party Meretz, which
charged that Netanyahu has failed in advancing the Oslo peace
process and there was nothing new in the government decision on
the further redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Meretz leader Yossi Sarid said that " there are no negotiations
and no peace. Meretz will only support steps which has already
agreed on with the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) and the
U.S. Administration. Unilateral Steps by the Israeli government
are not for real peace and have no chance."
</P>
<P>
Israeli Cabinet Sunday approved Netanyahu's proposal that
Israel is to implement further withdrawal from unspecified areas
of the West Bank on condition that Palestinian side fulfills its
commitments under the Hebron Agreement signed last January.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the opposition is continuing to keep the pressure
on the government. Labor party parliament members today voted for
the motion and will also present another no-confidence motion
against Netanyahu next Monday.
</P>
<P>
Labor leader Ehud Barak told Knesset caucus today that
Netanyahu has lost all credibility with the Palestinians and the
United States and the Labor will support the serious move toward
peace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Play Larger Role in Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The European Union Envoy to
the Middle East Miguel Angel Moratinos said today that the
EU will announce its new Middle East policy at next month's
European summit aimed at further strengthening its role in the
deadlocked peace talks.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Lebanon's Prime Minister Rafik Hariri, he
told the news conference that EU enjoys a common viewpoint
with Lebanon which stresses the importance of a stronger and
larger role played by EU in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
He said that the objective of his visit to Lebanon, the second
in less than one month, is to make preparations for the summit in
which some change will be made to the European traditional Middle
East policy.
</P>
<P>
"The EU role in the Middle East should be presented in
politics, culture and economic fields," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that the EU and the U.S. roles are
complementary. The parties concerned in the peace talks
simultaneously demand the U.S. mediation as well as the EU's.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos who arrived in Lebanon on Sunday for a two-day visit,
also held talks with Lebanese House Speaker Nabih Berry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
