<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Envoy: Presence in Chinese Market Vital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Germany's ambassador to China
Konrad Seitz has said that a strong market position in China is
vital for German large companies to keep their global
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the German General Anzeiger newspaper
today, Seitz said that China has already become the largest market
in the world for many industrial products, in particular capital
goods.
</P>
<P>
Taking power plants as an example, Seitz said the demand in
China alone already amounts to 25 percent of the world total. The
annual Chinese demand for the digital telephone exchange systems
is also larger than the combined demand in western Europe and
North America, he added.
</P>
<P>
For German transnational companies like the electronics giant
Siemens, a strong market position in China will help to reduce the
unit development costs of their products and will hence enhance
their competitiveness even on the European market, Seitz noted.
</P>
<P>
As a major success achieved by German companies in China, Seitz
referred to Volkswagen AG, which has invested 3.4 billion marks
(1.9 billion U.S. dollars) in China so far and has managed to
boost its market share in the country to over 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
This represents an unbelievable comeback for Volkswagen when
compared with its dwindling market shares in Asia forced by the
Japanese competitors in the 1960s and 1970s, Seitz said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the problem that small- and medium-sized German
companies are reluctant to take risks in China, the German
ambassador pointed to the reality that many smaller German
companies do perform successfully in China currently and it is
often true that they can do business there much easier than large
companies.
</P>
<P>
Seitz also dismissed the notion that the China-bound massive
investment is taking numerous jobs out of Germany, saying that by
setting up factories in China, German companies can boost the
exports of German-made machines and supplies parts, which means
more jobs at home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. FTC Revises Interpretation of "Made in USA" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Under the high pressure from
the Congress and labor groups, the Federal Trade Commission(FTC)
decided today that products bearing the "Made in USA" label must
be produced almost entirely with U.S. labor and materials.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. commission proposed in May that companies could use
the "Made in USA" label if a product had more than a small amount
of foreign content and labor. Under that proposal, merchandise
with as little as 75 percent U.S. parts would be eligible.
</P>
<P>
The FTC suggested that easing the standard would give the
country's enterprises the flexibility to compete worldwide while
ensuring consumers were not deceived.
</P>
<P>
However, the suggestion was strongly rejected by government
officials and organized labor. They argued it would encourage
corporations to send jobs overseas.
</P>
<P>
The attorneys general of 16 states jointly asked that the "Made
in USA" label be allowed only on products with at least 90 percent
U.S. content.
</P>
<P>
The FTC also said most of more than 1,000 written comments it
has received since May strongly supported the current 50-year-old
standard. The FTC voted 4-0 today to continue requiring that
claims of U.S. origin be substantiated by evidence that a product
is "all or virtually all" made in this country.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made after two years of study, including a
two-day public workshop and requests for public comment.
</P>
<P>
The FTC said that although there is no "bright line" to
establish when a product is "all or virtually all" made in the
United States, it would consider several factors.
</P>
<P>
These include first, "the final assembly or processing of the
product must take place in the United States". Other factors will
be the portion of the product's total manufacturing costs that are
attributable to U.S. parts and processing and how far removed from
the finished product any foreign content is.
</P>
<P>
In a policy statement to be published Tuesday in the Federal
Register, the commission said that when a "marketer makes an
unqualified claim that a product is "Made in USA," it should...
possess and rely upon a reasonable basis that the product is in
fact all or virtually all made in the United States."
</P>
<P>
The standard applies to all products advertized or sold in the
United States except for those governed by specific legislation.
For instance, country-of-origin labeling of clothing is generally
governed by the Textile Act.
</P>
<P>
Marketers will continue to make qualified U.S. origin claims,
such as "Made in USA of U.S. and imported parts" and "80% Made in
USA," as well as claims about specific processes or parts and
comparative claims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
