<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Talks to Arafat Over Phone on Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu today told Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
President Yasser Arafat that Israel's decision to pull back troops
from the West Bank is an "opportunity" for pushing the peace
process forward.
</P>
<P>
The decision is "an opportunity to promote the peace process,"
said Netanyahu while Arafat on the plan over telephone, according
to a statement issued by the Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
During the telephone call to Arafat, Netanyahu asserted that
"following the consolidation of the cabinet decision on this
matter, it is important that the two sides speak to each other in
order to make progress in the peace process."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made the call after his cabinet approved Sunday in
principle to carry out the second of the three-phase troop
redeployments stipulated under the Hebron accords signed last
January. But the cabinet did not spell out the extent and
timetable for implementing the pullout, adding the details would
be determined by a ministerial panel headed by Netanyahu and
includes ministers of foreign affairs, defense and national
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Israeli government also conditioned the implementation of the
second redeployment on the PNA's fulfillment of its commitments,
including fighting terrorism, amending the Palestinian Covenant
and reducing the size of Palestinian police forces.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli decision to further defer the second redeployment,
which should have been finished in early September, drew strong
criticism from the PNA. Arafat told a Fatah meeting Sunday night
that the Israeli decision was an attempt to avoid implementing
the signed peace agreements.
</P>
<P>
PNA chief negotiator Saeb Erekat dismissed the decision as
"being too vague, too little and much too late." 
</P>
</TEXT>
