<HEADLINE> Blair Sets up Commission to Reform Voting System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair today ordered the forming of a commission to prepare for a
referendum on replacing first-past-the-post system with
proportional representation.
</P>
<P>
An Electoral Reform Commission will be set up to decide on an
alternative system for electing the lower House of Commons which
would be pitted against first-past-the-post in the plebiscite.
</P>
<P>
The commission has one year to produce a "proportional" system,
which would be more fair to small political parties.
</P>
<P>
The commission's terms of reference require it to "observe the
requirement for broad proportionality," Interior Minister Jack
Straw said in answer to a parliamentary question.
</P>
<P>
The commission will be chaired by Lord Roy Jenkins, a former
European Union Commission President, who has just stepped down
from the leadership of the Liberal Democrats in the upper House of
Lords.
</P>
<P>
But Blair's official spokesman said the prime minister remained
personally "unpersuaded" of the case for proportional
representation.
</P>
<P>
"We will take a view on how to respond to the commission's
recommendation when it is made," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
