<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Youths Play with Sex Despite Known </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Although many young people in
Nigeria are aware that having unprotected sexual intercourse
could expose them to sexually-transmitted diseases and AIDS or
could result in unwanted pregnancy, they still engage in unsafe
sex.
</P>
<P>
This is the conclusion of a survey by the Society for Family
Health (SFFH) in six of the 36 states across the country on the
eve of the second World AIDS Day.
</P>
<P>
According to Zacch Akinyemi, AFFH's research and communication
manager, the respondents of the survey said they had to engage in
sex for sexual pleasure and financial gains.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted among adolescents aged between 13 and 19
years, also revealed that most of youths still believed they
could not contract AIDS even if they engaged in unsafe sex.
</P>
<P>
"Many think unsafe sex can be equated with unprotected sex,
while still many others do not believe pregnancy can occur at the
first sexual encounter," he said, quoted by the News Agency of
Nigeria today.
</P>
<P>
According to him, more than 70 percent of the 2,256 youths
interviewed got their knowledge about adolescent sexuality from
their peers, mothers, television, the media and siblings, in that
order.
</P>
<P>
The study further showed that the age for being initiated into
sex had fallen from around 16 to 14 years, Akinyemi said, adding
that till around 19 years, more boys were sexually experienced
than girls generally.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, most youths use contraceptives only
when they have casual relationships and the number of partners
maintained by each youth ranges from one to 25.
</P>
<P>
More than one fifth of girls interviewed have had at least one
pregnancy terminated although it could be argued that some
reported miscarriages could in fact be induced abortion, the
research manager said.
</P>
<P>
For suggestions on how to redress the situation, the youths
said parents should be educated to answer all their children's
questions on sexuality while a newsletter on the research
findings could be established to advise parents on how to go
about this.
</P>
<P>
The youths called for drama and television shows to X-ray the
problems of unwanted pregnancy and unsafe sex, while counsellors
should be appointed from their peers who are sexually
experienced.
</P>
<P>
The respondents said condom should be made available and
accessible, booklets on sexuality provided free, educational
programs should employ sexually-active persons to deal with
youths insecurities.
</P>
<P>
The youths agreed that making public, the high percentage of
abortion among teenagers could make positive change.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
