<HEADLINE> Iraq Still Rejects UNSCOM Inspection of Presidential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Foreign Minister
Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf today reiterated Iraq's stance that it
would not allow U.N. weapon inspectors to enter any Iraqi
presidential palaces.
</P>
<P>
Sahhaf said at a news conference that "all presidential sites
enjoy the diplomatic immunity and cannot be inspected. They have
nothing to do with the mission of the U.N. Special Commission
(UNSCOM) in charge of eliminating weapons of mass destruction in
Iraq."
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister also said Iraq's invitation to teams from
countries with representation in the U.N. Security Council and
the special commission to visit the presidential sites "stand
sound and valid" and can be implemented at any moment.
</P>
<P>
Sahhaf criticized the United States for manipulating the
UNSCOM, saying that "the Americans have to be made to realize
that the special commission is no longer a political tool in
their hands."
</P>
<P>
He urged the Security Council to recompose the special
commission in a balanced way "exactly as Iraq has suggested."
</P>
<P>
Iraq required in early November that the permanent members of
the Security Council send equal numbers of staffs to the special
commission to avoid the domination by a single country.
</P>
<P>
In order to bring an early end to the U.N. sanctions, the
Iraqi Revolution Command Council decided on November 26 to invite
representatives from the 20 countries that take part in the
U.N. inspection teams and experts or diplomats from the 15
U.N. Security Council members to inspect sites in Iraq under
suspicion of hiding weapons of mass destruction, like chemical or
biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has so far not allowed U.N. arms inspection teams to
enter its presidential sites.  
</P>
</TEXT>
