<HEADLINE> U.S., World Bank to Back Rescue Program for South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) --The United States and the
World Bank said today they would join a rescue package for South
Korea under the right conditions, but declined to reveal how much
money they could offer.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. President Bill Clinton told reporters he was willing
to offer U.S. funds for the effort if Seoul reached an agreement
with the International Monetary Fund (IMF) that included tough
reforms.
</P>
<P>
"I favor a strong agreement with the IMF that would actually
restore financial stability and confidence in South Korea,"
Clinton said. "If such an agreement could be made, then I would
favor the United States participating."
</P>
<P>
Clinton avoided answering questions about how much aid the
United States might contribute to an IMF-led aid package. Korean
media reports suggested the United States and Japan might
contribute in a total of 20 billion U.S. dollars to an overall 55
billion dollar aid package.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the World Bank spokesman Graham Barrett expressed
today that the bank had also been approached for help and expected
to join the rescue deal.
</P>
<P>
"We want this to be a substantial contribution, and a quick
one," he said. "We are working very intensively with the (South
Korean) government and the IMF, as the lead institution on this
issue."
</P>
<P>
It was reported the international bail-out package for South
Korea might be for a record-breaking 55 billion dollars, even
bigger than the rescue program for Mexico which was totaling some
50 billion dollars in 1995 and much bigger than Indonesia's 40
billion dollar deal. The United States, the main figure in the
1995 Mexico bailout, contributed 3 billion dollars to the
Indonesian rescue deal. 
</P>
