<HEADLINE> Feature: "Protect Us Against HIV/AIDS," Cry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Zambian children appealed to
the society for their protection against HIV/AIDS and demanded to
live in circumstances without the deadly epidemic.
</P>
<P>
During a ceremony held in the five-star Pomodzi Hotel in the
capital this evening to release the book HIV/AIDS in Zambia
compiled by Ministry of Health and Central Board of Health,
dozens of Zambian children made performances to express their
concern over the killer disease.
</P>
<P>
They asked their fathers and mothers not to leave them as
orphans and begged the responsible politicians to take effective
measures to protect them.
</P>
<P>
"Fathers, mothers and politicians, please protect us and save
us. We want parents! We don't want HIV/AIDS!" cried one
eight-year old boy during a performance, which aroused warm
applause as well as tears among several hundred adult audiences.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony, which is designed to commemorate the 1997 World
AIDS Day, attracted several Zambian political elites including
Finance Minister Ronald Panza, Health Minister Katele Kalumba as
well as visiting U.S. congressman Elijah Cummings.
</P>
<P>
In a moving speech, Cummings called on the Zambians to behave
themselves and look after their children carefully in order to
prevent the "innocent and vulnerable group" from falling victims
of the horrible disease.
</P>
<P>
"We must be one in protecting the children," the black
congressman shouted with his fist raised in the air and tears
rolling down his face.
</P>
<P>
In their separate speeches, both Panza and Kalumba stressed
the urgent need and expressed the Zambian government's unwavering
determination to fight against the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
HIV/AIDS is a social, economic, political as well as cultural
problem, which, if not be contained, will certainly neutralize
the country's efforts to develop its economy and to eradicate its
general poverty.
</P>
<P>
According to the book released this evening, Zambia is
undergoing one of the worst HIV/AIDS epidemics in the world and
20 percent of the adults have been infected with HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The book graphically pointed out the serious consequence of
AIDS deaths to men and women in their childrearing ages. That is
the increase in the number of orphans.
</P>
<P>
It warned that the number of maternal and double orphans in
Zambia would rise quickly from 20,000 in 1990 to over 500,000 in
2000 and to more than one million in 2010, which will become a
serious social problem and place a heavy burden on the future
governments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
