<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Egypt Goes All Out to Support Tourism  (by Hou Jia) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has reduced air fares,
scrapped entry fees and beefed up security in an all-out campaign
to buoy up the flagging tourism stricken by a recent terrorist
attack on foreign visitors.
</P>
<P>
EgyptAir, the national carrier, halved the price tags of all
domestic flights while the Ministry of Transport and
Communications removed dues on landing or take-off at Egyptian
airports and berthing at its ports.
</P>
<P>
The series of decisions were reviewed by Prime Minister Kamal
el-Ganzouri and several cabinet ministers who met today to weigh
the negative effects of the November 17 massacre of foreign
tourists in the southern Egyptian attraction of Luxor.
</P>
<P>
Following the meeting, Information Minister Safwat al-Sherif
told reporters that Egypt will cancel all additional dues imposed
by local administrations on visits to tourist areas and any other
tourist activities.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry, on the other hand, is making intensive
diplomatic efforts at embassy and consulate levels to capitalize
on "international understanding of the truth of the phenomenon of
terrorism."
</P>
<P>
The government advised private tourist and hotel companies to
go ahead with their promotion and marketing and refrain from doing
anything untoward. Today's ministers' meeting warned of license
withdrawal for those who try to lay off employees or manipulate
prices.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Central Bank, in a report on supporting and
easing the burden of the tourism sector, said Egyptian banks have
agreed to continue financing tourist projects and to defer for
three months the payment of installments owed by tourist
establishments and projects.
</P>
<P>
These measures have came hand in hand with a tougher and
comprehensive security plan on the heels of the carnage in Luxor,
about 500 kilometers south of Cairo, where six gunmen in black
police uniforms shot dead 58 foreign tourists and four Egyptians
before they were gunned down by the police.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two weeks, Egypt has carried out a massive
reshuffle in the security and police forces, reportedly involving
some 300 people, to shore up people's morale.
</P>
<P>
Within two days in office, the new interior minister, Habib Al
Adly, unveiled a "water-tight" security plan enlisting the help of
the military in maintaining security in tourist sites and
administering tougher penalties on abuses of police uniforms.
</P>
<P>
Admitting a security slip-up in Luxor, President Hosni Mubarak
said accused foreign governments of giving shelter to fugitive
Egyptian militants and in fact encouraging their operations in
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The government on November 27 issued a list of 14 leading
Egyptian Islamic militants allegedly masterminding violent acts
and urged the international community to work collectively to deny
them any safe haven.
</P>
<P>
The appalling killing of foreign tourists dealt a severe blow
to Egypt's lucrative tourism industry, wiping out the hope to
attract up to 4 million visitors this year. Thousands of
foreigners have canceled their trips after the Luxor slayings, the
worst in the country for years.
</P>
<P>
Tourism has become a 3.5-billion-dollar-per-year industry and
one of the main supports of the country's economy. Statistics show
every foreign tourist spends an averaged 1,000 dollars in Egypt
and brings about job opportunities for four Egyptians.
</P>
<P>
With much fewer foreign arrivals, tourism revenues are
estimated by experts to dwindle by some 2 billion dollars next
year, eventually snowballing to shave off some 6 billion dollars
from the gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
Hard hurt will be those 5-8 million Egyptians directly or
indirectly employed in the tourism sector as job opportunities
have been scarce in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Construction Spending Moves Up in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. construction
spending picked up by 0.1 percent in October, the fourth
consecutive month without a decline, the Commerce Department said
here today.
</P>
<P>
The increase to a record high seasonally adjusted annual rate
of 605.5 billion U.S. dollars came in the wake of a 0.4 percent
advance in September, the department noted.
</P>
<P>
The growth in October was led by a 0.7 percent increase in
residential construction to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of
265.6 billion dollars. Single-family construction rose 1.1 percent
to an all-time high while apartment building shot up 5.7 percent
to the highest level in nearly 10 years. But remodeling spending
declined.
</P>
<P>
Government construction increased 0.6 percent to a rate of
139.1 billion dollars. The growth was contributed by public
housing and redevelopment, schools, hospitals and at military
bases offset declines in spending on government offices, streets
and highways and water supply facilities.
</P>
<P>
Non-residential commercial construction fell 1.2 percent, which
representing the third monthly drop in a row, to a rate of 160.7
billion dollars. A decline in spending at factories, private
hospitals and hotels and motels more than offset gains for
offices, private schools and churches. 
</P>
</TEXT>
