<HEADLINE> Iraqi FM Urges UN Sanctions Committee to Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed
Saeed al-Sahhaf said today that there should be several changes in
the procedures of the U.N. sanctions committee.
</P>
<P>
Sahhaf said at today's news conference that it would be
unacceptable for Iraq to accept "the same defects and the same
problems and the same delay practice" as what had happened in the
first and second phases of the implementation of the oil-for-food
program.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said that all the permanent members of
the Security Council except the United States "have new ideas
and new suggestions."
</P>
<P>
He criticized the United States for obstructing the approval
of contracts signed by Iraq with other countries under the
oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
"As for the other sectors," he added that "there should be
idea of what we have suggested, as long as it is included in the
plan of distribution."
</P>
<P>
Answering a question on whether Iraq would reject an extension
to the third phase of the oil-for-food program if the Security
Council maintained the current format, Sahhaf said that "we have
received commitments that it would not be the same."
</P>
<P>
However, he added that "for sure, we will reject, we will
reject if they come again with the same kind of resolution."
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan today reportedly urged the
Security Council to consider raising the amount of oil revenue
Iraq can spend on food and medicine in a bid to ease the
suffering of the Iraqi people due to the U.N. imposed sanction.
</P>
