<HEADLINE> Syria Holds Seminar on Combating AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Syria held a seminar on
combating AIDS under the theme of "Let Us Safeguard Our Children
From AIDS" to mark the World AIDS Day today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session, Syria's Minister of Health
Iyad el-Shatti said that Syria is exerting efforts to implement
health programs to prevent AIDS.
</P>
<P>
He said that only 151 AIDS cases have been found in Syria,
including 54 foreigners, and no more than 11 cases reported this
year.
</P>
<P>
Syria is closely monitoring the deadly disease, and conducts
250,000 tests annually, Shatti said, adding that 192,000 tests
have been undertaken in the last nine months compared to 153,000
in the whole of last year.
</P>
<P>
He underlined that the blood kept in Syria's blood banks is
absolutely free from pollution.
</P>
<P>
The minister disclosed that Syria has adopted the strategy of
the World Health Organization of preventive measures against AIDS,
which lie in correct practices, right customs and traditions, and
a healthy lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the infection of the disease is made possible
only through unsafe sex relations, blood transfusion and injection
with polluted needle.
</P>
<P>
At the seminar, Director of the Office of the United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF) in Damascus Nihad Qanawati described AIDS
as a grave threat not only to adults but to children as well.
</P>
<P>
She said 3 million children under 15 have been diagnosed to
contract AIDS, and that about 1,000 of them died every day last
year.
</P>
<P>
She asserted that UNICEF will spare no efforts in combating
AIDS, particularly among children threatened by AIDS and suffering
from the disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
