<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Calls for U.S. National Security Transformation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- A congressionally chartered
panel today called on the Pentagon to cope with new threats in the
21st century, paying more attention to defending U.S. cities
rather than just being prepared for two wars in other regions.
</P>
<P>
"Our interests will be challenged in new ways," said Philip
Odeen, Chairman of the nine-member National Defense Panel. "We may
have to cope with new or changing regional threats. Some of these
new challenges may differ markedly from those we plan for today."
</P>
<P>
The 94-page report, "Transforming Defense: National Security in
the 21st Century," said that the U.S. military, which has
protected the nation's interests in the past, may not be able to
solve the future problems.
</P>
<P>
He said that the United States is likely to have to cope with
penetrations of its information systems, mass destruction, and
attacks against U.S. cities and satellites.
</P>
<P>
The Panel calls for a comprehensive reshaping of the skills and
capabilities of the armed forces to adapt the U.S. forces from the
Cold War era to the security threats that are likely to face
America and its allies 20 years from now. It urges that the
process begin immediately.
</P>
<P>
"This transformation must be undertaken as a part of an overall
reassessment and redesign of our national security structure,"
said Odeen. "The challenges we face do not follow traditional
bureaucratic or geographical boundaries. They go beyond today's
national security structures and require the interaction of local
and national domestic agencies, non-governmental organizations,
traditional allies, and new international partners," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Panel suggested that the American forces should make
greater mobility, precision, speed, stealth and strike ranges
while sharply reducing their logistics and support "footprint."
</P>
<P>
"All operations will be increasingly joint, combined (with
allies), and interagency," added the group.
</P>
<P>
The Panel said that the Pentagon should devote 5 billion to 10
billion U.S. dollars a year to developing the new strategy through
experimentation with new weapons and warfighting concepts.
</P>
<P>
The report said the Pentagon should move away from its
familiar assumption that the armed forces must be able to fight
two major regional wars at the same time. It said the two-war
strategy is becoming an obstacle to long-term change.
</P>
<P>
The Panel agreed with the Pantegon's suggestion to shrink the
current force levels and close additional military bases in order
to finance weaponry development.
</P>
<P>
Congress created the National Defense Panel a year ago at the
same time it instructed the Pentagon to review military programs
through 2005. The panel was asked to provide an alternative view
of the Defense Department's "Quadrennial Defense Review" and to
take a longer-range look at defense needs.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Department was not immediately commenting on the
report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
