<HEADLINE> HIV/AIDS Threatens Zambia's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Zambian finance minister Ronald
Penza said here today that although Zambia's macro-economic
stabilization is being achieved, the HIV/AIDS epidemic threatens
people's expectations for a high standard of living.
</P>
<P>
To mark World AIDSs Day which falls on December 1, Penza said
"a bold and innovative process is taking place in Zambia to
restructure our economy and to expend our social infrastructure.
Clearly, a stable and growing economy fuels social development
and facilitates the provision of quality goods and services."
</P>
<P>
"As we enter the next millennium, Zambians can realistically
aspire to a standard of living considered to be a human right in
richer countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, these expectations are now threatened by the HIV/AIDS
epideic. AIDS is a relentless killer that has the potential to
sabotage the economic and social gains achieved during the past
few years, he said when he launched the book "HIV/AIDS in Zambia:
Bakcground, Projections, Impact and iIterventions".
</P>
<P>
He said the economic impact of HIV/AIDS is difficult to
predict, but it is evident that widespread sickness and mortality
of the productive segment of the population are affecting the
operation of economy.
</P>
<P>
AIDS related illnesses and deaths to employees treaten this
objective by both increeasing costs and reducing revenues for
companies in his country, Penza said.
</P>
<P>
AIDS is attacking the most productive segment of Zambia's
population, primarily people between 15 and 49 years of age and
nearly 20 percent of the adult population is infected with HIV,
he said.
</P>
<P>
It is projected that the number of maternal and double orphans
will rise to over 500,000 in the year 2000, and to more than one
million in 2010.
</P>
<P>
However, Penza said there are opportunities to control and
prevent the spread of AIDS. "We are not helpless victims of the
epidemic, but that we have the power to control our destiny," the
minister added.
</P>
<P>
Today activities including marches, rallies and performances
were held across the country to mark the World AIDS Day.
</P>
<P>
At the rallies speakers called on Zambians to change the
behaviour to protect themselves and the children from AIDS.
</P>
</TEXT>
