<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Devaluation Not Necessarily Means Competitiveness: HK Seminar  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the short run, these asset price decreases will be painful
for some, but they will help reduce cost pressures for the economy
as a whole, Fung argued.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, "the regional currency swings may affect business,
they do not necessarily threaten Hong Kong's competitiveness,"
Fung continued.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong's long-term competitive advantages are actually
undervalued. Hong Kong is a premium product. You pay more - but
you get more," Fung concluded.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Secretary for Trade and Industry Tam Wing-pong offered
similar views from the government's perspective.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong dollar's peg to the U.S. dollar offers the sort
of stability or security for the local economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
"If your currency fluctuates from time to time, the willingness
of investors will naturally be affected in the long term," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The devaluation of other currencies in the region was not
designed to improve competitiveness, instead it was out of
economic concerns, Tam remarked.
</P>
<P>
The official pointed out that Hong Kong's competitiveness has
not significantly diminished in the wake of the turmoil.
</P>
<P>
According to him, it would be fatal if Hong Kong tries to
compete on cost, but "Hong Kong can compete on other areas where
its competitiveness lies."
</P>
<P>
First of all, Hong Kong is sitting at the doorstep of a huge
economy with almost boundless opportunity, which gives the city a
unrivaled advantage to play as a bridge for the two-way traffic
between the Chinese inland areas and the other part of the world,
Tam pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Resilience of the economy and the top-caliber business people
are another two strengths making Hong Kong competitive, he added.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Michael Enright, a visiting professor at Hong Kong
University, agreed that although Hong Kong has felt the contagious
effect of the regional crisis, that "doesn't necessarily mean a
decline in competitiveness."
</P>
<P>
On the strategy to foster medium- and long-term
competitiveness, the scholar suggested focusing on issues such as
education and training, infrastructure and environment.
</P>
<P>
It is very important for Hong Kong to make moves that are
difficult or impossible to copy, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
