<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Calls for Swedish Investment, Stronger Baltic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Russia President Boris
Yeltsin said here today Swedish investments should not be
discouraged by the West's exaggeration of Russia's bureaucracy,
corruption and organized crime.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin is on a three-day visit beginning today. His visit,
the first by a Russian head of state since 1909, is expected to be
dominated by Baltic security and trade.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Swedish news agency TT, Yeltsin called on
Swedish businessmen to invest more in Russia, saying the
proportion of bureaucracy, corruption and organized crime has been
considerably overestimated by Western media.
</P>
<P>
He told the news agency that cooperation between countries
around the Baltic Sea and above all relations between Sweden and
Russia will be on the top of his agenda.
</P>
<P>
Trade between Sweden and Russia has intensified since 1991 with
Russian statistics listing Sweden as its seventh largest foreign
investor in 1996.
</P>
<P>
A number of business representatives were among Yeltsin's
entourage of about 200 people. He is due to meet Swedish Prime
Minister Goran Persson later today and sign about eight bilateral
agreements on various issues including economic cooperation, trade
and combating crime.
</P>
<P>
Also topping Yeltsin's agenda will be Russia's relationship
with the Baltic states -- Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania.
</P>
<P>
He said his country is sincerely interested in building
good-neighborly relations with the Baltic states.
</P>
<P>
Russia has repeatedly proposed to provide a security guarantee
to the Baltic region in an attempt to dissuade the three Baltic
countries from seeking entry into the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
During the interview, Yeltsin praised Sweden for its policy of
neutrality and non-alignment, saying that would only strengthen
the European security system.
</P>
<P>
Sweden, a neutral country in the Baltic since the early 19th
century, says it would stay out of any military alliance but would
continue its cooperation within NATO's Partnership for Peace
program -- a cooperation program with former eastern bloc
countries and other European non-NATO countries on regional
defense. 
</P>
</TEXT>
