<HEADLINE> Irish Shoppers Urged to Boycott UK Goods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Irish shoppers have been urged
to boycott British produce after Welsh famers' action against meat
imports from the Irish Republic.
</P>
<P>
About 500 Welsh farmers blockaded the port of Fishguard early
today, forcing back to Ireland six trucks carrying what they said
were cheap beef imports.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Press Association reported that the farmers stood in
front of the entrance to the southern Welsh port for two hours
after a ferry arrived at 1 am from Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Over 600 Welsh farmers blockading the Irish port of Holyhead
Monday threw a truckload of Irish beef-burgers into the sea.
</P>
<P>
Irish truckers' leader Jimmy Quinn was quoted as saying, "The
action was a deliberate attempt to sabotage the Irish meat export
trade."
</P>
<P>
Quinn, of the Irish Road Haulers Association, said that he was
very disappointed with the Welsh farmers and he asked Irish people
to avoid UK goods.
</P>
<P>
The Welsh farmers were reportedly seeking an urgent meeting
with Welsh Secretary Ron Davies to discuss the situation.
</P>
<P>
British beef farmers' incomes have plunged since the discovery
of link between bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE) and its
brain-wasting human equivalent, Creutzfeldt Jakob disease (CJD).
</P>
</TEXT>
