<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Strategic Planners Meet in Brussels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- NATO military chiefs were
reassured Tuesday about the safety of Russia's nuclear weapons when
they met here for their year-end ministerial meeting.
</P>
<P>
A NATO spokesman told the press that the NATO nuclear planning
group was briefed about the status of Russia's tactical nuclear
forces and was reassured that Russia was devoting efforts and
resources to safeguard its nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
Russia and the United States have established a reciprocal
exchange between their strategic force commanders. A senior U.S.
strategic commander, who has recently visited Russian nuclear
installations, briefed the NATO military chiefs.
</P>
<P>
The issue concerning nuclear weapons safety will be discussed
for the first time in Wednesday's NATO-Russia Permanent Joint
Council (PJC) meeting, which will be held in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman, who asked not to be identified, quoted
participants at the nuclear planning group meeting as saying that
the dialogue between NATO and Russia will foster increased
transparency and improve understanding of the role of nuclear
weapons in the security strategies of NATO and the Russian
Federation.
</P>
<P>
He said the outcome of the nuclear discussion at the PJC
meeting would be fruitful.
</P>
<P>
NATO strategists agreed that nuclear forces continue to play an
essential role in NATO strategy and their fundamental purpose is
political.
</P>
<P>
NATO officials said that nuclear forces are expected to help
preserve peace and prevent coercion and war.
</P>
<P>
During today's defense planning committee meeting, NATO
military chiefs reaffirmed their determination to ensure the
effectiveness and coherence of individual and collective military
capabilities to fulfill the full range of NATO missions.
</P>
<P>
As for a justification for non-Article V missions, the defense
planning committee agreed that it must be sufficiently flexible to
meet the demands of a changing and more complex security
environment.
</P>
<P>
Article five of the North Atlantic Treaty calls for military
action only when one or several members of the alliance is under
attack, which the treaty defines as an attack against all NATO
members.
</P>
<P>
NATO is shifting its strategic focus from defense of members'
territories to defense of members' common interests threatened by
crises that have been triggered by nationalism, ethnicity,
religion, social-economy or environment.
</P>
<P>
NATO defense ministers are slated to discuss later today the
issue of whether and how to maintain the SFOR forces in the former
Yugoslav republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina to make the Dayton peace
accord last. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
