<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak President Formally Tenders His Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 2 (Xinhua) -- President Farooq Leghari has
formally tendered his resignation soon after addressing a news
conference here this evening, sources said.
</P>
<P>
The 23-word resignation letter has been sent to Speaker of the
National Assembly Ellahi Soomro, they said, adding Leghari left
his office
for residential quarters of the Presidency immediately after
signing the
letter.
</P>
<P>
Leghari, who assumed his office as president four years ago,
told a crowded news conference here this evening that he received
today a summary to disqualify Chief Justice Sajjad and appoint the
senior most judge of the Supreme Court as the next Chief Justice.
</P>
<P>
The outgoing president said he had no option but to sign it.
But, instead, he decided to quit.
</P>
<P>
"I have decided to resign for the supremacy of the judiciary
and the constitution of the country," Leghari said, adding an
official announcement of his resignation will be released soon.
</P>
<P>
The nerve-wracking tussle between Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif
and Chief Justice Sajjad reached its climax today when Sajjad
suspended this morning the 13th amendment to the constitution
passed by the two houses of Parliament in April, which clipped the
presidential power to dismiss an elected government.
</P>
<P>
However, minutes after Sajjad's order, a rival 10-member bench
of the Supreme Court declared his order invalid because he has
been under suspension.
</P>
<P>
Leghari's resignation also came hours after his meeting with
the powerful Chief of the Army Staff Jahangir Karamat, who has
been acting as the mediator in the four-month-old confrontation
between the government and the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after the Supreme Court issued the conflicting
orders today, Karamat also met with Prime Minister Sharif earlier
in the day.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
