<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Committed to Limiting Nuclear Proliferation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The European Union today
pledged its commitment to the prevention of nuclear weapons
proliferation during a meeting in Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation union started negotiations with the International
Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) on three additional nuclear safeguard
protocols.
</P>
<P>
The protocols include one for the 13 non-nuclear weapon EU
member states, one for France and one for Britain. The latter two
are nuclear-weapon member states.
</P>
<P>
The protocols are designed to improve the international nuclear
non-proliferation regime and to increase security worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The initiative of the European Union is unique in that it
constitutes the negotiation of protocols both for nuclear weapon
and non-nuclear weapon states.
</P>
<P>
It will also provide a basic and important reference for the
continuation of peaceful nuclear cooperation activities in the
union and elsewhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
European Commission Vice-President Sir Leon Brittan, EU
commissioners Christos Papoutsis and Hans van den Broek all
welcomed the negotiations as a further demonstration of the
union's will and commitment to the prevention of nuclear weapon
proliferation.
</P>
<P>
Papoutsis is in charge of the union's nuclear agency Euratom
Supply Agency, and van den Broek is responsible for external
relations.
</P>
<P>
Ensuring a strong non-proliferation regime is one of the
European Union's key common foreign and security policy
objectives. The union and its member states attach great
importance to the strengthening of IAEA safeguards.
</P>
<P>
Commissioner Papoutsis said: "The union will play a
considerable role in the implementation of several measures under
the new system.
</P>
<P>
"The dual assurance of the application of both Euratom and IAEA
safeguards in our member states is clear evidence that nuclear
energy is used in the union in a framework of impeccable
non-proliferation credentials," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
