<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Official Welcomes Endorsement in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Financial Secretary Donald
Tsang welcomed today the endorsement by the meeting of the finance
ministers held in Kuala Lumpur to develop a market-based approach
to address the intermediation problem in the region, reports
reaching here from Kuala Lumpur said.
</P>
<P>
At the conclusion of the meeting of the Association of
Southeast Asia Nations Plus Six (Australia, China, China's Hong
Kong, Japan, South Korea and the Unites States) today, the finance
ministers agreed that "there is an urgent need to develop a deep,
liquid and mature debt market in Asia to address the
intermediation problem. Ministers strongly endorsed the
initiative to develop a market-based approach to mobilize private
sector resources."
</P>
<P>
"While the authorities in the region are preoccupied with fire
fighting, we should not lose sight of the need for fire
prevention. Developing a market-based approach to address
intermediation problem is the right way forward," said Tsang.
</P>
<P>
"I felt encouraged by the warm support I got this morning from
other finance ministers on Hong Kong's suggested approach," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong will host the first meeting of technical experts to
explore these ideas with the assistance of international financial
institutions such as the World Bank and the Asian Development
Bank.
</P>
<P>
Tsang also shared the meeting consensus on the need to
strengthen domestic financial systems and to foster closer
collaborative efforts on financial regulation and supervision.
</P>
<P>
"We are all for more vigilant monitoring of domestic banking
systems. The Hong Kong experience has shown the value of sound
prudential standards in helping to withstand external shocks to
the banking system," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on, Tsang welcomed the undertaking by the International
Monetary Fund to examine how "below the line" hedging activities
of domestic activities should be monitored.  
</P>
</TEXT>
