<HEADLINE> Leghari's Resignation Boosts Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The news of President Farooq
Leghari's resignation triggered heavy buying of blue chips on the
stock market in Karachi, Pakistan's biggest city, dealers said
today.
</P>
<P>
The 100-Index of Karachi Stock Exchange (KSE) closed up 2.04
points to 1789.22 in official trading amid rumors.
</P>
<P>
However, after the final reports of the president's
resignation, trading continued in the kerb pushing the prices of
Hub Power and ICI up by at least Rs 2, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
During the official trading, prices of 55 scrips were in plus
column and 74 in minus as market capitalization soared by 541.6
billion rupees (about 13 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Trading volume surged to 63.9 million shares from 35.5 million
shares a day earlier showing signs of heavy activity.
</P>
<P>
An analyst at a leading brokerage house observed that the
latest developments on the political front in Islamabad have
infused new life into the stock market which had remained under
severe depression during the last three weeks.
</P>
<P>
He said that the signs of survival of an elected government
have revived the confidence of investors.
</P>
<P>
President Leghari announced his resignation here this evening
when the worst constitutional crisis involving Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif and Chief Justice Sajjad Ali Shah reached its climax
today.
</P>
<P>
Leghari, who assumed his office as president four years ago,
told a crowded news conference that he would step down for the
larger interests of the country and for the supremacy of the
country's constitution.  
</P>
</TEXT>
