<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cost, No Decisive Factor in Competitiveness: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 2 (Xinhua) -- It would be fatal if Hong
Kong tries to compete on cost, but Hong Kong can compete on other
areas where its competitiveness lies, a local official said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Some people are concerned that Hong Kong has become more and
more expensive, which casts doubt on how it could sustain economic
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
Responding to the argument, Deputy Secretary for Trade and
Industry of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region Tam
Wing-pong pointed out: "Hong Kong has always been expensive, at
lease since our economic development really started to take off."
</P>
<P>
"Unless we try to disrupt the market economy theory which we
hold on to so dearly, we cannot expect land price or labor cost in
Hong Kong to come down dramatically to match those in developing
economies," he told a seminar on Hong Kong's competitiveness,
organized by the American Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
"We would have died as early as the mid 1970s had we attempted
to do so," he added.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, "I have been told by my business friends that cost is
 seldom the sole decisive factor for any important business
decision," Tam noted.
</P>
<P>
He commented that Hong Kong can compete on other areas where
its competitiveness lies.
</P>
<P>
First, Hong Kong is sitting at the doorstep of a huge economy
with almost boundless opportunity, which gives the city a
unrivaled advantage to play as bridge for the two-way traffic
between China and the other parts of the world, Tam pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, Hong Kong has built up in past two decades strong
economic fundamentals so "we could weather whatever economic
turmoil well". "The resilience of our economy keeps us
competitive," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The recent financial crisis will serve as a good example in
that Hong Kong is always well prepared for the worst to happen and
to confront it head-on, he continued, and quoted Chief Executive
Tung Chee Hwa as saying that Hong Kong will be the first one to
bounce back when the crisis is over.
</P>
<P>
Tam also praised the top-caliber business people as another
strength Hong Kong owns.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is regarded as among the most competitive economies
in the world. Free market, infrastructure and business friendly
environment, free trade, rule of law and human resources are major
factors for Hong Kong's competitiveness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
