<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Reports 161 HIV-Positive Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Macao has reported a total of 161
HIV-positive cases, of which 11 have developed into full-blown
AIDS disease and seven died.
</P>
<P>
The Va Kio newspaper quoted Joao Claro, director of the Macao
Public Health Department, as saying that 118 of those who were
found HIV positive were women.
</P>
<P>
The number of HIV-positive cases dropped annually after 1993
when 40 cases were found. The number was 33 for 1994, 29 for 1995
and 21 for 1996.
</P>
<P>
Claro said that 113 people who tested HIV positive were Thai
nationals. Others were Portuguese and Vietnamese nationals.
</P>
<P>
Most of the cases were contracted through heterosexual means,
he said, adding that there were also 13 cases contracted through
homosexual means, and one case through blood transfusion. But he
did not reveal where the blood transfusion took place.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper report said that of those tested HIV positive, 99
were between the age of 20 and 29, and three were under the age of
19.
</P>
<P>
Macao started to track down people of HIV positive from
1986. The test targets female workers in entertainment companies
and massage parlors, blood donors, people ready for recruitment to
the guard forces, pregnant women and those voluntarily asking for
tests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
