<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Scholarships for HK Young People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hong Kong, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The British-funded Chevening
Scholarships will provide over 9 million HK dollars (about 1.16
million U.S. dollars) for about 50 Hong Kong leading graduates
and young professionals to pursue their higher studies in Britain
during the 1998/1999 period.
</P>
<P>
British Consul General Andrew Burns announced the call for
applicants for the third year of the Chevening scheme at a press
conference here today.
</P>
<P>
He said that 88 outstanding Hong Kong graduates have already
benefited from this scheme.
</P>
<P>
This demonstrates "our commitment to constructive and
professional links between Hong Kong and the UK", he said.
</P>
<P>
The Chevening Scholarships were launched in Hong Kong in
January 1996 following the success of the scheme in China's inland
 areas where some 400 scholarships have been awarded to date.
</P>
<P>
Administered by the British Council on behalf of the British
Consulate-General, Chevening Hong Kong is part of a worldwide
scheme funded by Britain's Foreign and Commonwealth Office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
