<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Sends Message to Gaddafi on Bilateral Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
has sent a letter to Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi, said French
Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Anne Gazeau-Secret today.
</P>
<P>
The letter was sent through Camille Cabana, the president of
the Institute of Arab World in Paris who recently visited Libya.
</P>
<P>
The spokeswoman did not give further details on the content of
the letter, but the Libyan media said that it was on bilateral
relations since the cooperation in oil exploration and production
between the two countries has resumed over the past several years.
</P>
<P>
Relations between France and Libya have remained deadlocked
since the 1989 explosion of a DC-10 passenger plane of the UTA air
company of France over Niger. France suspected that Libya was
involved in the bombing of the plane, in which all 170 people on
board were killed.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the French national employers' group CNPF said
on Monday that French enterprises intend to invest in Libya, which
has been under international sanctions since 1992 for its alleged
implication in the bombing of a Pan-Am Boeing passenger plane over
Lockerbie in 1989 and the UTA plane explosion.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, the trade volume between
France and Libya in the first eight months this year amounted to
228 million U.S. dollars, and in 1996 was 280 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Gaddafi said on September 24 that the relations between his
country and France are "excellent" and that Libya has been fully
cooperating with France in the investigation of the UTA bombing.
</P>
<P>
France sent to the United Nations Security Council on November
7 the report on the result of an investigation by the French judge
Jean-Louis Bruguiere in Libya on the UTA bombing.
</P>
<P>
France recognized that Libya responded to a great part of its
requests during the investigation, although the responses were not
satisfying "on all the points," said the foreign ministry
spokeswoman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Coal Mine Showing Profit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, December 2 (Xinhua) -- One of China's
better-known coal mines, the Kailuan Coal Mining Administration,
has been showing a profit for the past three years, and has been
setting a good example for state-owned enterprises nationwide.
</P>
<P>
The administration in Hebei province in northern China was
running in the red for eight years before 1994. However, the
situation began to change after it started allowing its 19
subsidiary mines to make their own business decisions in 1993, in
such areas as production, operation, materials purchase,
marketing, personnel and wages.
</P>
<P>
Another major change was the use of a flexible personnel
system. The administration has 127,000 workers, who are now
divided into three groups: coal production, other business, and
rear-echelon service, making the administration a more modern,
market-oriented enterprise to meet customer demand.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the mine has been using modern technology to
increase output, and profits of Tangshan Mine, one of Kailuan's
subsidiary, have increased 36 percent annually since 1992, when
more modern technology was introduced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
