<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angolan Peace Good for Regional Development: UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The realization of peace and
the ensuing political stability in Angola would benefit the
all-round development of the southern African region, a U.N.
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman of the U.N. observation group in Angola David
Wimhurst, who is ending his 18-month mission in the country, said
a resources-rich Angola will give a boost to the development of
southern Africa, once political stability there is realized.
</P>
<P>
Despite all the difficulties, peace process will get a
satisfactory result, he said, adding that the work must be done
to re-establish government institutions in the areas controlled
by the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA), and to disarm its army.
</P>
<P>
Also important is to turn UNITA's radio station into a
non-party commercial station and move UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi
into Luanda, as stipulated in the Lusaka Peace Protocol signed in
1994.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that the implementation of the peace agreement
would surely be accomplished by the end of January 1998 when the
U. N. Angola observation group is scheduled to finish its mission
in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
