<HEADLINE> US Agrees to Cooperate With Manila in Cleaning Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The United States has agreed to
cooperate with the Philippine government in removing toxic wastes
in its former military bases of Clark and Subic, the northern
Philippines, a senior Philippine official said today.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. expression of willingness to cooperate was in response
to an earlier Manila proposal for a joint task force to address
the recurring toxic waste issue once and for all, Foreign Affairs
Undersecretary Rodolfo Severino said.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was put forward by Philippine Foreign Affairs
Secretary Domingo Siazon to U.S. State Secretary Madeleine
Albright late last month when they met in Vancouver, Canada,
during the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) ministerial
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Severino said the U.S. response "is a big leap towards the
final resolution" of the toxic waste issue, which the U.S. had
denied since its withdrawal from the two bases in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The former U.S. Subic Naval Base and the former U.S. Clark Air
Base reverted to the Philippines in 1992 and were later converted
to special economic and industrial zones.
</P>
<P>
The presence of toxic waste contaminated sites in the two bases
has been confirmed by both Filipino and American environment
activists.
</P>
<P>
But Washington repeatedly denied the toxic waste issue and
refused to accept any obligation in dealing with such an issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
