<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Pragmatic Changes in Australia's Asia Policy (1)  by Jiang Guocheng </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The year 1997 has seen
Australia begin to abandon its image of following the steps of
some Western powers in dealing with other parts of the world,
particularly Asia, and encourage deeper US engagement with Asia
for the stability and prosperity of the region.
</P>
<P>
On the human rights issue, Australia has adopted a
down-to-earth approach and refused to join those Western countries
in using the issue as an excuse to defame some selected developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, Australia refused to cosponsor a resolution at
the United Nations Human Rights Commission in Geneva, put forward
by some European countries and supported by the US, which
unjustifiably criticized China's human rights record and
intentionally ignored rapid social and economic progress China has
made during the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
Instead, Australia undertook a dialogue with China on the human
rights issue in August on the basis of equality and mutual
respect, which Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer later
described as satisfactory and conducive to the relations between
Australia and China.
</P>
<P>
In the interest of its own and other parts of the world,
Australia has also devoted great efforts to persuading the US to
have better ties with Indonesia, Australia's largest neighbor and
the largest Muslin nation in the world, and gave up its
confrontation with the country over the human rights issue.
</P>
<P>
A rift between Indonesia and the US came to a head in June,
when Jakarta, angered by US congressional criticism of its human
rights situation, canceled plans to buy nine F-16 fighter aircraft
and pulled out of a US-sponsored military education program.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to the United States in late June, Australian
Prime Minister John Howard called on his host to drop its
confrontational attitude towards some Asian countries on the
human rights issue, saying its human rights concerns should be
addressed through dialogue in a broad relationship, not through
confrontation with Indonesia and China.
</P>
<P>
He said the US Administration's commitment to deeper engagement
with China and its disavowal of notions of containment and
confrontation were "central to the region's future stability."
</P>
<P>
The continued US engagement in Asia was not only crucial for
the region, but also in its own interest, as 40 percent of US
trade now occurs with East Asia, he added.
</P>
<P>
Australia went a step further. It had tried to influence US
thinking on Indonesia by sending a high-level team to Washington
for talks in mid-September to act behind the scenes to help mend
the rift.
</P>
<P>
Mending the rift was also high on the agenda of Australian
Foreign Minister Alexander Downer and Defense Minister Ian
McLachlan in October when they met with their US counterparts
during an annual Australian-US ministerial meeting in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Downer urged the US to improve its ties with Indonesia and said
there was strong support from Australia for a strong and effective
relationship between the United States and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
McLachlan attacked American congressional critics of
Indonesia's human rights record, saying some people in Congress
are always complaining about human rights. "We are of Asia. Our
economic well-being is as tightly bound with Asia as our defense
and security interests. Above all else this is our region. These
are our friends and neighbors," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Government Calls for Mine Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 2 (Xinhua) -- China's Labor Ministry and the
State Economic and Trade Commission has called for greater safety
measures in mines after a series of gas explosions have rocked the
industry, saying that serious attention should be given to this
matter.
</P>
<P>
This year there had been 12 serious incidents. In November
alone, there were four serious gas explosions. On the 4th, an
explosion at Yueliangtian Mine in Guizhou province killed 43
miners. On the 13th, an explosion at Pansan Mine in Anhui province
killed 89. On the 27th, explosions at Xie'er Mine in Anhui killed
45 and an explosion at Jiaoping Mine killed 28.
</P>
<P>
The main cause of the accidents was a lack of attention to
safety details, the ministry says, and lax management.
</P>
<P>
The incidents have had serious consequences for reforms,
development, and stability, and must be investigated and cadres
who were responsible for them must be dealt with in accordance
with state laws and regulations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Pragmatic Changes in Australia's Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Another example of Australia's pragmatic foreign policy change
is its decision to send Foreign Minister Alexander Downer to the
swearing-in ceremony of the Provisional Legislative Council of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) on July 1, 1997 in
support of China, as Downer's US and British counterparts chose
not to attend.
</P>
<P>
There is little doubt that Australia's policy change springs
from realist calculations of Asia's current and potential
significance to Australia, but it also reflects Australia's desire
to show the seriousness of its eagerness to integrate with Asia.
</P>
<P>
With about 60 percent of its goods and services export going to
Asia, Australian economic growth, job creation and the standard
of living for average Australians are closely linked with Asia's
sustained stability and economic growth.
</P>
<P>
It is only natural for Australia to move closer to Asia, even
sometimes it means to distance itself to some extent from its
traditional allies.
</P>
<P>
"The days are long gone when an Australian prime minister
waited for London or Washington to decide what he did," the prime
minister declared in June when he announced the decision on
Downer's representation at the HKSAR Provisional Legislative
Council swearing-in ceremony.
</P>
<P>
It is no surprise that the Australian government has also taken
practical actions over the past several months to help Asia
overcome the financial crisis which hit Thailand, Indonesia and
some other Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Australia has already agreed to provide one billion US dollars
towards an international bailout of Thailand negotiated by the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) and could be called on for
another one billion US dollars to top up a loan package for
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Australia's participation in the IMF rescue
package on  November 28, Downer said, "We are right in there
helping, thereby proving for the first time in many years that we
are no fair-weather friend. In fact, proving we are a partner and
a neighbor for the long haul."
</P>
<P>
It is worth noting that Australia's effort for deeper
engagement with Asia is driven primarily by economic factors, and
was made after it strengthened its political and military ties
with the United States and Japan since the Howard government came
to power last year.
</P>
<P>
As Australia's white paper on foreign relations put it,
"Australia's alliance with the United States is an asset both
redefined and strengthened by the end of Cold War."
</P>
<P>
The document, which was released in August, went on to say that
"the success of key Australian security and economic objectives is
greatly influenced by the economic strength and political
influence of the United States."
</P>
<P>
Therefore, how far the Howard government will go in following
its pragmatic Asia policy remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
Australia's policy change in the first half of this year
prompted US Ambassador to Australia Genta Holmes in June to call
on Australia and the United States to work together to minimize
the "differences and tensions which will emerge."
</P>
<P>
But with Sino-US relationship back to normal and improving, it
is less likely that there would be such a difficult position in
which Australia has to choose between Asia countries and the
United States. Chances are high that Australia's current pragmatic
Asia policy will go on in the near future.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian President Reshuffles Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(Rong Shoujun, Wang Nengbiao)
</P>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- President Frederick Chiluba
reshuffled his cabinet here today, demoting his vice president
and defense minister, the first since his re-election last year
in a bid to heighten efficiency and avoid corruption.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference held in the State House, Chiluba declared
that Vice President Godfrey Miyanda becomes the Minister of
Education and he was replaced by former Mines Minister Christon
Tembo.
</P>
<P>
The other reshuffle arrangements are as follows: Home Affairs
Minister Chitalu Sampa becomes Defense Minister while former
Labor Minister Peter Machongwa has been moved to the Home Affairs
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Former Minister of Works and Supply Keli Walubita becomes
Foreign Affairs Minister while professor Lawrence Shimba, the
incumbent there, goes to the Ministry of Science, Technology and
Vocational Training.
</P>
<P>
Enock Kavindele who has been at the ministry has been
transferred to Commerce, Trade and Industry to fill the vacancy
left by Alfeyo Hambayi who goes to the Ministry of Environment
and Natural Resources.
</P>
<P>
Former Education Minister Syamukayumbu Syamujaye becomes the
Minister of Mines.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba has also replaced the army commander Nobby Shimbeye
with major general Mumbi While Zambia Air Force Commander Ronald
Shikapwasha, who would retire, has been replaced by S. Kayunbei.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said that the reshuffle is designed to "reinforce and
rejuvenate the cabinet", and replace the "unaccountable and
unqualified" persons.
</P>
<P>
"From time to time, I need to look at the government and see
how it operates, to see some people maybe have stayed too long to
be accountable, too long to feel that they are appointed," said
the president.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba described the shake-up of the government as
"necessary" for better governance.
</P>
<P>
This cabinet major shake-up took place after some army
officers staged a coup on October 28, but the coup was smashed by
government forces just five hours later.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba declared a 7-day state of emergency the next day, and
parliament extended it by three months early in November.
</P>
<P>
Over 80 people have been detained under emergency laws since
the abortive coup attempt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
