<HEADLINE> Vietnamese Government Takes Care of Blind People: Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnamese government has
always attached great importance to helping blind people in the
country, senior Vietnamese officials told a regional meeting on
the blind which ended here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the two-day regional meeting of the World Blind Union
(WBU), Labor, War Invalids and Social Affairs Minister Tran Dinh
Hoan said "Vietnam Blind Association (VBA) will get more
experience in expanding the association's activities, taking care
of the blind, and helping to rehabilitate them and improving their
education."
</P>
<P>
In a separate address to the meeting, VBA Chairman Dinh Thuyen
said that during the past five years, the VBA, with help from the
government, has granted 25.5 billion Vietnamese dong (about two
million U.S. dollars) worth of loans to help more than 26,000 blind
people set up and develop businesses.
</P>
<P>
The association has also decided to start an illiteracy
eradication program for the blind to enable them to integrate more
easily into the community.
</P>
<P>
The official also said that international organizations have
assisted nearly one million Vietnamese blind people with
rehabilitation, job creation and improvement of their cultural
lives.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from the organization's eight members in the
Pacific and the east Asian region attended the meeting, which
aimed to help blind people to exchange and draw experience from
the regional blind associations' activities.
</P>
<P>
The VBA has established bilateral relations with 26 national
blind unions throughout the world since it joined the WBU in 1987.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
