<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Stresses Environment Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Vice-President
Omar Ali Juma has pointed out that environmental protection will
continue to be an important part in the government's social and
economic programs.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a conference on "Biodiversity of the Eastern Arc
Mountains" which opened Monday, the vice-president appealed to
the international community to support Tanzania in its efforts to
curb environmental pollution and degradation.
</P>
<P>
Juma said his office has already prepared a draft of the
national environmental policy, which would ensure sustainable and
rational use of resources to meet the basic needs of the present
generations, according to today's Daily News.
</P>
<P>
Juma commended the Tanzania Forestry Research Institute
(Tafori) for its achievements in the conservation of Tanzania's
biodiversity and called on the international community to lend
more support in capacity building.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony, Finnish Ambassador to
Tanzania, Ilari Rantakari, said that his country will support
Tanzania in conserving natural resources, including the Eastern
Arc Mountains.
</P>
<P>
He said mountains are important as water sources of various
rivers, like Ruvu, Pangani, Kihansi, Wami, Ruaha and Rufiji.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president stressed the importance of community
participation in environmental management and conservation
programs.
</P>
<P>
Juma said that environmental degradation in Tanzania is
closely tied to poverty, because much wood has been used for fuel
and construction. Under such circumstances, he noted, environment
campaigns must raise people's awareness of choosing alternative
energy sources and building materials.
</P>
<P>
The conference is jointly sponsored by Tafori, the University
of Dar es Salaam and the Sokine University of Agriculture.
</P>
</TEXT>
