<HEADLINE> ADB Helps Nepal in Rural Electrification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
(ADB) has approved a technical assistance of 450,000 U.S. dollars
to Nepal for improving the country's rural electrification, said a
news release issued today by the bank.
</P>
<P>
The technical assistance will assist Nepal's National
Electricity Authority (NEA) in identifying potential rural
electrification schemes and preparing preliminary designs of these
schemes for future implementation, the news release said.
</P>
<P>
Nepal has a very low national electrification ratio of only 14
percent, and most of the people with electricity service live in
urban areas. Only four percent of the rural population have access
to power, the news release noted.
</P>
<P>
The total generating capacity of the NEA will double over the
next five years with the planned commissioning of the ADB-financed
Kali Gandaki "A" Hydroelectric Project of 144 megawatts in 2000
and several other smaller hydropower projects, said the news
release.
</P>
<P>
The ADB is a member of the Nepal Aid Group.  
</P>
</TEXT>
