<HEADLINE> Britain Contributes a Million Pounds for Holocaust Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Britain today announced the
establishment of a special fund to compensate survivors of the
holocaust that occurred during World War II; they also contributed
one million pounds to the fund.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made by British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook at an international conference that opened here today. The
conference will discuss the fate of millions of U.S. dollars in
gold seized by Nazis from European countries invaded during World
War II and the Jewish people.
</P>
<P>
"Britain is not a recipient of any of the Tripartite Commission
gold. But I still believe it is right that Britain should
contribute to the fund. So I am pleased to announce that Britain
will be contributing one million pounds (about 1.7 million
U.S. dollars)," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Secretary also urged all the participants to help
"ensure that the unbearable tragedy of living through the
Holocaust is not compounded by an old age marked by the fear and
sadness of poverty."
</P>
<P>
"We must let them know that the international community is not
indifferent to their plight," he added.
</P>
<P>
The three-day conference will attempt to discover where the
gold came from, what happened to it and what steps may be taken to
compensate victims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
