<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 65,000 Tanzanian Kids Get HIV Every Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 2 (Xinhua) -- At least 65,000
Tanzanian children are infected every year with HIV which causes
AIDS, local newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a public rally in Dar es Salaam to mark the world
AIDS day Monday, Tanzanian Premier F. Sumaye said the children
are infected by their mothers especially during delivery and
through breast feeding.
</P>
<P>
To date, Tanzania alone has about 300,000 orphans who have
lost their parents because of AIDS, the Prime Minister said in a
speech, read by Minister for Finance Daniel Yona.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, 1,000,000 children are estimated to
have been infected with HIV in the world, Sumaye said.
</P>
<P>
He said about 90 percent of HIV carriers are found in the
developing countries and 70 percent of people with HIV carriers
are in the sub-Sahara Africa.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, at least nine million children in the
world will have lost their mothers because of AIDS, he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the rally, the Minister for Health Dr Aaron Chiduo
said the Tanzanian government will launch another five-year AIDS
control program next year, with emphasis on raising public
awareness of the deadly disease.
</P>
<P>
He said the program would be implemented from district to
village level, in an effort to reach the grass-roots people.
</P>
<P>
A total of 18,000 teachers from about 11,000 primary schools
in Tanzania have received training on HIV/AIDS sponsored by the
United Nations Children Fund, said Agnes Aidoo, the
organization's representative in Tanzania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
