<HEADLINE> Philippine Congress Urged to Pass Tax Reform Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
today urged Congress to finally pass the Comprehensive Tax Reform
Package (CTRP) and a new oil deregulation law to strengthen
investors' confidence in the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting of the Legislative-Executive Development
Advisory Council, Ramos said the quick passage of the two bills
will assure local and foreign investors that the government is
consistent in its economic policies and reform program.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said foreign investors still regard the Philippines as a
"good investment destination" in Asia despite the regional
currency turmoil.
</P>
<P>
But they also raised concern over the protracted passage of the
two important bills, he added.
</P>
<P>
These foreign investors who are searching for a good investment
destination can be drawn into the Philippines by putting in place
a stable policy environment, Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
The CTRP bill, which is designed to improve the government's
fiscal position by boosting its tax revenues, has been blocked in
the Congressional Bicameral Conference Committee due to
differences over the level of income tax relief.
</P>
<P>
The old oil deregulation law, which took effect in February
this year, was nullified by the Supreme Court last month which
declared the oil industry liberalization law unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, the government withdrew its huge subsidy to the
oil industry, and the country's three major oil companies were
allowed to adjust oil prices freely. 
</P>
</TEXT>
