<HEADLINE> China Expects Good Harvest This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Grain output in China for 1997 is
expected to be the same as last year, according to the Agriculture
Ministry, which announced at a national agriculture conference
which opened here today.
</P>
<P>
It added that there will be record high grain reserves as well,
and a balance between supply and demand.
</P>
<P>
It said that there will be more cotton this year, but output of
oil-bearing crops will drop a bit. Sugar output will increase a
little, and meat, eggs, milk, aquatic products, and vegetables
will increase sharply.
</P>
<P>
Added value of rural enterprises will be up 18 percent
from last year. And farmers' incomes will grow by 4 percent, when
adjusted for inflation.
</P>
<P>
Premier Li Peng has said that the good harvest will contribute
to healthy economic development and a sound environment. He says
that basic rural policies should be stablized next year, and rural
reforms increased, and is urging the use of science and education
in developing agriculture for better rural businesses, improved
production, and better lives for farmers.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that agricultural added value should increase by 4
percent in 1998, and grain output stay at this year's level, while
farmers' incomes should increase by more than 5 percent. To do
this, the country should maintain the size of planted areas,
improve quality and quantity, and explore new ways for farmers to
make more profit.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the conference, Vice-premier Jiang Chunyun said that
the current severe drought is threatening the summer harvest and
reaching next year's goals will be a tough job.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
