<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria to Adopt 12-Year Compulsory Education System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- In an effort to meet the
requirements on joining the European Union (EU), Bulgaria will
adopt a 12-year compulsory education system in place of the
current 11-year system.
</P>
<P>
This change is provided for by an education law amendment
passed by the government Monday, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The amendment, to take effect in 1998, also stipulates that a
child must be seven years of age to enter the first grade and a
6-year-old child also can attend primary school with the consent
of the parents.
</P>
<P>
Those who fail to send their children under the age of 16 to
school would be fined 100,000 Leva (240 U.S. dollars), according
to the amendment.
</P>
<P>
Under the country's present secondary education system, all
Bulgarian middle schools adopt the 11-year education system except
the 12-year language and polytechnical schools. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
