<HEADLINE> Dhaka Allows Limited Self-rule by Tribal People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government today
signed a historic peace treaty allowing limited self-rule by the
tribal people in Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT), in a bid to end the
25-year-long insurgency in this country's southeastern parts.
</P>
<P>
The treaty came on the seventh day of the seventh-round talks,
initiated by the present government early this year with
Parbattaya Chattagram Jana Sanghati Samity (PCJSS), the political
wing of the pro-independence armed rebels.
</P>
<P>
A beaming Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina witnessed the historic
moment as Chairman of the National Committee Chief Whip Abul
Hasanat Abdullah and PCJSS Chief Santu Larma signed the accord
this morning.
</P>
<P>
She sought the cooperation of all, including the opposition
parties, for implementing the treaty, saying while in power, the
opposition too had held 13 rounds of talks with the PCJSS to
restore peace in the hills.
</P>
<P>
Larma said, "We are going to establish a new life." The people
in the hill region would live in peace, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's Foreign Minister Abdus Samad Azad and Chief of
Army Staff Lt. Gen. Muhammad Mahbubur Rahman hailed the signing of
the peace accord and urged everybody in the country to back the
document.
</P>
<P>
The preamble of the accord said that the government and the
PCJSS reached the agreement "within the constitutional framework
keeping full and firm allegiance to Bangladesh's territorial
integrity and sovereignty".
</P>
<P>
"Both sides have recognized the necessity to preserve the
characteristics and develop the region considering the CHT as a
tribal inhabited area," the peace accord said.
</P>
<P>
Under the 15-page agreement, a 22-member Chittagong Hill Tracts
Regional Council (CHTRC) will be created, which will be elected by
the members of the three hill district councils for a term of five
years.
</P>
<P>
The CHTRC will be headed by a tribal person with the status of
a state minister and its Chief Executive will be a public servant,
preferably a tribesman, who will be a joint secretary of the
government.
</P>
<P>
One-third of the council will be from non-tribals and three
seats will be reserved for women, the accord said.
</P>
<P>
The CHTRC would oversee employment, in which the tribals would
be given priority, as well as local development, education, health
and revenue.
</P>
<P>
The CHTRC will coordinate the general administration, law and
order and development activities in the three hill districts and
deal with the tribal laws and social justice.
</P>
<P>
The three hill district councils would be elected for a term of
five years and two-thirds of their members would be tribals. A
tribal chairman would head each of the three district councils,
which will control local affairs.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, temporary camps of the army and
other security forces in the hill tracts will be closed down, but
three cantonments and three border forces garrisons would remain.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
