<HEADLINE> Southwest China Opens Outlet To Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, December 2 (Xinhua) -- A 898.7-km railway from
Kunming, the capital of Yunnan Province to Nanning, the capital
of the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, officially opened to
traffic today, providing a sea outlet in remote parts of
southwestern China.
</P>
<P>
The railway is expected to promote industrial, agricultural,
and service trade development along its length and to help 15
million poverty-stricken people, a fifth of China's poor.
</P>
<P>
It is also a principal part of the Central Government's policy
of May, 1992 for a land, air, and water transport network in
southwestern China. The 1.5 million-sq.km. area it covers has a
population of 200 million in Yunnan, Sichuan, Guizhou, Hunan, and
Guangdong provinces, and Guangxi.
</P>
<P>
It has half of China's hydropower resources and a large part of
its reserves of 11 types of minerals. Guizhou has 12.1 billion
tons of high-quality coal reserves, and annual coal output will go
from 8 million tons now to 20 million tons by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The network is expected to increase the phosphate ore and
non-ferrous metal transport in Yunnan from 10 million tons to
15 to 20 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Premier Zou Jiahua says that the network will get the
east coast to help the western interior and reduce supply
shortages of raw materials and help restructure industry.
</P>
<P>
The network's Chengdu-Chongqing, Chengdu-Kunming, and
Guizhou-Kunming railway lines have already been completed, and a
highway linking the cities of Chengdu, Chongqing, Guiyang, Nanning
and Zhanjiang cities is being built.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi has spent two billion yuan on a project that will allow
1,000-dwt ships on the 845-km water course between Nanning and
Guangzhou, the capital of Guangdong Province in the south. Four
port cities on the Beibu Gulf are also expanding cargo handling
capacities.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan, Guizhou and Guangxi have built a dozen new airports or
are expanding existing ones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
