<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Discloses Second Case of New Flu Virus Strain in Humans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- A second case of human infection
with influenza strain A (H5N1), known to infect only birds before,
has been found by China's Government Virus Unit (GVU) in the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region, the World Health Organization
(WHO) announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Confirmation of the laboratory specimen is now being sought
from the WHO Collaborating Center on influenza at the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) in Atlanta, USA, said WHO.
Results are expected to be available within the next week.
</P>
<P>
The second suspected case of influenza A (H5N1) involved a
two-year-old boy who developed fever in early November and was
then admitted to hospital. A nasopharyngeal aspirate taken during
his stay in hospital was positive for influenza A (H5N1). The boy
recovered quickly and was discharged.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary investigations, however, have not indicated that
the second case is related to the first one, confirmed in August
1997, the WHO added.
</P>
<P>
The first incidence of influenza A (H5N1), which beforehand had
only been known to infect birds, was in a three-year-old boy who
died in Hong Kong in May 1997 of Reye Syndrome during an acute
respiratory illness.
</P>
<P>
The Reye Syndrome, involving the central nervous system and the
liver, is a rare complication in children who may have ingested
salicylates (e.g. Aspirin). It occurs mainly in children with
influenza type B and less frequently in children with influenza
type A or chickenpox.
</P>
<P>
"There is no evidence that the infection has spread widely in
the community or that there has been human to human transmission,"
emphasized Dr. Daniel Lavanchy of the WHO Division of Emerging and
other Communicable Diseases Surveillance and Control.
</P>
<P>
"The WHO will maintain its surveillance and monitoring
activities, and assistance to national health authorities, to
ensure that, should additional cases occur, they will be rapidly
investigated," he said.
</P>
<P>
Since the first incidence of human infection in May 1997, the
Chinese Ministry of Public Health has increased influenza
surveillance measures. In the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region, possible sources of exposure to the virus are being traced
and the Chinese Ministry of Public Health is liaising closely with
the WHO and WHO Collaborating Centers in Atlanta, London of the
United Kingdom, Melbourne of Australia, and Tokyo of Japan,
according to the WHO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
