<HEADLINE> China Gets New Ruling On Assets Valuation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Starting next year, China will
restrict the determining of assets valuation reports to certified
public valuers, the Chinese Assets Valuation Association said
today.
</P>
<P>
It added that certified public valuers will be held legally
responsible for reports they sign.
</P>
<P>
An official of the State Administration of State Property said
that, as China develops its market economy and the assets
restructuring process continues, ensuring the correctness of
assets valuation has become essential. The new system will
considerably improve the overall quality of assets valuation in
China, he said.
</P>
<P>
China has developed two qualification tests for certified
public valuers since 1995, and now has 4,960 licensed certified
public valuers. That number is expected to reach 10,000 by the end
of this year.
</P>
<P>
Official sources say that China has formulated 58 laws and rules
on assets valuation since 1989.  
</P>
</TEXT>
