<HEADLINE> Macao Foreign Trade Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Macao's imports and exports
increased in the first nine months of this year, resulting in a
trade surplus of 275 million patacas (about 34.81 million
U.S. dollars) compared with a deficit of 363 million patacas
(about 45.95 million dollars) in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Latest figures released by the Macao Census and Statistics
Department show that the value of export goods between January
and September was 12.709 billion patacas (about 1.61 billion
dollars), up 11.4 percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Imports during that period reached 12.434 billion patacas
(about 1.57 billion dollars), up 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
As a result, a trade surplus of 275 million patacas was
recorded. It was the first surplus in more than two years.
</P>
<P>
Of the exports, 85 percent were textiles and garments,
whose exports saw an increase of 19.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Exports of most non-textile goods, including machinery and
equipment, footwear and cement, dropped.
</P>
<P>
More than 77 percent of the exported goods went to the United
States and the European Union (EU). The export value to the U.S.
rose by 23.1 percent and that to the EU 14.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the increase of imports was due to more purchases of
capital goods (up 15.8 percent), raw materials and semi-finished
goods (up 6.9 percent), fuel and lubricant oil (up 8 percent) and
consumer goods (up 0.1 percent).
</P>
<P>
The main import market of Macao was in the Asia-Pacific
region. While imports from Japan and China's inland and Taiwan all
 increased, those from the Republic of Korea, Hong Kong and
Australia declined.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
