<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 12:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Civil Delegation Calls for Lifting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 2 (Xinhua) -- A United States civil delegation
that just visited Iraq has called for an end to the seven-year-old
sanctions on Iraq to ease its people's suffering.
</P>
<P>
"The most dangerous mass destruction weapon you can use today
is economic weapon and many children (in Iraq) are dying from this
weapon rather than from atomic bombs," said Bert Sacks, head of
the delegation, at a press conference here today.
</P>
<P>
The delegation arrived here Sunday after an eight-day visit to
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"We want a complete ban of use of economic weapon if it takes
lives," said Sacks, who together with three other delegation
members are from the Chicago-based Voices in the Wilderness.
</P>
<P>
Delegation members said the sanctions imposed by the U.N. after
Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait now deprived the Iraqi people of a
constant and sufficient supply of medicine and food.
</P>
<P>
The delegation spelled out food allotments by the Iraqi
government for its people. Each person can only get 2.25 kilograms
of flour, 625 grams of rice, 31 grams of salt, 680 grams of baby
milk plus a little bit of tea and edible oil every month.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, major fruits and vegetables like orange, eggplant
and cucumber as well as cheese were completely out of reach for
the Iraqis, said delegation member Joe Eito.
</P>
<P>
Children were the major victims of short supply of humanitarian
goods and "a million children (in Iraq) are malnourished," said
Sacks at a press conference held before the U.N. Development
Programs (UNDP) building here. "What possible justice are there?"
he asked.
</P>
<P>
Delegation members showed a number of photos featuring
malnourished or sick Iraqi children.
</P>
<P>
Delegation member Randall Mullins told Xinhua that there was a
very limited medicine supply in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In light of such a situation, the delegation took 220 kilograms
of medicine to Baghdad which included Aspirin, Ultracillin,
Pectolyn Pediatric, Colfed Expectorant and Brufen Pediatric
Syrup, said Mullins, adding these medicines were not available for
the Iraqis under the oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
Delegation member Dan Handelman showed a bottle of murky water
taken from the Basra Hospital, five hours' drive form
Baghdad. Doctors there said that the water was for patients'
drinking but in fact it was totally undrinkable, Handelman said.
</P>
<P>
Sacks said the electricity and sewage systems destructed during
bombing in the Gulf War were beyond restoration. There was a
six-hour-long power cut every day due to the limited capacity of
electric generation, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said his delegation would leave for Amsterdam this evening
for another press conference on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The crippling sanctions can only be lifted only when the
U.N. verifies that all mass destruction and biological weapons in
Iraq are destroyed. A U.N. inspection team is now working in
Baghdad for this purpose. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
