<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Status as International Financial Center Unchanged: Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's status as an
international financial center has been well preserved after the
handover, with limitless potential in the longer term on the basis
of China's sustainable economic growth, experts told an
international seminar here today.
</P>
<P>
While many other regional markets have stumbled as a result of
the recent currency and stock turmoil, Hong Kong's market systems
and regulatory structure have served it well, they said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Second Conference on International Financial
Centers, Prof. Y. C. Jao from the University of Hong Kong said
that both the Central Government of China and the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (SAR) government value the city's
role as an international financial center, which is explicitly
affirmed in the Sino-British Joint Declaration and the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
In addition to being ranked among the top three international
financial centers in the Asia-Pacific Region and the top nine in
the world, Hong Kong's role as an international financial center
has become more varied and multi-faceted around the handover, said
the academic.
</P>
<P>
The restructuring of state-owned enterprises on China's
mainland, which was high on the agenda of the 15th Congress of the
Communist Party of China, has highly positive implications for
Hong Kong's status as an international financial center, since
Hong Kong is the premier fund-raising center for these
enterprises, he added.
</P>
<P>
Another speaker at the conference, Jon Anda from Morgan Stanley
Asia, examined Hong Kong's position as a financial center against
the backdrop of the recent Asian financial crisis, which exerted a
contagious effect on Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
He listed Hong Kong's competitive edge as a financial center as
the following: the strategic position as a service center for
China, an open market with free flow of information, the excellent
infrastructure, a sound banking system and the stable currency
outlook.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's competitive edge, he added, is supported by a
strong market and regulatory framework, which served it well in
the regional financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Trading, execution and settlement systems at both exchanges and
clearing houses have withstood the test of high volumes and
extreme volatility, he said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's regulators have also withstood the public pressure,
that arises in any market crisis, to take interventionist
measures, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"In the wake of any market crisis, investors return to
fundamentals," the investment banker noted.
</P>
<P>
"Although there are many challenges ahead, the current
environment represents a tremendous opportunity for Hong Kong to
consolidate and build upon its position as a regional and
international financial center," he said.
</P>
<P>
The conference was sponsored by the International Financial
Centers Association, the World Bank and the International Monetary
Fund. The first such meeting was held in Shanghai, China, in
1994.  
</P>
</TEXT>
