<HEADLINE> 8 Killed by Tamil Rebels in Northern Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Seven government soldiers and
one civilian were killed and five other soldiers injured when
rebels of Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) attacked them in
Sri Lanka's Northern province today, military spokesman said here
this evening.
</P>
<P>
The Tamil rebels ambushed an army bus traveling from Murunkan
army camp to Murunkan town at around 8:15 this morning.
</P>
<P>
Government troops retaliated with small arms right away,
causing the rebels to withdraw with their dead and wounded, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Seven soldiers and the civilian driver of the bus were killed
and five other soldiers were injured in the cross fire.
</P>
<P>
A search and clear operation is in progress in the area, he
added.
</P>
<P>
In another incident in Amparai district, Eastern province
today, 25 civilians and a policeman were injured when LTTE rebels
threw a hand grenade to their bus.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels have been fighting a war for a separate Tamil
state in the north and east of the island country since 1983.
</P>
</TEXT>
