<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Financial Centers Conference Opens In HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Second Conference on
International Financial Centers opened here today, bringing
together financial specialists and policy markers from all over
the world to explore issues related to Asian markets today and
next century.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the conference is reform, transition and
consolidation of Asian financial centers to meet competition and
challenges in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
"Along with the rapid growth of Asian economies, especially
over the recent years, we have witnessed both the achievement of
continued successes and the emergence of new challenges," said
Zhang Shengman, vice president of the World Bank, in his opening
speech at today's conference.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that on the one hand, emerging Asia capital
markets continued its trend toward robust growth, and on the other
hand, some Asian economies are making painful adjustments to cope
with the recent currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
The financial jitters first occurred in Thailand in July, then
spread to other parts of Southeast Asia, and in mid-October swept
the North East Asia countries like Japan and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund (IMF) has thrown life ropes to
Thailand, Indonesia and South Korea to help bail out their
battered economies with multi-billion-US dollar rescue programs.
</P>
<P>
"While local in their origin, these issues have attracted the
close attention of both specialists and policy-makers throughout
the world," said the World Bank official, who believed that "the
conference can hardly be more timely and useful."
</P>
<P>
Participants in the two-day conference are expected to discuss
such topics as capital flows and financial integration in the
globe, reform of China's financial system, Hong Kong's role as an
international financial center and the Asia currency turmoil.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank president James D Wolfensohn and the IMF
Managing Director Michel Camdessus both wrote letters to wish the
conference a success.
</P>
<P>
Sponsored by the International Financial Center Association,
the World Bank and the IMF, the first such conference was held in
Shanghai, China, three and half years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
