<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Free Capital Flow Should Go On: IMF Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 2 (Xinhua) -- An International Monetary
Fund (IMF) official said here today that promoting free flows of
capital still makes sense despite the Asian currency crisis that
put some economies into a downward spiral.
</P>
<P>
"Notwithstanding the recent financial turmoil, the shared
belief of our members remains that the capital account
liberalization should be promoted," said Shailendra J. Anjaria,
director of External Relations of the IMF when addressing the
Second International Financial Centers Conference that opened here
today.
</P>
<P>
The regional financial crisis that first began in Thailand in
July where substantial macroeconomic imbalances occurred, then
spilled over into Southeast Asia, and most recently spread to
Northeast Asia economies like South Korea and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Among many other reasons, the huge and rapid outflow of capital
is blamed for causing the financial turbulence in this part of
the world.
</P>
<P>
The IMF official disagreed and told the participants of the
conference: "Movements in international capital are more often a
symptom, rather than a root cause, of financial turmoil."
</P>
<P>
He cited Hong Kong and Singapore to say that the economies with
the most open capital accounts were not where the crisis
originated, instead, they are the economies that have so far
seemed most able to withstood the regional instability when it has
reached their shores.
</P>
<P>
Anjaria analyzed the benefits and risks of capital account
liberalization, which channels resources more efficiently to their
most productive uses and at the same time poses challenges to
policy makers and embryonic banking systems.
</P>
<P>
Benefits outweigh costs, he remarked. "Capital markets are
generally the messenger, but not usually the bad news," said
Anjaria. "We should not shoot the messenger just so as to overlook
the bad news."
</P>
<P>
The official acknowledged that the recent crisis reminded
people of the risks, to which no country is immune. "In the long
run however no country can afford to cut itself off from the
international capital markets," he said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the liberalization should be introduced in
an orderly manner, backed both by adequate national policies and
by a solid multilateral system for surveillance and financial
support.
</P>
<P>
Summing up the lessons from the Asia currency turmoil, he
suggested that a country should have swift reaction to warning
signals by taking timely action, enhance transparency of economic
policies and data, and establish a sound banking system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
