<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's Customs Warn of Home-brewed Wines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Customs warned
local drinkers to stay away from untaxed, home-made alcohol after
its officers raided a shop selling bottled wines and wine-making
equipment here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
During their raid of a "cellar" in Yau Ma Tei, Kowloon,
officers found it had been selling for several months
"do-it-yourself" brewing kits and its own wine, made on the
premises and Canadian-made kits which included ingredients,
equipment and instructions.
</P>
<P>
It is the first ever case of home-brewed wines being seized in
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,200 liters of dutiable bottle wine, 200 liters of
fermenting materials and several pieces of equipment, including
blenders, filters and glass vats, were seized during the raid.
</P>
<P>
The head of the Customs and Excise Department's Prosecution,
Intelligence and Investigation Bureau, Senior Superintendent
Gregory Wong Pui-sham, said the raid came after a report last
month on the shop by local English-language newspaper South China
Morning Post.
</P>
<P>
"It is illegal to make wine or any alcohol without license,
regardless of whether it is for your own consumption or to sell,"
Wong was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Customers of the shop had the choice of making the wine at home
or leaving their brew at the shop to be looked after by staff
during a 28-day fermentation period, according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The five persons arrested during the raid and released later on
bail, face a maximum of one million HK dollars (0.12 million U.S.
dollars) in fines and two years' imprisonment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
