<HEADLINE> Pak PM, Army Chief Discuss Political Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif held a meeting here today with Chief of the Army
Staff General Jahangir Karamat and discussed with him the
political crisis in the country, official sources said.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the meeting lasted for about one hour,
but details of the meeting were not available immediately.
</P>
<P>
The meeting took place soon after a three-member bench of the
Supreme Court headed by Chief Justice Sajjad Ali Shah suspended
the 13th Constitutional Amendment, restoring the power of the
president to dissolve the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The three-member bench said in its order that "there is
complete breakdown of the Constitutional machinery and it appears
that the government is not being run according to the provisions
of the Constitution."
</P>
<P>
However, another order issued only minutes later by a 10-member
bench of the Supreme Court led by Justice Saeed Uzzman Siddiqui
suspended the order retaining the 13th Amendment.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the 10-member bench also suspended the appointment
of Sajjad Ali Shah as Chief Justice of the Supreme Court of
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Speaker of the National Assembly Ilahi Buksh Soomro today
called on Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif after the three-member bench
issued the order that restored the presidential power to dismiss
the government.
</P>
<P>
Reliable sources told Xinhua that Sharif and Soomro discussed
ways and
means to safeguard the democratic institutions.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister is in contact with his top aids, cabinet
colleagues
and legal experts to discuss the grave situation, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
The sources said a proposal of impeaching the president was
discussed
in the light of the latest political development.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the president held a meeting with Chief of Army
Staff General Jahangir Karamat and discussed the prevailing
political crisis in the country.
</P>
<P>
The meeting between the president and the army chief lasted
more than
20 minutes. However, no details of the meeting were immediately
available. 
</P>
</TEXT>
