<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tim Duncan Named Rookie of Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Tim Duncan of San Antonio Spurs
was named today the first Rookie of the Month for the 1997-98
season for games played from opening night on October 31 through
November.
</P>
<P>
Duncan, the first selection in the 1997 NBA Draft, averaged
15.2 points, 11.1 rebounds, 2.56 blocked shots and 1.9 assists in
35.4 minutes per game and ranked sixth in shot blocking and field
goal percentage (106 for 187) and eighth in rebounding among
league leaders.
</P>
<P>
Among rookie league-leaders, he ranked first in scoring,
rebounding and minutes played, fourth in field goal percentage and
tied for 11th in assists.
</P>
<P>
The 7-0 forward and center from Wake Forest University teamed
with David Robinson to help lead the Spurs to a 9-7 record to
start the season, a six-game improvement over San Antonio's 3-13
record after 16 games last season.
</P>
<P>
The pair, the league's only teammates each averaging a
double-double, has the Spurs ranked first in shot blocking (7.13
blocked shots per game), fourth in defensive rebounding (32.1
rebounds per game) and eighth in field goal percentage in the
league.
</P>
<P>
Duncan posted double figures in points 12 times and in rebounds
nine times. He had several standout performances during the month
including 19 points and a Spurs rookie-record 22 rebounds against
the Chicago Bulls on November 3, and 19 points and 13 rebounds
against the Los Angeles Lakers on November 13.
</P>
<P>
Other candidates for the Rookie of the Month were Boston's Ron
Mercer, Cleveland's Zydrunas Ilgauskas and Brevin Knight, Denver's
Bobby Jackson, Philadelphia's Tim Thomas, Sacramento's Lawrence
Funderburke and Vancouver's Antonio Daniels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
