<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Peace Accord with Tribal Rebels Hailed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The signing of an historic peace
agreement between the Bangladeshi government and the tribal rebels
in the Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT) today has won wide acclaim in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina told newsmen shortly after the
signing, "I am surely delighted to see the solution of such a
long-standing problem."
</P>
<P>
The agreement, which means an end to more than two decades of
armed conflict in the hill areas bordering India and Myanmar, is
the outcome of six days of crucial peace talks between the
National Committee on Chittagong Hill Tracts formed by the
government and the Parbattaya Chattagram Jana Sanghati Samity
(PCJSS0, the political wing of the pro-independence armed rebels.
</P>
<P>
"We have always opted for peace and not divisions," Hasina
said. "The people of Bangladesh also want peace."
</P>
<P>
PCJSS Chief Jyotirindra Bodhipriya Larma, who is signatory to
the accord, said here today, "We are going to establish a new
life. We are coming back to our normal life."
</P>
<P>
Larma expressed the hope that overall development of the area
would take place from now on.
</P>
<P>
On how soon the accord would come to effect, the PCJSS chief
said "from right now". "It is a difficult task to sign a treaty
and a much more difficult job to implement it," he said.
</P>
<P>
He sought cooperation of all the people of the country to help
implement the accord. "We all have to work together for the
advancement of the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
The PCJSS leader also voiced total confidence in the present
government and said the people in the region will live in peace.
</P>
<P>
Bangladeshi Foreign Minister Abdus Samad Azad said that the
treaty was signed at an appropriate time, and expressed his hope
that everybody would extend support to the accord.
</P>
<P>
Chief of Army Staff Lt. Gen. Muhammad Mahbubur Rahman said that
everybody wanted peace in the hill tracks. "Our religion Islam
also advocates for peace," he noted. he was happy to see that the
problem, which existed for 25 years, was solved through political
process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
