<HEADLINE> Organ Donations Badly Needed in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Organ donations are
needed to save the lives of more than 1,500 people awaiting
kidney, heart or liver transplants, South Africa's Organ Donor
Foundation (ODF) said.
</P>
<P>
Transplant programs in the country's nine transplant centers
were running into serious difficulty because of a shortage of
donors, ODF spokesman Jaoqui Thomson said Monday.
</P>
<P>
This was because of lack of urgency, misconception and lack of
awareness and religious constraints, she said.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of patients with kidney failure were unable to be
accepted on hospital dialysis programs because of distance and
frequency of visits, and more than 10 people a week were sent
home, waiting to die because of lack of space on dialysis
machines.
</P>
<P>
Costs of keeping a person on dialysis were three times that of
a kidney transplant.
</P>
<P>
Need for kidney transplants was remarkably high in the black
community with the incidence of end stage renal failure, three
times higher than in the rest of the population because of a
high incidence of severe hypertension, said Thomson. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Looks for Possible Sources of Water Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
today gave orders to the National Irrigation Administration (NIA)
to undertake a thorough survey of all rivers in the Philippines to
harness them as water sources to mitigate the effects of the El
Nino weather disturbance.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting here, Ramos stressed the urgency of tapping
rivers as water sources to irrigate farmlands.
</P>
<P>
"Look at all the rivers in the Philippines for harnessing as
water sources for a variety of purposes -- water supply, hydro for
power generation, but especially for irrigation," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to a press statement issued by the presidential
office this afternoon, Ramos urged the NIA through the Department
of Agriculture to survey the rivers in the country because of the
worsening effects of El Nino.
</P>
<P>
El Nino refers to the abnormal warming of sea surface
temperatures in the South Pacific, which erupts every two to seven
years and causes severe flooding and drought.
</P>
<P>
The 1982-1983 El Nino, the worst one in 100 years, caused 13
billion U.S. dollars in damage and killed 2,000 people in the
world.
</P>
<P>
However, experts warned that the current El Nino, which began
in March, could be among the most severe in this century.
</P>
<P>
The worst effect will be felt over the next few months and
possibly extend into 1998 -- beyond its usual Christmas time peak,
they said.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Secretary Salvador Escudero said his department is
stepping up cloud-seeding operations to induce rains around Angat
Dam in Bulacan, which supplies waters to the Manila area.
</P>
<P>
"We are working jointly with the Philippine Air Forces in an
attempt to augment as soon as possible the water in Angat Dam," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Airplanes have also been deployed to critical regions to carry
out cloud-seeding operations, he said.
</P>
<P>
During the past eight months, El Nino has unleashed severe
drought in parts of the Philippines. In the Northern Philippines,
rainfall has been below normal since May, affecting major rice and
corn growing areas.
</P>
<P>
In the Philippine capital of Manila, the Metropolitan Water
Works and Sewerage System started Monday to reduce water supply by
12 hours. Normal water supply in the capital will not resume until
July next year due to the El Nino phenomenon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
