<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Manage Modest Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Australian stock market
managed a modest rise today, as softer exchanges in Tokyo and
South Korea conspired to cancel out a strong performance on Wall
Street overnight.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index added 11.4 points or just under half a
percent to finish at 2524.8.
</P>
<P>
Brokers described the local bourse's performance as lackluster,
given the Dow Jones index in New York jumped 189.98 points, or
more than two percent to 8013.11.
</P>
<P>
"I think South Korea's early falls set the tone for us today,"
Henderson Charlton Jones broker Stuart Smith said.
</P>
<P>
Tokyo's Nikkei 225 index closed 97.30 points softer at
16910.29.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's stock market plunged to a 10-year low during
morning trade on the back of panic selling due to the delay on the
International Monetary Fund rescue package. The Seoul index
finished 16.29 points lower at 376.87.
</P>
<P>
Closer to home, the gold index continued weaker, easing 3.6
points to 866.5 while bullion was 293.75 US dollars in late Sydney
trading, down from 296.65 here late yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The industrials sector climbed 17.9 points to a close of 4319.8
while the resources index moved up 6.4 to 1094.0.
</P>
<P>
The retail index improved despite the release of data showing
retail trade was down 0.2 percent on a seasonally adjusted basis
in October.
</P>
<P>
Resources giant BHP gained four cents to 14.14 Australian
dollars, Rio ended 18.6 cents and Normandy slipped back one to
1.30 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Telstra installment receipts rose six to 2.76 Australian
dollars, with 39.17 million changing hands valued at 107.2 million
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover topped 372.83 million shares valued at 1.01
billion Australian dollars (680 million US dollars). Rises
outpaced falls 591 to 535, with 405 steady.
</P>
<P>
Australia's big four banks had mixed fortunes.
</P>
<P>
NAB rose 37.7 cents, ANZ climbed 20 cents, Westpac ended 16.2
cents weaker and CBA shed 24 cents.  
</P>
</TEXT>
