<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Currency Continues to Slide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 2 (Xinhua)-- India's currency rupee
continued its down trend today when it dropped close to 40.00
against the U.S. dollar in the local foreign exchange trading
market.
</P>
<P>
The rupee opened weaker today at around 39.30/40 per U.S.
dollar after Monday night's free fall in the market nervous about
the lack of intervention of the Reserve Bank of India (RBI). At
around 11:00 local time, it slumped to 39.85 against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Dealers attributed the slump to political turmoil in the
country and heavy bank and corporate demand of U.S. dollars in the
market.
</P>
<P>
Later in the day, the rupee, however, recovered substantially
on reports of the RBI's coming out with a package of measures. It
was trading around 39.45/55 against the greenback.
</P>
<P>
RBI today announced a package of measures to arrest further
fall of the rupee against the dollar. the measures include raising
cash reserve ratio (CRR) by 0.5 percent, doing away with the 10
percent incremental CRR on non-resident rupee deposits and
suspending facilities granted to authorized dealers to offer
forward dollar contracts.
</P>
<P>
RBI also kept in abeyance the schedule of CRR reductions
already announced and enhanced the interest rate on fixed rate
deposits for Wednesday from 4.5 percent to five percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
