<HEADLINE> S. Africa Rejects Taiwan's Demands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Two major demands from
Taiwan in negotiating its future ties with South Africa are
"untenable" , Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
NZO made the statement at a press conference in the
headquarters of the African National Congress (ANC) in
Johannesburg, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
He said, Taiwan had asked to maintain its "symbols, flag and
name" at whatever premises their representatives continue to
occupy after 1997.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela announced last November
that his country would relinquish its diplomatic relations with
Taiwan in favour of the People's Republic of China at the end of
1997.
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately that would mean maintaining its current
status," Nzo stressed, giving an overview of achievements by the
ANC-led government in international relations during the past
three years.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said Taiwan also wants to keep open its
three consulates in South Africa, a position that could only
apply when diplomatic relations existed between countries.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations between South Africa and Taiwan on the nature of
their future relationship have been protracted, but agreement had
to be reached soon, Nzo said. 
</P>
