<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Slumps to New Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar slumped
to a new four-year low as worse-than-expected domestic data
compounded the threat of a second wave of Asian currency turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Australian dollar finished the session at 67.83 U.S. cents,
from 67.88 U.S. cents late Monday.
</P>
<P>
It had fallen to 67.38 U.S. cents in overnight trading - the
lowest level since December 1993 - following the release of the
latest domestic current account figures.
</P>
<P>
Today's release of retail sales figures provided more bad news
for the local currency in a market which is looking increasingly
negative.
</P>
<P>
Retail trade fell 0.2 percent in October from September, the
Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) said. Market expectations
had centered on a rise of 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The ABS also said building approvals rose 3.7 percent to 12,153
units in October. Economists had on average expected a rise of 3.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
Colonial State Bank foreign exchange dealer Nick Volanakis said
the market was very disappointed with the retail sales figures.
</P>
<P>
IBJ Australia Bank senior foreign exchange trader Darrin
Stewart said those figures, combined with the continuing adverse
outlook from Asia, drove the Australian dollar to its new low
overnight.
</P>
<P>
"This outlook is going to remain for the next few weeks, if not
months. The Australian dollar is going to suffer from the fallout
of the Asia crisis because we are talking about trade and that is
where the concern is," Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
At today's close, the Australian dollar finished at 87.07
against the Japanese yen from 86.69 Monday. It was at 1.2046
German marks, from 1.1980 Monday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
