<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Contract Signed to Rehabilitate Sri Lankan Fuel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka has decided to spend
more than 20 million U.S. dollars to rehabilitate the main
petroleum facilities in Colombo, which were damaged in an
explosion in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The China Huanqiu Chemical Engineering Corporation (HQCEC) and
the Ceylon Petroleum Corporation (CPC) signed the contract for the
emergency rehabilitation project here this morning.
</P>
<P>
The HQCEC won over all the other 86 international bidders to be
the sole contractor of the project.
</P>
<P>
The value of the contract is 21.8 million US dollars.
Meanwhile, the CPC is also planning to build infrastructure
facilities related to the project, putting the overall cost to
around 50.3 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Under the contract, the Chinese company is to build some new
oil tanks while rehabilitating other tanks that were damaged in
the explosion on October 20, 1995.
</P>
<P>
At the signing ceremony, HQCEC President He Lishan assured the
Sri Lankan side that his company will finish the project ahead of
schedule with high quality and low cost.
</P>
<P>
The construction is estimated to take 22 months.
</P>
<P>
The CPC also decided to decentralize its oil storage in order
to improve fuel distribution. A mini-terminal will be built at
Sapugaskanda, near Colombo, to this effect.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
