<HEADLINE> Former Boxing Champion Dies after Falling into Coma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Edwin Rosario, former boxing
champion, died Monday night, just months after a comeback fight
that he said would mark the end of his cocaine addiction.
</P>
<P>
A local TV report said the 34-year-old boxer died of a drug
overdose, but Rosario's Wilfredo Vazquez denied, saying "he was in
good health and strong but, sadly, he died tonight."
</P>
<P>
Police sources said the cause of death would not be known until
an autopsy was performed.
</P>
<P>
Promoter Felix Zabala said Rosario was training for a January
fight in Miami and had passed drug tests administered by the
boxing commissions in recent months.
</P>
<P>
Rosario complained of illness on Monday night and never waked
up in his sleep before his parents found him in a coma. He died
before receiving any medical care.
</P>
<P>
Rosario was one of the world's top boxers in the 1980s. His
wife divorced him for his cocaine addict.
</P>
<P>
In June, he staged a comeback in his hometown of Bayamon,
knocking out Maurice Patterson in four rounds, followed by a
third-round stoppage of James Moody in Miami. The two victories
pushed his career record to 40-6 with 35 knockouts.
</P>
<P>
Rosario stopped Akinou Hiranaka for the WBA junior-welterweight
crown in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
