<HEADLINE> 60 People Gunned Down in India's Bihar State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 2 (Xinhua)-- Sixty people were gunned down
by a private army of landowners in Lakshmanpur Bathe village of
Bihar state in eastern India late Monday night, Press Trust of
India (PTI) reported today.
</P>
<P>
This is the worst-ever mass killing in Bihar state since 1988
when 42 people were killed by ultra-left activists in
Dalelchak-Baghora village.
</P>
<P>
About 300 members of the outlawed private army Ranvir Sena with
firearms swooped on the Lakshmanpur Bathe village around 22:30
local time and indulged in killing for nearly two hours in
gruesome culmination of the running feud between landowners and
ultra-left activists.
</P>
<P>
The village is suspected to be sympathizer of the outlawed
ultra-left outfit, PTI said.
</P>
<P>
Before the massacre, a number of clashes between the two groups
had been reported from the region.
</P>
<P>
Home commissioner and director general of police from the
divisional and district headquarters have rushed to the spot.
</P>
</TEXT>
