<HEADLINE> Share Prices Slightly Higher on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Share prices moved in a
narrow range on the Singapore market today with the benchmark
Straits Times Industrials gaining 3.07 points to close at 1697.26.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that share prices finished higher on random
institutional buying of selected blue chips. Gains were
liquidity-driven as cash-rich fund managers hunted for stocks to
park their money in, they observed.
</P>
<P>
However, they warned that the market was far from seeing a
turnaround, as uncertainty prevailed in the region amid confusion
over the bailout package of the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
for South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Total market volume increased to 161.97 million units, valued
at 349.4 million Singapore dollars (about 218.38 million U.S.
dollars). Advances overtook declines by 182 to 152, while 284
other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore Telecom was the most actively traded stock as it
registered a turnover of 12.32 million units. It was followed by
Rekapac which had 9.57 million shares traded. Inno-Pacific was
next with 8.52 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore Press Holdings (SPH) Foreign led the gainers of
the day as it rose by 1.1 dollars to finish at 23.1 Singapore
dollars. The Overseas Chinese Banking Corporation (OCBC) Foreign
and the United Overseas Bank (UOB) Foreign increased by 85 cents
each to end at 10.8 and 10.7 Singapore dollars respectively. The
DBS (Development Bank of Singapore (DBS) Foreign gained 60 cents
to close at 15.8 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Creative 50 was the biggest loser as it
declined by 2.1 dollars to end at 41.1 Singapore dollars. Hume
fell by 1.13 dollars to close at 1.75 dollars, while Asean Fund
was 30 cents lower finishing at 8.7 U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
