<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Releases National Defense Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Australia released its
national defense policy here today, foreshadowing extensive
upgrading of its armed forces to make it more capable of defending
national interests beyond the coastline.
</P>
<P>
Releasing the review of Australia's strategic circumstances,
Defense Minister Ian McLachlan said the document went a step
beyond previous reviews in which it detailed a rigorous set of
priorities for force development.
</P>
<P>
The top priority for the Australian Defense Force (ADF) is
maintaining the ability to operate smarter than any likely
adversary, exploiting information technology to allow Australia's
small forces to be used to maximum effect, said the review, titled
"Australia's Strategic Policy".
</P>
<P>
That includes intelligence, surveillance communications and
command systems.
</P>
<P>
The Australian government has already approved 5 billion
Australian dollars (3.5 billion US dollars) worth of spending to
improve existing capabilities and to acquire new capabilities
including up to seven of the long-awaited airborne early warning
and control aircraft, rather than four previously proposed.
</P>
<P>
The second priority is for development of capabilities to
defeat threats in maritime approaches, including upgrading of
guided missile frigates and submarines.
</P>
<P>
The third priority is the ability to strike at hostile forces
through retaining an upgraded F-111 fleet in service to the year
2020. It will be equipped with longer range stand-off missiles.
But the government has ruled out acquisition of long-range
Tomahawk missiles.
</P>
<P>
The fourth priority is development of land capabilities. Army
units will get more wheeled armored vehicles and a helicopter fire
support and reconnaissance capability.
</P>
<P>
McLachlan said the current defense budget, plus likely savings
from the defense reform program, would allow modernization of
existing equipment.
</P>
<P>
But it would not make it possible in the medium term to develop
major new capabilities such as new fighters or warships.
</P>
<P>
"Indeed our strategic geography dictates that we should plan on
more pro-active operations which focus on defeating attacks in our
maritime and air approaches before they reach Australian
territory."
</P>
<P>
McLachlan said the review identified no immediate threats and
confirmed that Australia was one of the most secure countries in
the world.
</P>
<P>
This year's defense budget was one of the very few that escaped
axe by the Australian government eager to eliminate its budget
deficit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
