<HEADLINE> Bushfires Leave 2 Australian Firefighters Dead, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Two Australian firefighters
died and two were injured today as 200 bushfires fanned by strong
winds burned out of control across New South Wales (NSW) state and
licked at Sydney's outskirts.
</P>
<P>
At Lithgow, west of Sydney, two people lost their lives in a
fire which swept over the coalmining town, the Australian
Associated Press quoted police and Rural Fire Service spokesmen as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The fire was currently burning on both sides of the Great
Western Highway and homes on the northern side of the town had
been evacuated.
</P>
<P>
Dry and hot summer weather was blamed for the bushfire.
</P>
<P>
NSW Bush Fire Services acting assistant commissioner Mary Anne
Carmichael said two firefighters had been injured at the Pilliga
fire west of Coonabarabran, in the northern part of the state.
</P>
<P>
The Rural Fire Service said the country towns of Coonabarabran
and Lithgow and the Sydney suburbs of Menai, Lucas Heights,
Thornleigh and Normanhurst were emerging as the worst trouble
spots as more than 130 fires continued to burn around the state.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-eight aircraft were in the air and 4,500 firefighters
deployed statewide to battle the blazes.
</P>
<P>
On Sydney's southern fringe, two major fires and numerous spot
fires were threatening homes in the Sutherland Shire and another
blaze was out of control near the Lucas Heights nuclear reactor.
</P>
<P>
In northern NSW a huge fire was continuing to menace the towns
of Coonabarabran and Narrabri.
</P>
<P>
The fire had burned out 180,000 hectares of bushland and had
been close to being controlled until fresh outbreaks today.
</P>
</TEXT>
