<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Questions U.S.-backed African Peace Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's head of state, General
Sani Abacha Monday faulted the proposed African conflict response
initiative which is being sponsored by the United States.
</P>
<P>
Although some African states have already chosen to
participate in the training program, Abacha said, it would have
been more far-reaching if the initiative is managed by the
Organization of African Unity.
</P>
<P>
Without the participation of Nigeria, he noted, such an
initiative would be fatally-flawed and inappropriate, considering
Nigeria's outstanding role in both sub-regional and global
peace-keeping efforts.
</P>
<P>
Abacha made the comments in Abuja while opening a conference
on "military democracy and security in sub-Saharan Africa."
</P>
<P>
"I can not say that Nigeria would necessarily have accepted
the proposal, but it does seem inappropriate in view of our role
in ECOMOG (west African peace-keeping force) and long history
of peace-keeping under the U.N. auspices, that we have not been
invited to join the discussion on it," he was quoted by The
Guardian newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
Abacha noted that Nigeria's vision for the peace and security
of the sub-region and the rest of the sub-Saharan Africa is a
strong, resilient, confident and assertive multi-national
regional peace-keeping force such as ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
The concept of an African high command, he continued, had been
mooted for decades, resulting in a litany of reasons why it is
not practicable. But recent experience has shown that
sub-regional efforts, as in west and central Africa, might
provide a better answer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
