<HEADLINE> Social Welfare Extends to Farmers in North China City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Farmers on the outskirts
of Shijiazhuang, capital of north China's Hebei Province, are
getting access to benefits such as old age insurance, minimum
living guarantees, medicare, disaster relief loans which were
previously enjoyed only by urban residents.
</P>
<P>
The local government has raised the poverty line from 120 yuan
per month in 1996 to 140 yuan this year. Farmers living under this
poverty line will be given an extra allowance. More than 400
people living below the poverty line on the outskirts of
Shijiazhuang have received allowances.
</P>
<P>
So far, 230,000 farmers in the city's suburbs have participated
in the old-age insurance system with premiums totaling 22 million
yuan; and 519 people aged 60 or above have received 170,000 yuan in
old-age insurance benefits.
</P>
<P>
About 190,000 of the 200,000 farmers in the suburbs have bought
medicare insurance.
</P>
<P>
Disaster relief loans also are available. In August of 1996, a
devastating flood struck the city's suburbs. The local government
offered 1.2 million yuan in relief funds and 100,000 kilograms of
relief grain to 5,000 disaster victims.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
