<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Plus Six Finance Ministers for Sound Financial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 2 (Xinhua) -- ASEAN finance ministers
and their counterparts from China, Japan, South Korea, Australia,
the United States and the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
today agreed to work together towards a successful conclusion of
the WTO negotiations in financial services to enhance the
soundness of financial systems.
</P>
<P>
The ministers welcomed ASEAN's firm commitment to the
liberalization of financial services and to tabling offers before
the deadline of the conclusion of the negotiations in the WTO
(World Trade Organization), according to a statement issued here
today after their meeting.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to support measures to strengthen the financial
resources and institutional capabilities of the International
Monetary Fund (IMF), World Bank (WB) and Asian Development Bank
(ADB) working with the international regulatory bodies,
particularly in the areas of strengthening banking and financial
systems and deepening capital markets.
</P>
<P>
The ministers agreed that there is an urgent need to develop a
deep, liquid and matured debt market in Asia to address the
intermediation problem.
</P>
<P>
They endorsed the initiative to develop a market-based approach
to mobilize private sector resources with the intermediation of
the international financial institutions to assist adjustments in
this region.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, the ministers warmly welcomed the initiative of
Hong Kong to convene the first meeting of technical experts with
the assistance of international financial institutions to discuss
these ideas as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also endorsed and agreed on the rapid
implementation of the Manila Framework as a constructive step
towards promoting financial stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
The ministers noted in this regard that Japan would convene a
meeting of finance and central bank officials early next year to
carry forward the initiatives under the Manila Framework and work
closely with the IMF, WB, ADB and the international regular
bodies.
</P>
<P>
They noted the importance of sound, consistent and transparent
policies to promote efficient markets and emphasized the need for
greater transparency of capital markets and such efforts should be
implemented on a global basis and endorsed the IMF initiatives on
this matter.
</P>
<P>
They also recognized the need for enhancing and coordinating
supervision and prudential regulations given the importance of
raising prudential management in the private sector to enable them
to cope with the issues in the years to come.
</P>
<P>
They urged the IMF members to agree on early ratification of
the new arrangements to borrow and the agreement to increase IMF
quotas reached in Hong Kong recently.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also urged the IMF to work expeditiously towards
the establishment of a new quick disbursing short term facility.
</P>
<P>
They also welcomed the preliminary findings of a study carried
out by an IMF task force on the role of hedge funds in the recent
crisis in Southeast and Northeast Asia and looked forward to
receiving the full report.
</P>
<P>
They also urged the IMF to expand the scope of the study to
examine the structure of the global financial markets and short
term capital flows, including the impact of hedging activities on
the banking sector as well as the impact and implications of
technology on capital flows.
</P>
<P>
They recognized that in addressing the current financial
crisis, there was an equal urgent need for a balance between short
and long term measures to restore confidence.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that in addition to the Manila Framework,
the focus on policy should also be on developing market-based
solutions to address the intermediation problems in the region.
</P>
<P>
Efforts should also focus on strengthening domestic financial
systems to the deepening of financial markets and closer
collaborative efforts on financial regulations and supervision.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also noted that the process of surveillance
provided a mechanism for economies to identify areas that required
technical assistance to enhance the capacity of their domestic
financial systems to meet the challenges of globalization.
</P>
<P>
They expressed support to strengthen training programs for
financial supervisors and urged closer collaboration among
international and regional training providers towards that
objective.
</P>
<P>
They also expressed support for South Korea's effort to put in
place a program of economic policies and structural reform to
restore financial stability.
</P>
<P>
The statement also said that the ministers were briefed by WB
officials on its perspective on recent events in Southeast and
Northeast Asia and the measures that would need to be undertaken
to restore confidence in those economies.
</P>
<P>
The WB also affirmed its support for the implementation of the
Manila Framework.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
