<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 09:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab World to Support China, G77 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon and other Arab
countries will support the position of China and Group 77
countries to delay reducing greenhouse gas emissions till 2000 at
the world environment conference in Kyoto, Japan, the country's
Daily Star reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Lebanese Environment Minister Akram Shuhayyeb,
leader of a United Arab delegation to the conference, as saying
that Lebanon and the Arab countries are against the U.S. proposal
to trade in emission rights.
</P>
<P>
"We are also calling for industrialized nations like the
U.S. to pay compensation to developing countries who will be most
affected by climate change, caused by the large emissions from
well-developed countries," he added.
</P>
<P>
As agreed in Bonn last October, he said, there will be one
united position for the developing countries. "We do not believe
countries like Lebanon or Egypt that contribute to 0.001 percent
of emissions must adhere to the same policies or cut backs as
industrial nations," Shuhayyeb said.
</P>
<P>
In line with the position of China and G-77, joint
implementation on emission cutbacks should only start after 2000,
"because if developing countries cut back now, it will leave some
poor countries without electricity, which is unfair," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the an important suggestion from the United Arab
delegation was that "agreement of the protocol or any other
legally binding clauses must be endorsed unanimously and not by a
majority vote."
</P>
<P>
The 10-day conference kicked off Monday, which is expected to see a
bitter war of words among delegates from all over the world on how
to curb the growing global warming trend.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said that the U.S. has recently announced a shift
in policy, declaring that it would consider setting different
targets levels for different countries instead of a uniform rate
among the 34 affected countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
