<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Historical Evidence of Chinese Sovereignty over Islands on South China Sea Discovered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The discovery of a large number
of relics on Xisha Islands on the South China Sea has proven
China's sovereignty over all the islands on the South China Sea.
</P>
<P>
A survey in April 1996 of 18 islands, 4 shoals, and 4 atolls of
Xisha Islands found 1,300 relics on land and nearly 500 relics
in the sea in eight different spots.
</P>
<P>
"Many items were left from ships that sank there, to the north,
east and west of the islands, on a line from central China to the
south," Song Xinchao, an official from the State Bureau of
Cultural Relics, said at the Conference on Archaeological Findings
held here recently.
</P>
<P>
The relics mainly consist of pottery and porcelain, the oldest
of them dating back to the Tang Dynasty (618-907).
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the archaeological discovery proves that
Xisha Islands were first discovered by the Chinese, who have
developed the South China Sea region since the Tang Dynasty, at
the latest, and provides irrefutable evidence that Xisha
Islands have been Chinese territory since ancient times.
</P>
<P>
Most of the relics came from Guangdong, Fujian, Zhejiang, and
Jiangxi provinces, according to their design.
</P>
<P>
Underwater archaeological work was a major part of the study,
Song said, and many stone sculptures, pieces of pottery and
porcelain from the Ming and Qing dynasties were found during the
survey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
