<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Once Robust Czech Economy Suffers Down Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Once acclaimed as a tiger among
the region's economies and the symbol of a new Central Europe, the
Czech economy has taken a sharp downturn this year to face
unprecedented difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The tiger, if it really has ever been, rose to its paws after
successive years of economic recession in 1991 through 1993, when
the gross domestic product (GDP) was down by 14.2 percent, 6.4
percent and 0.9 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
After the initial pains believed to be brought about by the
country's economic transformation, the Czech economy returned to
the growth path in 1994, resulting in a 4.8 percent GDP growth in
1995 and a 4.4 percent growth in the year after.
</P>
<P>
However, beginning early this year, the overall economic
performance has retreated from what was considered the relatively
better off state among Central and East Europe nations, the growth
lost its momentum, and problems, micro and macro, showed up.
</P>
<P>
As indicated by official data, the Czech Republic's economic
growth this year will be no more than 1.8 percent, or less than
half of the government's earlier projection, and much lower than
that of Poland, Hungary, Slovakia or other countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
During the first nine months of the year, while the country's
manufacturing sector grew by only 0.5 percent over the same period
of 1996, its construction sector shrank by 0.5 percent and the
inflation rate climbed to two digits to stay at 10.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the republic's foreign trade deficit is likely to
reach 139 billion crowns (about 4.21 billion U.S. dollars), or 5.7
percent of the GDP, by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
And already recognized, by popular standards, as an alarming
high is its public sector foreign debt of total 21.2 billion
dollars, which is equivalent to 43 percent of the GDP.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the current unemployment rate of 4.8 percent has
been an all-time high. And huge budgetary deficit, together with
decreased foreign reserves, has driven the historically strong
crown down by more than 20 percent, to the current exchange rate
of 33 crowns for 1 dollar.
</P>
<P>
Facing up with such a grave situation, the Czech government
adopted a series of economic austerity measures, first time in
April and again in May, including increasing government revenues,
cutting spendings and curbing foreign imports.
</P>
<P>
But so far none of these measures have appeared to be working
as expected.
</P>
<P>
The worsening economy has increasingly alienated the Czech
people and further undermined the country's political stability,
resulting in the resignation of Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus and
his cabinet on November 30.
</P>
<P>
Behind the Czech Republic's economic decline are a number of
causes.
</P>
<P>
Firstly, it's the inadequate economic guidelines and policies
to be blamed. The Klaus administration, a strong advocate of
market economy, relied too heavily on the so-called "market force"
and gave up too much in exerting macroeconomic controls.
</P>
<P>
While the framework of a market economy was in place, a series
of facilitating measures were lagging behind, and legislative and
judicial efforts were too weak to check the rise of economic
crimes, such as graft, embezzlement and tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
To make it worse, over a dozen of banks went bankrupt, leading
to the confusion on the capital and financial market.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, the government didn't have a clearly defined
industrial policy, the physical and financial infrastructure was
obsolete, many economic sectors still stayed in the shadow of the
old production system, and microeconomic mechanisms were prone to
numerous problems.
</P>
<P>
While the government claims that the private sector now account
for 85 percent of the GDP, analysts point out that a sizable
proportion of the country's big businesses are still under the
state control, and deep-rooted problems of the economic structure
are yet to be resolved.
</P>
<P>
As industrial restructuring has been progressing rather slowly,
business managers are more inclined to take short-term measures to
boost performances and invest little in technical renovation
programs. As results, their products often lack of competitiveness
and are hardly marketable overseas, and over one-third of all
industrial enterprises are reporting losses.
</P>
<P>
Seven years after embarking on the market economy path, the
overall Czech economy is still below what it used to be before the
transformation period. In the industrial sector, the output in
1996 was only 82 percent of the 1990 figure.
</P>
<P>
To walk out from the economic difficulties and regain the
momentum for growth, economists here said, the Czech government
has to give priorities to speeding up the renovation of the
country's state businesses, specialized banks and social security
systems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
