<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Bar Association Supports Chief Justice Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Bar Association of the
Supreme Court has expressed its support to the suspension of the
13th Amendment of the Constitution by a three-member bench led by
Chief Justice Sajjad Ali shah.
</P>
<P>
The Bar Association of the Supreme Court made a statement
today, accusing the Government of Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif of
splitting the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
However, Parliamentary Secretary Zaffar Ali shah said the
suspension of the 13th Amendment is "illegal" and
"unconstitutional."
</P>
<P>
The move by Sajjad Ali Shah was aimed at creating "chaos" in
the country, Zaffar added.
</P>
<P>
An order issued earlier today by the three-member bench headed
by Chief Justice Sajjad Ali Shah said, "there is complete
breakdown of the constitutional machinery and it appears that the
government is not being run according to the provisions of the
Constitution."
</P>
<P>
However, another bench of the apex court headed by Justice
Saeed Uzzman Siddiqui toppled the order and asked to suspend the
appointment of Sajjad Ali Shah as the Chief Justice.
</P>
<P>
The 13th Amendment to the Constitution, which was passed by the
two Houses of the Parliament in April this year, took away the
powers of the President to dissolve the National Assembly and
government.
</P>
<P>
The 13th Amendment repealed some controversial items, or the
notorious 8th Amendment.
</P>
<P>
The 8th Amendment was passed in 1985 during the marshal law by
late president Zia ul Haq. It stipulates that the president has
the powers to dissolve the National Assembly when the president
feels it is not working under the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
Under the 8th Amendment of the Constitution, the president also
has the power to dissolve a government when he feels it is not
working in accordance with the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
Since 1985, there are altogether four elected governments which
were dissolved by the president under the 8th Amendment of the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
Nawaz Sharif assumed the premiership in February this year
after staying more than three years in the opposition when his
Pakistan Muslim League (N) won a landslide victory in the national
elections.
</P>
<P>
Taking the advantage of an overwhelming majority in the
National Assembly as well as in the Senate, the government passed
the 13 Amendment of the Constitution, depriving the president of
the powers to dissolve the National Assembly and government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
