<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Push OIC Summit to Create Common Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 2 (Xinhua) -- In order to improve economic
cooperation among the Islamic countries, Iran will push the
forthcoming summit of Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC)
to create an Islamic common market.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to see this common market created and hope
that agreement in this regard will be reached during the OIC
summit," Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister for Economic Affairs
Mahmoud Vaezi was quoted today by local daily Iran News as
saying.
</P>
<P>
He said that despite various difficulties, Iran hopes the
issue of Islamic common market will be discussed at the eighth
OIC summit due to be held here on December 9-11.
</P>
<P>
On the sidelines of the OIC summit, Iran has decided to hold
an Islamic trade fair in Tehran as a measure to push the OIC
members to consider the issue of Islamic common market.
</P>
<P>
The trade fair was aimed at preparing grounds for the
formation of the Islamic common market, executive director of the
trade fair Akbar Nematollahi said last month.
</P>
<P>
He said that a dozen of countries as well as the Islamic
Development Bank and some U.N.-afflicted institutions will take
part in the fair.
</P>
<P>
The fair will be held on December 4-15 in five sections,
including industry and mines, agriculture and cattle breeding,
industrial and scientific research section, culture, arts and
communications, and trade and commerce.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic countries enjoy about 70 percent of the world's
energy reserves, 30 percent of world's natural gas reserves, 70
percent of phosphate resources and 42 percent of world oil
exports, according to Iranian officials.
</P>
<P>
However, Vaezi noted that the OIC members were facing serious
difficulties to form the Islamic common market, one of them is
that the OIC members are not all at the same level of economic
development.
</P>
<P>
"We are also aware that a mere agreement (at the OIC summit)
will not necessarily result in the actual formation of such a
market," he said.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the Islamic countries would hopefully reach
a consensus regarding the issue of Islamic common market through
various meetings at the OIC summit.
</P>
<P>
Vaezi also cited the European Common Market as an example,
saying that the European Common Market is still pursuing its
objectives despite the existing conflicts among its members.
</P>
<P>
Iran, during its tenure as the OIC chairman following the OIC
summit, will endeavor to translate the summit's decisions into
practical measures, bringing the stances and points of view of
the member states closer together, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
