<HEADLINE> Turkey to Upgrade F-5 Fleet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Turkey is considering to upgrade
its aged F-5 fighters and will appoint a foreign company next week
to do the job.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's Defense Industry Executive Board is scheduled to meet
December 9 to choose the project partner, local newspaper Daily
News today quoted senior officials from the General Staff as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz and Chief of General Staff
Ismail Hakki Karadayi are expected to attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
A board's meeting held in mid-October favored Israeli and
Singaporean companies in the project which involves 48 F-5 planes.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz, however, reacted strongly to the result, saying that
the project should be given to France as Paris is a key supporter
of Turkey' European Union membership bid.
</P>
<P>
France, a co-producer of the Airbus planes, was disappointed
with Turkey's recent decision to buy 26 Boeing 737 aircraft from
the United States.
</P>
<P>
Western countries supply nearly 80 percent of the arms of the
Turkish armed forces, a strong power in the region, official
statistics show. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
