<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank to Aid Kenya in Speeding up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank will provide
Kenya a credit of 1.4 billion Shillings (24 million U.S. Dollars)
next year to help speed up the privatization of government-owned
institutions, the Daily Nation newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The faster pace of privatization will free funds formerly tied
up in non-performing assets while reducing the drain on the
treasury by those parastatals, said Ian Knapp, leader of the team
in charge of privatization and civil service reform at the bank's
Nairobi office.
</P>
<P>
Privatization would play a big role in poverty alleviation
since the privatized institutions are much more productive
without being a burden on public funds, he noted.
</P>
<P>
As many as 159 enterprises have already been privatized in
Kenya which has a total of 207 government-owned institutions.
</P>
<P>
For the further move, the privatization of the Kenya Posts and
Telecommunications Corporation (OBTC) is expected to be the
biggest of all and may be launched soon after the elections set
for December 29.
</P>
<P>
The partial divestiture of the government from Kenya
Commercial Bank will also take place next year, with the
government further reducing its 60 percent shareholding by an
additional 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
A recent study of ten of the privatized companies has showed
that the number of employees rose by 120 percent while their
salaries shot up by 170 percent.
</P>
<P>
Exports also jumped by 380 percent while all other indicators
pointed to an across-the-board improvement in performance, the
study showed.
</P>
<P>
The burden on Kenya's exchequer arising from sustaining
parastatals dropped sharply from 2.25 billion Shillings (38.6
million Dollars) in 1992 to about 500 million Shillings (8.6
million Dollars) last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
