<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 08:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Systematic Defects Blamed for Mashaal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Fundamental defects were
found in the functioning of Israeli secret intelligence Mossad by
Israeli Knesset (parliament) committee investigating the Mashaal
Affair, Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the Knesset committee on secret services
finished on Monday the first stage of its investigation into the
bungled assassination of Hamas political leader Khaled Mashaal,
which was carried out by Mossad on September 25 in Amman.
</P>
<P>
The committee issued a statement saying that the
decision-making process in the government's upper echleon was
faulty, and that nobody involved in the planning of the affair had
warned Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu that carrying out an
attack in Jordan could have serious diplomatic ramifications.
</P>
<P>
"So far, significant deficiencies were noted in the functioning
of the bodies involved. Some of the problems identified by the
committee are fundamental and have accompanied activities -- at
all levels -- for a period of time," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
However, the committee recommended that at this stage there is
no need for action to be taken against anyone involved in the
affair.
</P>
<P>
"At the end of this stage of its work, the committee is
convinced that changes should be considered in some fields of
operation, but there is no place for drawing personal conclusions
against those involved," the statement noted.
</P>
<P>
It added that "the committee will continue to examine
wide-ranging aspects of this issue. It will make its conclusions
and present the principal recommendations in a classified report."
</P>
<P>
The botched attempt in Amman soured Israel's relations with
Jordan. Two Israeli agents were taken prisoner, and in return
for their release, Israel had to free Hamas founder Sheikh
Ahmed Yassin and dozens of other Palestinian and Jordanian
prisoners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
