<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Has Stepped Up Anti-doping Battle, Chinese Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 2 (Xinhua) -- China has stepped up the
anti-doping campaign through clear stipulation, tight check and
harsh penalty, Chinese sports official said here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We have increased greatly the number of drug checks in the
year of 1997," said Professor Yang Tianle, member of the Chinese
Olympic Committee's Medical Commission and co-founder of the
Beijing Drug-testing Laboratory which is sanctioned by the
International Olympic Committee (IOC).
</P>
<P>
In swimming alone, 576 tests, including 397 out-of-competition
checks, had been taken from January 1 to October 30 this year and
none turned out positive, said Yang, also member of the IOC
Medical Commission.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Chinese swimmers had taken 293 drug tests, with 153
conducted out of competition, China's leading drug fighter said.
</P>
<P>
The 24 IOC-sanctioned labs in the world had done a total of
3,757 tests on swimmers in 1996 and as Yang predicts, this year's
total remains that many.
</P>
<P>
"In the number of tests on swimmers, few countries can compete
with China in the year of 1997," Yang said.
</P>
<P>
Australia, hailed as vanguard in the battle against drugs,
registered 220 tests on swimmers from July 1996 to June 1997, with
102 done out of competition.
</P>
<P>
In the sports as a whole, 3,349 doping checks, including 1,733
flight tests, had been done on Chinese athletes in the past 10
months and the numbers for 1994-1996 had risen from 1,292 to 1,914
and to 2,080 last year, the Chinese official said.
</P>
<P>
The numbers of flight tests for 1994-1996 were 526, 708 and
1,115, he added.
</P>
<P>
Yang noted that China's percentage of positive case was lower
than international average mark. "In 1995, seven out of 1,000
cases were positive, the rate lower than 1.37% internationally,"
he said. "We got 0.5% in 1996 against 1.63% internationally and
0.63% in 1997."
</P>
<P>
Australia recorded 1.14 in the percentage of positive case in
1996, with Japan at 1.28, France 4.06 and Canada 4.32, Yang said.
</P>
<P>
Yang stressed that China welcomes flight tests on Chinese
athletes by world sports ruling bodies.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome out-of-competition drug checks by international
federations, but double standard must not be applied," he said.
</P>
<P>
Doping charges against Chinese swimmers surfaced during
October's Chinese Eighth National Games which saw two world
records tumbled in the pool.
</P>
<P>
Australian swimming head coach Don Talbot accused Chinese
swimmers of taking drugs, inviting criticism from both the
Australian Olympic Committee (AOC) and the International Swimming
Federation (FINA).
</P>
<P>
John Coates, AOC president and one of Australia's two IOC
members, said that Talbot's charge was groundless.
</P>
<P>
FINA general secretary Gunnar Werner noted that Australians'
allegation against Chinese came out because they felt threatened.
</P>
<P>
"I'm a little surprised about Don Talbot. Usually he is very
balanced. Maybe he is under pressure from the other coaches in
Australia," Werner told an Australian radio on October 21.
</P>
<P>
Yang was indignant with the smear campaign kicked off by a few
coaches.
</P>
<P>
"You can't sling mud at athletes who have achieved good
results," he said. "Before you have evidence, you had better keep
your mouth shut."
</P>
<P>
Shi Kangcheng, other member of the Chinese Olympic Committee's
Anti-doping Commission, refuted the charge that China encouraged
systematic doping.
</P>
<P>
"The allegation of systematic doping is sheer fabrication," he
said. "China only has systematic anti-doping."
</P>
<P>
For those caught dopers and coaches held responsible, harsh
punishment is unavoidable, Shi noted.
</P>
<P>
"The whole club will be banned for one year if it registers two
positive cases," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
