<HEADLINE> Bangladesh PM Hails Agreement With Tribal Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina today expressed her happiness at the signing of an historic
agreement between her government and the tribal rebels in the
Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT).
</P>
<P>
"I am surely delighted to see the solution of such a
long-standing problem," she told newsmen shortly after the signing
of the treaty, which is to end more than two decades of armed
conflict in the hill areas bordering Indian and Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
According to a copy of the agreement obtained by Xinhua, a
powerful regional council, holding the status of a ministry, will
be founded in charge of the CHT affairs and it will be headed by a
tribal person.
</P>
<P>
Hasina said her government, hoping to restore peace in the
region, initiated work for finding a durable solution to the
problem soon after coming to power in June last year.
</P>
<P>
"We have always opted for peace and not division," she said.
"The people of Bangladesh also wanted peace".
</P>
<P>
The agreement was an outcome of six days of crucial peace talks
between National Committee on Chittagong Hill Tracts formed by the
government and Parbattaya Chattagram Jana Sanghati Samity (PCJSS),
the political wing of the pro-independence armed rebels.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Drops in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The underlying rate of
inflation in Kenya which excludes food prices, fell from 6.5
percent during the period from October last year to October this
year to 5.2 percent during the past 12 months before November
this year, the Daily Nation newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
It was the third consecutive monthly decline in the underlying
inflation rates, the report quoted the Central Bank as saying.
</P>
<P>
On a three-month annualized basis, underlying inflation fell
to 10.8 percent in the three months to November from 15.1 percent
in the eastern African country.
</P>
<P>
However, overall inflation rose to 5.5 percent in the three
months to November from 3.9 percent in the three months to
October, according to the bank data. 
</P>
</TEXT>
