<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Merge Exchange Rates in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Paul Ogwuma, Governor of the
Central Bank of Nigeria has revealed that the official and
autonomous foreign exchange rates of the local currency Naira
would be unified next year, according to press reports today.
</P>
<P>
"I want to assure you that by next year, we should have a
unified exchange rate of the Naira," the country's number one
banker said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Under Nigeria's dual exchange rate system, all government
transactions with the Central Bank are retained at the official
exchange rate of 22 Naira to one U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, all other commercial transactions depend on the
autonomous foreign exchange market introduced in 1995 for the
green back at a rate which has remained at an average of about 82
Naira to one dollar this year.
</P>
<P>
But it turns out that the target beneficiaries of the scheme,
namely, the industrial sector, has become the ultimate loser, as
the people who buy foreign exchange at the autonomous market are
only interested in reselling at higher rates at the black market,
or parallel market as it is called locally.
</P>
<P>
This subsequently gave rise to public criticisms of the dual
exchange rates and calls for their merger.
</P>
<P>
The expected unification of the two rates and a liberalized
trade and exchange system would ultimately lead to the full
convertibility of the Naira, said the Central Bank governor.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the government plans to stabilize the
exchange rate at 75 Naira to one dollar by gradual strengthening
of the local currency at the foreign exchange autonomous market
where the Central Bank sells dollar to other commercial banks
once a week.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate at the market hovered between one dollar for
80 Naira between 1995 and early 1997 but later depreciated to 85
Naira. The current rate stands at 79 Naira to one dollar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
