<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Million Nigerians Being HIV Positive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Over two million people in
Nigeria, or nearly one fifth of its population, are currently
living with the HIV virus, while about 103,000 AIDS-related
deaths have been reported so far, the Ministry of Health has
said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing Monday in Abuja commemorating
this year's World AIDS Day, the ministry's acting Permenant
Secretary Suleiman Sani said 10,803 AIDS cases have been reported
as of August this year, compared to two cases in 1986.
</P>
<P>
About 66,510 children have been estimated to be infected with
HIV in 1997, while 45,070 children were reported to have AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Also in this year, 44,580 children have died of AIDS while
118,308 children under five became orphans as a result of their
parents' death due to AIDS, the official said.
</P>
<P>
"It is most appropriate for us to stop for a while and focus
our attention on the fate of our children and young people in a
world where HIV infection is increasing at an alarming rate," he
added.
</P>
<P>
"Children living in a world with AIDS" is the theme of this
year's World AIDS Day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
