<HEADLINE> Two Chinese-Filipino Businessmen Kidnapped in Manila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Five armed men abducted a
Chinese-Filipino trader in front of his home in downtown Manila at
dawn today, police said.
</P>
<P>
Police said that the suspects, armed with pistols, forced
Agustin Uy, 54, owner of KC Industrial Corporation, into his own
car parked beside his residence on Tomas Mapua Street, Manila.
</P>
<P>
Uy was walking toward his car when held at gunpoint by the
suspects who approached him from behind at about 04:30, police
said.
</P>
<P>
Less than 12 hours earlier, several heavily armed men abducted
at gunpoint a 78-year-old Chinese-Filipino businessman along a
highway in Quezon City, the Northern Manila.
</P>
<P>
The suspects blocked the car of Go Chong Liok, owner of Falcon
Metal Industries, along Acme Road, in Quezon City, and took Go and
his driver away.
</P>
<P>
The driver, who was freed a few hours later, reported the
incident to the police.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, 98 kidnappings have taken place
in the first nine months of this year in the Philippines. Most of
the victims were Chinese-Filipinos.
</P>
<P>
A week ago, Gordon Tan, a 24-year old Chinese-Filipino
businessman, was shot dead while trying to wrench himself free
from several armed men who took him by force as he walked in front
of his family's shoe factory.
</P>
<P>
As an expression of solidarity and sympathy for Tan and other
kidnap victims, some Chinese schools and shops in Chinatown,
Manila were closed today.  
</P>
</TEXT>
