<HEADLINE> Southwest China Transportation Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China is extending
great effort to build up a transportation network radiating in all
directions in order to promote economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Guizhou Province plans to invest between 8-9 billion yuan for
highway construction by the year 2000. The province has also
introduced electrification to upgrade sections of three railway
lines.
</P>
<P>
Progress has been made in establishing a high-grade highway
network linking Kunming with prefectures in Yunnan and various
other neighboring provinces. Yunnan has also constructed eight
airports.
</P>
<P>
Some 20 ports rated at 10,000 tons have entered operations in
Fangcheng, Qingzhou and Beihai in the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region. Efforts to harness the Xijiang River have been accelerated
in order to enable 1,000-ton cargo vessels to reach Hong Kong and
Macao via the Nanpan and Youjiang rivers.
</P>
<P>
The Nanning-kunming Railway Line officially entered operations
today. The line runs from Nanning, capital of the Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region, to Kunming, capital of Yunnan Province, with a
trunk line running to Hongguo in Guizhou Province. The line,
southwest China's outlet to the sea, was constructed at a cost of
20 billion yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
