<HEADLINE> Overseas Investment Helps Shanghai in Urban Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Overseas funds have accounted
for about 25 percent of Shanghai's investments in urban
construction, giving a new look to the major trade center in China.
</P>
<P>
Urban construction projects with overseas financing include the
new subway, a waste water treatment plant, a water supply plant,
roads, and reconstruction of old areas.
</P>
<P>
From 1991 to 1995, the city used over one billion US dollars
in indirect foreign investment, including foreign government
and international financial organization loans, for its
infrastruture.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, Shanghai used the BOT (built, operate, transfer)
method for the first time to get foreign investments for a
1.8-billion-yuan (217 million US dollars) tunnel project.
</P>
<P>
Eight BOT projects, involving 4 billion yuan in overseas
investment, have been started in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Becvause the city needs 300 billion yuan for urban construction
and environmental protection in the 1996-2000 period, it expects
to expand the use of overseas funds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
