<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 08:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peace Process Increases Polarization in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Oslo peace process has
widened the gap between sections of Israeli population, a
polarization that weakens society and undermines its ability to
achieve peace with its neighbors, a survey published today said.
</P>
<P>
The research, published by local English daily The Jerusalem
Post today, was conducted by Dr. Tamar Hermann and Professor
Ephraim Yaar of Tel Aviv University's Steinmetz Center for Peace
Research on the relations between secular and religious
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
The research was also based on the August and October's "Peace
Index" findings, which reflected the Israeli society's attitude
toward the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The study, which surveyed 504 people with a 4 percent margin
of error, showed erosion in relations between secular and
religious Israelis in the wake of the Oslo peace process since
it began in 1993.
</P>
<P>
A total of 47.6 percent of secular Israelis and 59.1 percent
of religious Israelis said they believed the peace process has
caused a "distancing" between the two sections of the Israeli
society.
</P>
<P>
The findings showed an evenly divided society on the Oslo
process, as 55.6 percent secular respondents favor the Oslo
accords, while 59.1 percent of those observant religious oppose
them.
</P>
<P>
It also found that 70 percent of those polled believe the
influence of the religious political bloc is too strong;
surprisingly, about 60 percent of the religious respondents agree
with this view.
</P>
<P>
The current Likud-led rightwing-religious coalition is under
heavy influence of the religious parties, which oppose making
major concessions according to the widely-accepted "land for
peace" principle, which is the corner-stone of the Oslo
process.
</P>
<P>
Since the Likud government came to power in June last year,
the peace process has been in deep trouble, leading to
increasing tensions with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-seven percent of those polled termed themselves
"right-wingers," 32 percent "left-wingers," and 20 percent
someplace in between the two, while 7 percent said they belonged
to neither of the two camps. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
