<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maritime, Aerospace Exhibition Opens in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The fourth Langkawi
International Maritime and Aerospace (LIMA) Exhibition opened
today in Malaysia's northern resort island Langkawi.
</P>
<P>
This year's six-day event, including an aerospace exhibition
and a maritime exhibition, has drawn the biggest-ever number of
participants with 903 companies from some 40 countries and
regions, reports monitored here said.
</P>
<P>
During the show, there will be aerial displays by several
aircraft manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that several memorandums of understanding of
billions of ringgit (about 3.5 ringgit equal to one U.S. dollar)
will be signed during the show.
</P>
<P>
Opening the exhibition, Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad expressed optimism about Southeast Asia's aerospace
industry which had been growing at the same accelerated pace as
the region's economy prior to economic setbacks in July.
</P>
<P>
He said the manufacturing of aircraft and components has
advanced a lot since 1991 when the first LIMA, now the world's
largest air and maritime show, was held in the scenic resort
island, some 500 kilometers north from here.
</P>
<P>
Many Southeast Asian countries are now producing small aircraft
and components for big commercial airplanes, Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
He said with depreciating currencies now, the region was going
to be more attractive for the production of high quality
components at lower cost, particularly labor-intensive composite
items.
</P>
<P>
Some countries in the Asia-Pacific region are now actively
negotiating joint ventures to produce regional jets and commercial
aircraft, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that by 2014 the demand for aircraft by Asia-Pacific
countries was estimated at 3500, or one quarter of the world's
requirement of 15,000 with a value of 400 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said though the region's currency depreciation reduced
purchasing power, everyone was convinced that the region's
resilience would make the present problem temporary.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian leader stressed that there was no arms race in
the region but old equipment needed to be replaced with more
modern ones as areas of defense responsibility widened.  
</P>
</TEXT>
