<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Reviews Gender Advancements in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Poverty eradication is
one of the main challenges to advancing women's political and
economic empowerment in Africa, a spokesman for the United
Nations Development Program (UNDP) said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Poverty is still the main focus of the Ugandan UNDP program,
spokesman Wilson Kwamya told the UNDP Regional Bureau for Africa
(RBA)'s regional gender round-table being held in Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
However, Kwamya said, much progress on gender issues had been
made in Uganda since the fourth World Conference on Women held in
1995 in Beijing, China.
</P>
<P>
Political empowerment for women had been aided by reserving
some seats in parliament for women and affirmative action was
being applied so that more women could enter university.
</P>
<P>
Uganda was reviewing its laws relation to marriage,
particularly customary marriage, to see how inequalities for
women could be addressed, he said.
</P>
<P>
An umbrella group of special interest women's groups, the
National Association of Women's Organizations, had also been
formed.
</P>
<P>
The round-table meeting focused on progress made in women's
political and economic empowerment in Africa and attempted follow
up on commitments made at the Beijing world conference.
</P>
<P>
A five million U.S. dollar RBA gender pilot program had been
set up to target the greatest obstacles to gender equality and
equity in Africa, particularly the lack of women's access to
formal power and decision-making.
</P>
<P>
The meeting aimed to formulate an overall work plan and to
ensure the cohesiveness of the program which would operate in
partnership with local governments, agencies and civil
organizations.
</P>
<P>
"Achieving gender equity is pivotal to achieving sustainable
human development. Sub-Saharan Africa still faces critical
challenges in order to level the playing field for women and
men," said David Whaley, UNDP's resident South African
representative.
</P>
<P>
UNDP representatives from the 12 African countries involved in
the RBA program made presentations on Monday, which included
Uganda, Tanzania, Ethiopia, Rwanda, Sierra Leone, Mozambique and
South Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
