<HEADLINE> Nankun Railway Brings Hope to Ethnic Minority Groups </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Nankun Railway, which
entered operations today, has brought great change to the once
isolated lives of ethnic minority groups in southwestern China.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the railway created tens of thousands of jobs
for local residents in southwestern Guizhou Province, and enabled
more than 520,000 people escape poverty during the 1993-1996
period, according to a local official.
</P>
<P>
"The Nankun Railway embodies the hopes of over 700,000 ethnic
people for a better life. The railway project has also expedited
the construction of highways, water supply facilities and power
plants," according to Huang Kangsheng.
</P>
<P>
Members of 30-odd ethnic groups living in the region account
for more than 40 percent of the local population. The region has
remained economically backward due to adverse geological factors
and inadequate transportation systems, with the average annual
income for the local residents standing at slightly over 400 yuan
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The region has designed a blueprint for the accelerated
development of mineral, agricultural and tourism resources near
the line. Large-scale construction of highways and various other
infrastructure facilities is in full swing.
</P>
<P>
Constantly improving transportation conditions in the area are
attracting an increasing number of foreign investors. The contract
on establishing a Sino-Canadian coal mine involving a total
investment of 250 million US dollars was signed recently. A gold
mine in the area has also attracted investors from the United
States and Canada. 
</P>
</TEXT>
