<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- The importance of developing the military ties between
China and Japan is signaled in the Japanese tour of Xiong
Guangkai, deputy chief of the General Staff of the People's
Liberation Army of China.
</P>
<P>
Xiong held talks with Japan's Defense Agency Chief Fumio Kyuma,
Kazuya Natsukawa, Chairman of Joint Staff Council of Japan's
Defense Agency, Koichi Kato, General Secretary of the ruling
Liberal Democratic Party and other Japanese defense and government
officials. The Chinese visitor and the Japanese officials
exchanged views on the international situation and regional
security, and reached broad consensus. (Japan-China-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korea has reportedly accepted most of demands of
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) to reach an agreement on the
terms of the IMF bailout package for its economy in early Tuesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
In the last-ditch round of negotiations held downtown Seoul
midnight Monday, South Korea has reportedly agreed to allow
foreign firms to take over South Korean financial institutions
through mergers and acquisitions. Seoul also agreed to lower the
macro-economic growth rate to 2.5 percent, cut government fiscal
budget next year by 7.5 trillion won (about 6.4 billion U.S
dollars) to assist the restructuring in financial sector, and
reduce next year's current-account deficit to less than five
billion dollars, as the IMF demanded, government sources said.
(Skorea-IMF)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Speakers of the Russian and Ukrainian parliaments
said Monday the Treaty of Friendship, Cooperation and Partnership
will be ratified by the two parliaments at the end of the year,
the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Russian State Duma Chairman Gennady Seleznev met with visiting
Ukrainian Supreme Soviet Chairman Alexande Moroz and discussed the
approval of the treaty and parliamentary cooperation.
(Russia-Ukraine) 
</P>
