<HEADLINE> Shanghai Improves Postal Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Despite the fact that
communicating via telephones or fax machines is quicker and much
simpler than using mail services, Shanghai residents led the
nation by sending an average 14 letters during the first seven
months of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The 575-odd post offices in the city, one of China's economic
powerhouses, completed transactions valued at nearly 500 million
yuan, with overseas business accounting for 10 percent of the
total.
</P>
<P>
Each facility serves an average area of 8.9 sq.km., and offers
computerized services to an average population of 18,300 people.
</P>
<P>
Local officials attributed growth in postal transactions to
expansion of the service network and improved infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
For example, the Pudong International Airport is constructing a
mail handling center, a business building providing comprehensive
postal services and an air mail exchange center.
</P>
<P>
Postal savings are also increasing rapidly. Official sources
note that 100 new savings outlets and 100 ATMs (automatic teller
machines) will be available within the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
