<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Seeks Conservative Views on Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Faced with complaints that
President Bill Clinton's dialogue on race is one-sided and closed
to his critics, the White House revealed plans on Monday to meet
with conservatives later this month to seek their views.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry made this announcement just
before the first town hall meeting on race, following the drive
launched by Clinton in June. It is to be held Wednesday in Akron,
Ohio, in a bid to fend off concerns that the forthcoming session
would just be a forum for friendly views.
</P>
<P>
Though admitting that participants were chosen on
recommendations from a university and local officials, McCurry
said there was no plan to insulate Clinton from people with
differing views.
</P>
<P>
So far, the only conservative publicly tapped for Clinton's
initiative is Abigail Thernstrom, co-author of a book arguing that
blacks are progressing faster and Americans' racial attitudes are
much more accepting than usually believed.
</P>
<P>
Thernstrom and two other authors were asked to facilitate the
Akron discussion, which will focus on racial attitudes among
American youth.
</P>
<P>
A consultant for Clinton's Race Advisory Board cautioned Monday
that Clinton's efforts for racial harmony face a high risk of
failure if the Akron meeting has too much happy talk, according to
an Associated Press report.
</P>
<P>
"There's a great tendency in all of this to try to focus on
areas where we are most likely to find common ground. If that
becomes a preoccupation, then the initiative will not succeed,"
said Christopher Edley, who is also a law professor at the Harvard
University.
</P>
<P>
A mayor or a school board member struggling with a racially
divided community would need solid advice, he said.
</P>
<P>
Edley said he voiced his concerns to the White House, and
suggested aides pursue input from conservatives.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman McCurry said Clinton wouild likely "have a further
session with exactly those kinds of people" eventually. But he
wanted the Akron meeting to involve authors "who would stimulate
the kind of conversation the president wants." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
