<HEADLINE> Proposed Carbon Tax Can Cause 20 Billion U.S Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC) stated that it's members could lose
some 20 billion U.S. dollars in annual revenue as a result of the
proposed measures to reduce global greenhouse gases.
</P>
<P>
According to an OPEC statement issued here Monday after the
conclusion of the organization's 103d ministerial meeting, OPEC
wanted compensation for loss of revenue that could be caused by
the carbon tax proposed at the International Climate Meeting being
held this week in Kyoto, Japan.
</P>
<P>
The statement, which is available today, reiterated the OPEC's
position concerning the Third Conference of the Parties (COP3) to
the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC)
in Kyoto, which gathered together representatives of more than 150
nations on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Like the other nations sharing this small planet, the statement
said, OPEC members countries have an interest in a clean, healthy
and harmonious environment.
</P>
<P>
"We recognize a global responsibility to future generations who
have a right to inherit a sound and sustainable world," it added.
</P>
<P>
Thus, OPEC believes that certain steps may need to be taken to
avert the possible consequences of man-made (anthropogenic)
climate change. But as the group of developing countries that is
most dependent upon fossil fuel, it is concerned that the
legitimate right to economic developing, shared by all developing
countries, is under threat from the mitigation measures that may
come under discussion at the Kyoto meeting.
</P>
<P>
"OPEC unreservedly supports the case for more scientific
research into the global climate system," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
OPEC groups Algeria, Indonesia, Iran, Iraq, Kuwait, Libya,
Nigeria, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates and
Venezuela.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
