<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: India, Pakistan Trying to Improve Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 2 (Xinhua) -- After decades of rivalry,
both India and Pakistan have come to realize that it is time for
them to change their attitudes.
</P>
<P>
This year, the 50th after their independence in 1947, has
witnessed great efforts by the two arch rivals to try to improve
their bilateral ties and enhance economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The two countries in March resumed their
foreign-secretary-level talks, stalled for about three years, in
New Delhi, capital of India. Since then three rounds of such talks
have been held, in New Delhi and in Islamabad, capital of
Pakistan, respectively.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the two sides discussed all bilateral issues
of mutual concern including the Kashmir issue and reportedly
reached some consensus.
</P>
<P>
The atmosphere of the talks was said to be warm and cordial and
both sides have time and again expressed their desire to continue
their peaceful dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Then Indian Foreign Minister I. K. Gujral, who is now caretaker
prime minister, and his Pakistani counterpart Gohar Ayub Khan held
informal talks here on April 9 to further push forward the
rapprochement process between the two countries. They agreed that
the two countries should draw lessons from the past 50 years of
confrontation and resolve their disputes through peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
In the past 50 years, the two countries have suffered a great
deal of money and personnel in their confrontation.
</P>
<P>
Since division in 1947, India and Pakistan have gone to war
three times over the dispute of Kashmir and religious issues.
Skirmishes were often reported along the actual control line
between the two countries in Jammu and Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
But the two countries finally realized that development was
their most important task in the face of a changing world after
the "cold war."
</P>
<P>
Gujral said on February 26 while addressing a seminar on
"South-South Perspective" that "a global arms race has depleted
resources available for development without serving the cause of
peace and security for any country in the long run."
</P>
<P>
"We must be able to concentrate on the task of improving the
living standards of our own people and build a progressive and
economically vibrant India," he said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani leaders expressed similar views.
</P>
<P>
In a speech at the Institute of Strategic Studies in Islamabad
on March 16, Gohar Ayub Khan said that India and Pakistan had
"both realized the importance of bilateral discussions if they are
to witness a stable future."
</P>
<P>
"Has anybody sat down in India or Pakistan to calculate how
much they have spent on defense since 1948 and how long we
continue doing this?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
"We can compete, India and Pakistan, on an economic front," he
said.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with an Indian TV program on June 6, Pakistan
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif said, "This is not the time to fight.
We must learn from our past mistakes and should analyze what all
we have gained or lost. We fought wars and spent so much on
defense budget instead of concentrating on the development of both
nations. We have only suffered by adopting a path of
confrontation. It's high time we should change our attitude."
</P>
<P>
In their first-ever meeting in recent years in Male, capital of
the Maldives, on May 12, the two prime ministers, Gujral and
Sharif, reached several agreements on improving bilateral
relations. The agreements included setting up joint working groups
to specially deal with all their disputes, establishing hot lines
between the two prime ministers to timely consult each other and
discuss urgent problems between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Again they met for the same purpose in New York on September 24
and in Edinburgh, Scotland, on October 25. In their meetings, they
expressed the desire to continue their dialogue no matter what
difficulties and ups-and-downs would come across in their way
ahead.
</P>
<P>
The rapprochement process between the two countries has been
widely welcomed and supported by the two countries' public
opinions, which have also been building up for the improvement and
normalization of relations between the two South Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
At its third session in India's Calcutta city, the
Pakistan-India People's Forum for Peace and Democracy called on
the two governments to sign a comprehensive treaty for lasting
peace in the region. A declaration of the meeting attended by
leading citizens of the two countries urged the two governments to
begin working to realize the aspirations of the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
It may take time for India and Pakistan to normalize their ties
because the two countries are still widely divided over their
disputes, especially the Kashmir issue. But one thing is certain:
the leaders of the two countries want to solve their differences
through dialogue.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
