<HEADLINE> Russia, Bulgaria Seeks to Bridge Gap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Russia and Bulgaria today sought
to bridge a gap between the two countries and said they were
determined to give new impetus to their traditional ties.
</P>
<P>
Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov said in a joint press
conference that his talks with Bulgarian Foreign Minister Nadezhda
Mikhailova were "very useful". Although the two countries have
different views on the eastward expansion of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO), there were not any "rifts" or
"conflicts" in the bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Primakov proposed that Russia and Bulgaria should seek common
interests and further bilateral relations on the basis of mutual
benefit.
</P>
<P>
Mikhailova said her Russia visit will be conducive to
discussing political and economic issues and in seeking
resolutions in conformity with bilateral interests.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria, once the Soviet Union's closest ally, has forged
closer ties with Western Europe since 1989.
</P>
<P>
On October 3, Bulgaria hosted a meeting of defense ministers
from southeast Europe and the United States. They discussed how to
reform their armies to prepare them for NATO membership, and how
to work together to reduce regional tensions.
</P>
<P>
Russia protested that it was not invited, but Sofia said that
as Russia was not in southeast Europe and had no plans to join
NATO, it did not qualify for an invitation.
</P>
<P>
In earlier October, the two countries failed to agree at talks
in Sofia on prices and terms for delivery of Russian natural gas
to Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
The Bulgarian foreign minister arrived here today on a working
visit aimed at bridging the gap between the two countries and
paving the way for Bulgarian President Petar Stoyanov's
forthcoming Russian tour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
