<HEADLINE> China, Japan Stressing Military Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The importance of developing the
military ties between China and Japan is signalled in the Japanese
tour of Xiong Guangkai, deputy chief of the General Staff of the
People's Liberation Army (PLA) of China.
</P>
<P>
Xiong and his delegation arrived in Japan on November 30 on a
three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
Xiong held talks with Japan's Defense Agency Chief Fumio Kyuma,
Kazuya Natsukawa, Chairman of Joint Staff Council of Japan's
Defense Agency, Koichi Kato, General Secretary of the ruling
Liberal Democratic Party and other Japanese defense and government
officials.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese visitor and the Japanese officials exchanged views
on the international situation and regional security, and reached
broad consensus.
</P>
<P>
Both sides held that relations between the PLA and Japan's
Self-Defense Forces are an important part of bilateral ties and
should be strengthened on the basis of principles reached by top
leaders of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed on exchange visits between Chinese Defense
Minister Chi Haotian and Kyuma, Fu Quanyou, Chief of General Staff
of the PLA and Natsukawa in 1998. Details of the visits remain to
be worked out.
</P>
<P>
Xiong and his party visited a naval base for Japan's Maritime
Self-Defense Force in Yokozuka, Kanagawa Prefecture, before
leaving for home this afternoon. 
</P>
