<HEADLINE> NASA Decides on Second Spacewalk to Test Station Equipment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Two astronauts aboard the
space shuttle Columbia will make a second spacewalk Wednesday to
test equipment to be used for building an international space station.
</P>
<P>
The United States National Aeronautic and Space Administration
(NASA) made the decision today after the American astronaut
Winston Scott and his Japanese colleague Takao Doi were hindered
from doing so in their first spacewalk last Monday.
</P>
<P>
It will be NASA's last spacewalk before next summer when
construction on the international space station begins.
</P>
<P>
NASA said it was necessary for astronauts to have all the
spacewalking experience before building the space station.
</P>
<P>
In their seven-and-a-half-hour spacewalk, Scott and Doi had no
chance to lift an extendible, 3.5 meter crane and a free-flying
robotic camera as planned.
</P>
<P>
Instead, they had to grab, with hands gloved, the Spartan
science satellite which was malfunctioning after its November 21
release from the shuttle.
</P>
<P>
Later they worked with the crane and a large, batterylike
object, and conducted some other station experiments.
</P>
<P>
Columbia's 16-day mission is scheduled to end with a landing
at Cape Canaveral, Florida Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
In November 1996, astronauts on Columbia were locked in the
shuttle by a jammed hatch and failed to test the crane. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Likely to Meet Euro Deficit Ratio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Italy is likely to meet the 3
percent deficit to GDP ratio this year required for entry into the
euro area.
</P>
<P>
The figures released today by the Treasury showed that the
country's financial deficit is 78 trillion lire (45 billion
U.S. dollars) in the first 11 months this year, 43 percent less
than the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The deficit ratio and inflation rate specified in the
Maastricht treaty are regarded as two prerequisites for entering
the economic and monetary union in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Italy's financial deficit accounted for 6.7 percent of the GDP
in 1995. Through cutting public spending and other austerity
measures, the government expected to bring it down to or within
the specified limit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
