<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Major Newspaper on Country's Political Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 2 (Xinhua) -- India's major English
newspaper The Hindustan Times said in an editorial that with no
political party being able to muster enough support so far, the
president's efforts seemed to be running out of options.
</P>
<P>
"With arithmetic remaining steadfastly uncooperative, President
K.R. Narayanan's efforts to install an alternative government in
place of Inder Kumar Gujral's seven-month-long government seem to
be running out of options," it said.
</P>
<P>
"The Bharatiya Janata Party (the biggest opposition in the
country), which has so far remained an interested onlooker of the
unseemly wrangles between the United Front and its outside
supporter (the Congress), now feels that it deserves another
chance. There is more wishful thinking than logic to its claim,"
it said.
</P>
<P>
"As for the United Front and the Congress, all permutations and
combinations offer no hope but each side feels that the other
would have no option but to support it. The longer Mr. Narayanan
takes to form his judgment, the greater the chances of attempts by
major parties to engineer splits and defections to close the
number gap between minority and majority," it added.
</P>
<P>
"The President also has the discretion to go beyond the claims
of rival groupings to think of other combinations. Going to the
people should continue to be the last option," it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
