<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chittagong Port Under Closure Threat for Tips Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's largest port
Chittagong is under the threat of closure as a dispute between
port master stevedores and dock workers over tips worsened.
</P>
<P>
Port sources said today that the master stevedores have decided
to stop employing dock workers from December 4 if the workers do
not withdraw their present "go-slow" tactics by December 3.
</P>
<P>
The dock workers started their "go-slow" tactics on November 10
following a decision by the master stevedores to stop giving
"speed money" (tips) to them which had long been paid.
</P>
<P>
The Chittagong port has been constantly troubled by labor
disputes or trade issues, hampering the national trade badly. More
than 35 days of activities at the port have been suspended this
year due to non-cooperation by the dock workers and strikes called
for various reasons.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, foreign feeder operators are considering imposing
congestion surcharges in the backdrop of the fresh congestion
created at the port due to the tips dispute, which has also caused
the port's productivity to fall to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
Since 1980, congestion surcharges have been imposed by
frustrated foreign feeder operators over a dozen times.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
