<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Largest University Links in Commercial Partnership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 1 (Xinhua) -- California State University
(CSU) plans to bring data, voice and video infrastructure up to a
present day technology baseline on its campuses through
partnership with four high-tech firms.
</P>
<P>
University officials said the plan aims to "meld technology and
intellect to provide ubiquitous telecommunication services, to
improve education, and do so with a reasonable rate of return."
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, called California Educational Technology
Initiative (CETI), a company will be formed between CSU and the
firms of Microsoft, GTE, Fujitsu and Hughes.
</P>
<P>
Pouring 300 million U.S. dollars into building and maintaining
computer and telephone networks, the new company will be the
exclusive provider of all the campuses' baseline technology,
ensuring students and professors easy access to high-speed
communications networks by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The company will also gain access to a potential market of more
than a million customers, including students, professors, staff
and CSU alumni. A contract is to be signed this month.
</P>
<P>
With a total enrollment of 337,000 students and 37,000 faculty
and staff, the 22-campus CSU is the world's largest university
system. Almost 1.7 million people have graduated from CSU campuses
since 1960.
</P>
<P>
The working capital of 36 million dollars for the initiative
will come from the commercial partners. The commercial team will
lease the infrastructure to CETI or the CSU through a financial
institution.
</P>
<P>
Bonds will be sold for 180 million dollars to finance the
balance of the infrastructure and CETI will sign loan documents
and the commercial partners will guarantee any loans required.
</P>
<P>
The company hopes to generate revenues as high as 3 billion
dollars over 10 years by selling services such as computer
support, pager accounts and Internet access to the public.
Whether or not students would be charged for Internet and computer
access has not been worked out, university officials said.
</P>
<P>
The CSU leaders view the arrangement as a creative solution for
a university facing deep cutbacks in state money and
ever-increasing numbers of students. The CSU-San Francisco
president Robert Corrigan told a local newspaper:"As a president
who can't get the money either from the students or from the
state, I'm driven into working with the corporate sector."
</P>
<P>
But many professors and students feel worried about the
possible corporate takeover of academia, says the San Francisco
Chronicle. Some are wary that the corporations would dictate
things like course requirements, the usage of software and
hardware and the publication of course materials.
</P>
<P>
Others are afraid of being forced to cede control over the
university's educational direction to high-tech companies. Student
leaders are concerned that students are treated in the plan as
consumers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Not Optimistic Over Kyoto Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia hopes the United
Nations climate change conference in Kyoto, Japan, will reaffirm
the 1992 Rio commitment to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, but
says it will opt for "reasonable" solutions if the meeting is
deadlocked.
</P>
<P>
State Minister of Environment Sarwono Kusumaatmadja said here
Monday before departure for the Kyoto meeting that due to the
apparent deadlock among some countries over the target for gas
emission reduction, Indonesia was taking a "realistic" stance to
the 10-day conference.
</P>
<P>
"We base ourselves on our own national interests which conform
to (global) climate stabilization programs, so we have no problem
at all with the Rio commitment," official sources today quoted
Sarwono as saying.
</P>
<P>
The problem now lies with the lack of international unity on
establishing allowable levels for greenhouse gas emissions, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The international conference on climate change began in Kyoto
on Monday with the aim to set limits for gas emissions and
determine which gases are to be included.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia sticks to the 1992 Rio commitment to reduce emissions
to the 1990 level by 2000, with carbon dioxide, methane and
nitrousoxide among the gases which must be reduced.
</P>
<P>
Sarwono hoped that all parties will adhere to the 1992 Rio
commitment.
</P>
<P>
However, Sarwono was not upbeat about the outcome of the
conference, saying that "even if the conference succeeds in
getting a consensus, it will be a compromising one, softer than
the Rio commitment."
</P>
<P>
More than 150 countries are taking part in the conference to
tackle the myriad of thorny issues to reach an agreement,
hopefully a Kyoto Protocol, to combat the threat of global
warming.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Seek to Join MIGA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will apply to join the
Multilateral Investment Guarantee Agency (MIGA) in a bid to
protect Thai investments from running high risks, a local
newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Thai Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanahaeminda discussed the
matter on Monday in Malaysia with Lorin Weisenfeld, an executive
of MIGA, the Nation said.
</P>
<P>
MIGA is a World Bank affiliate which provides guarantees on
investments against currency transfer risks, contract breach
risks, and assets expropriation risks.
</P>
<P>
Joining the international body will make Thai investments safer
against foreign exchange losses, especially in other Southeast
Asian nations that are seeing a currency turmoil, the newspaper
said.
</P>
<P>
The body also provides guarantees on other risks, like war and
civil disturbances, it said.
</P>
<P>
To be a MIGA member, Thailand will have to enact related laws
governing MIGA activities in Thailand and contribute 4.5 million
U.S. dollars to the body.
</P>
<P>
MIGA currently has 128 full members, including Malaysia, the
Philippines and Indonesia, the newspaper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
