<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand 11 Months' Inflation Rate at 5.5 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 2 (Xinhua) -- As a result of the weakening
baht, higher value-added tax and rising production costs,
Thailand's inflation in the first 11 months of this year rose by
5.5 percent as compared with the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate in November, 7.6 percent higher than the
same month of last year, was the highest this year, according to
business economics department deputy director-general Vithun
Tulyanond.
</P>
<P>
Vithun said it was unusual for inflation to rise towards the
end of a year, adding that normally prices remain stable in the
last few months of a year as it is the season when more
agricultural produce is supplied to the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
The unseasonal inflation increase has caused concern that the
government will have to make more efforts if it wants to keep the
inflation rate below its targeted 6 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
According to the department, the price of high-speed diesel in
November was 32.30 percent higher than it was before the baht was
floated on July 2, with unleaded gasoline up 28.80 percent.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco and alcoholic drinks were also among those commodities
which saw high price hikes due to an increase in excise tax and
the higher price of fuel oil.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
