<HEADLINE> Thai Plan for Export Industries' Recovery in 5 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Industry Ministry has
drawn up a five-year plan for the recovery of export-oriented
industries, hoping that the country will be back on track toward
global competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
To achieve the target, the ministry will offer loans to those
industries with good prospects, especially exporters, to help them
regain the edge in terms of production costs, according to
Industry Minister Somsak Thepsuthin.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will focus on upgrading machinery and development
of the processed food sector, which relies on local raw materials,
the Bangkok Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
Loans will be used to improve food hygiene, which is an
important factor for export.
</P>
<P>
Other industries standing to benefit are jewelry, leather
goods, decorative products, vehicles and electrical appliances.
</P>
<P>
Loans totaling 1.2 billion U.S. dollars have been obtained from
the World Bank and the Asian Development Bank to pay for industry
restructuring, with the first 300 million dollars due early next
year and the rest in 1999 and 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
