<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Weapons Provision Does Not Reflect Hostility: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali
Alatas said the large number of weapons being imported into
Southeast Asia does not reflect any feelings of mistrust or
hostility among ASEAN members.
</P>
<P>
"The increasing expenditure on defense or weapons should not be
seen as an arms race," Alatas said here Monday at the Parliament,
sources at the Parliament disclosed today.
</P>
<P>
According to a report raised at the Parliament by the
International Institute for Strategic Studies (IISS), East Asia
and Saudi Arabia are the biggest annual arms consumers in the
world, while Indonesia and Thailand are among the biggest
importers of weapons, spending approximately 700 million U.S.
dollars. Third biggest importer is Singapore with a total of 400
million U.S. dollars and Malaysia is fourth with imports of 350
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASRAN) groups
Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand,
Myanmar, Laos and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Alatas said that to properly understand the IISS report, "we
should be aware that every country has different motivations and
considerations in their defense expenditures."
</P>
<P>
He admitted some ASEAN member countries have recently
modernized their armed forces to improve their high-tech
armaments, and to improve their ability to deal with pirates and
smugglers.
</P>
<P>
Arms development in the ASEAN region is considered neither
offensive nor defensive against other countries, said Alatas. The
single most important principle of the ASEAN security agreement,
he said, is to maintain regional security in comprehensive ways.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New IAEA Chief Takes His Seat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The new director-general of the
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), Mohammed El Baradei,
assumed his office here today, taking the place of Hans Blix who
had held the post for 16 years.
</P>
<P>
The new chief was elected by a conference of IAEA's Board of
Governors in July, 1997 and recognized by its General Conference
later.
</P>
<P>
The peaceful use of atomic energy, Baradei said, was sure to
develop in the future.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1957, IAEA aims at enlarging the contribution
atomic energy makes to peace, health and prosperity throughout the
world, and ensuring that its assistance, provided or requested
under its supervision or control, was not used in such a way as to
further military purposes.
</P>
<P>
In January, 1984, China joined the IAEA and its Board of
Governors and signed, with 37 other nations, the Convention on
Nuclear Safety at the 38th conference of the IAEA in September,
1994 in Vienna. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
