<HEADLINE> Growth Slows in U.S. Manufacturing Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Growth rate in
U.S. manufacturing sector slowed slightly in November, the
National Association of Purchasing Management (NAPM) reported
today.
</P>
<P>
NAPM said its index of manufacturing activity fell to 54.4 in
November from 56.0 in October, although November marked the 18th
consecutive month of manufacturing growth.
</P>
<P>
An index above 50 indicates that the manufacturing sector is
generally expanding while a rate below 50 indicates it is
contracting.
</P>
<P>
However, the manufacturing employment increased to 53.5 in
November from 52.4 in October, marking the 9th consecutive month
of job growth in manufacturing sector, said NAPM, whose members
include purchasing managers at more than 300 industrial companies
across the United States.
</P>
<P>
NAPM's report also said business leaders remain optimistic
about the future of the U.S. economy, which continued to grow in
November for the 79th consecutive month.
</P>
<P>
"The economy is still very strong. Our members continue to be
very optimistic about the future," Norbert Ore, chairman of NAPM's
Business Survey Committee, told reporters in a
teleconference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
