<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OPEC's Basket Oil Price 18.8 U.S. Dollars Per Barrel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Secretary General of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting countries (OPEC) Rilwanu
Lukman said here last night that the basket price of the cartel's
oil in the world market is about 18.8 u.s. dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
The basket price, he said, indicated that the cartel's decision
to increase its production ceiling to 27.5 million barrels per day
(bpd) would not influence the world oil price.
</P>
<P>
Delegations of the OPEC countries at their 103rd conference
that ended here Monday, decided to increase their production
ceiling from 25.033 million bpd to 27.5 million bpd at the first
half of next year.
</P>
<P>
Lukman, who was reelected at the meeting as the organization's
secretary general for the second time, admitted many parties were
worried about OPEC's offensive decision to push up its production
ceiling.
</P>
<P>
However, considering that OPEC's actual production in 1997 was
more than 27 million bpd while its world market price remained
stable, he believed that the oil price would continue to remain
stable at about 18 U.S. dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
The estimation was based on the organization's analysis that
the coming winter would be too cold and the world's demand for oil
in the first half of 1998 was believed to increase about 1.5 to 2
million bpd, he added.
</P>
<P>
But Lukman reminded each of the cartel's member country to
respect their own individual oil quota.
</P>
<P>
The six-day conference was attended by oil ministers from the
11 OPEC members. They are Algeria, Indonesia, Iran, Iraq, Kuwait,
Libya, Nigeria, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates and
Venezuela.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
