<HEADLINE> Brazilian President Leaves for Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso left today for Britain on a five-day official
visit aiming to promote bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Cardoso is scheduled to meet British Prime Minister Tony Blair
and about 250 British businessmen, Brazil's Foreign Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The world's financial situation, cooperation in education,
science and technology, the environment, human rights, the fight
against drugs, organized crime and money laundering are expected
to be key issues on their agenda.
</P>
<P>
They will also review cooperation between the European Union
and the South America's largest trade bloc Mercosur and discuss
the next two-bloc summit scheduled for early 1999.
</P>
<P>
Cardoso`s trip is viewed as an attempt to attract the attention
of British investors to Brazil's economy.
</P>
<P>
Britain is the third largest foreign investor in Brazil with
investments amounting to 6 billion U.S. dollars. The two
countries' bilateral trade was worth 2.5 billion dollars in 1996.
