<HEADLINE> SAARC Meeting Stresses Poverty Alleviation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Council of Ministers of
the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) has
again stressed the need to make poverty alleviation and regional
economic cooperation the prime objectives of the group, the SAARC
Secretariat said.
</P>
<P>
The SAARC foreign ministers, meeting in the Maldives on
November 29-30, reviewed progress made in the cooperative
activities to eradicate poverty from South Asia at the earliest
possible time, according to a press release issued on Monday by
the Kathmandu-based SAARC-Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The council also directed that coordinated and effective
actions be taken to achieve the goal of a South Asian Free Trade
Area (SAFTA) by 2001 as decided at a SAARC summit in May, the
press release said.
</P>
<P>
The council stressed the need to adequately address the
concerns of the least developed member states through implementing
concrete steps during the process of trade liberalization in South
Asia.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh, Bhutan, Nepal and the Maldives are the least
developed member countries of SAARC, which also comprises India,
Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of the seven countries also stressed the
importance of promoting trade-creating investments along with
steps to improve transport, communications and other
infrastructures in the region, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
The next session of the Council of Ministers will be held in
the first half of August, 1998 in Colombo, Sri Lanka, prior to the
10th SAARC summit, the press release said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
