<HEADLINE> China, Mexico Agree to Forge Trans-Century Partnership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang
Zemin and his Mexican counterpart, Ernesto Zedillo, agreed today
that China and Mexico should establish a cross-century partnership
of all-round cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders reached the agreement during their talks here
at the presidential residence. They maintained that such a
relationship is of great importance to raising the overall
strength of developing countries and establishing a new
international political and economic order.
</P>
<P>
Jiang and Zedillo also agreed on four points for the
development of China-Mexico relations:
</P>
<P>
-- Increase high-level exchanges and promote political
cooperation;
</P>
<P>
-- Enhance economic and trade cooperation on the basis of
equality and mutual benefit;
</P>
<P>
-- Conduct all-round cooperation and expand the connotation of
friendship;
</P>
<P>
-- Cooperate closely and support each other on international
issues, particularly strengthen their coordination and cooperation
in the United Nations and the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation
(APEC) forum.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said China and Mexico, as two developing powers that
carry weight and members of APEC, enjoy political stability and
economic development and bear a major impact on regional and
international issues.
</P>
<P>
The broad common ground shared by the two countries is a solid
foundation for the further development of their friendly relations
of cooperation, Jiang added.
</P>
<P>
Zedillo said Jiang's on-going visit will bring Mexico-China
relations into a new stage of development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
