<HEADLINE> Jordan Hints at Retirement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- NBA superstar Michael Jordan
is giving hints that the 1997-1998 season may be his last.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's Chicago Bulls, strggling for their sixth NBA crown in
eight years, have started with a lackluster run of 9-7 with
Scottie Pippen sidelined with injuries and demanding a trade,
Dennis Rodman inconsistent and Jordan unhappy with the turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Complaining about the present situation of the Bulls, Jordan is
sending a message that his farewell is near, at least to the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, following the murder of his father, Jordan made his
first retirement and began playing baseball, only to return to the
Bulls in early 1995.
</P>
<P>
"My purpose for coming back has always been to support Scottie
Pippen, as well as Phil Jackson (head coach) as well as the team;
whatever way we all can prosper from that. (Pippen) feels as
though that can't happen for him right now," said Jordan.
</P>
<P>
"I don't know if I can do anything to change those feelings. I
think that's something that he has with management and that's made
some deeper scars than what can be healed at this point," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
