<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Honduras Elects New President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEGUCIGALPA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Carlos Flores of Honduras'
ruling Liberal Party, won the election on Sunday to become the
country's new president.
</P>
<P>
With nearly 1.4 million votes counted as of Monday, Flores
gained 52.8 percent of the votes while his rival, Gunera de Melgar
of the National Party, won 42.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Some 2.8 million registered voters cast their votes in Sunday's
ballot, the fifth general election in this Central American
country since military rulers ceded power in 1981.
</P>
<P>
The country's two major parties, the Liberal Party and National
Party, as well as three other smaller parties, joined the race.
</P>
<P>
Flores, 47, is president of the Congress and a newspaper
owner. By law, he is scheduled to replace the current president,
Carlos Roberto Reina, and take office on January 27, 1998.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, the Honduran voters also elected three vice
presidents, 128 congressional deputies, 20 deputies to the Central
American Parliament and 297 mayors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
