<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Looks to Alternative National Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The Bulgarian Cabinet has
seconded a bill allowing young men to undertake an alternative to
military national service.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Georgi Ananiev said after a Monday cabinet
meeting that under the bill, alternative non-military service
would be performed in the interests of the public by young men
unwilling to serve in the army as envisaged by the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
Young men who do not want to fulfill their military service are
expected to submit applications to a yet-to-be Central Commission
for Alternative National Service, under the Ministry of Labour and
Social Affairs.
</P>
<P>
The Commission, which would be completely independent from the
military, would decide whether applicants had decided to take up
an alternative service out of their own choice, or because of
other pressure.
</P>
<P>
It was proposed that alternative service was double the time of
military service, the Defense Minister said. Such was the practice
in France, Greece and Hungary, he said.
</P>
<P>
A youth could perform the alternative national service in
various branches of the national economy, the social sector and
Civil Defense as well as posts in the armed forces which did not
require the bearing of arms.
</P>
<P>
They would draw wages equal to those paid for military service,
said Ananiev.
</P>
<P>
The bill also envisages penalties for alternative service
evaders. The Penal Code is expected to be amended in compliance
with the new law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0308 </DOCNO>
