<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Inspectors Start Monitoring U.S. Nuclear Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- United Nations inspectors
today began monitoring an Ohio plant that dilute weapons-grade
uranium into fuel to produce electricity.
</P>
<P>
The International Atomic Energy Agency began installing video
cameras, seals and other monitoring gear at the government-owned
Portsmouth Gaseous Diffusion plant at Piketon, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
The Geneva-based IAEA will conduct spot checks of the
Portsmouth plant roughly twice a month from December 17 until the
anticipated completion in August 1998 of the current downblending
operation.
</P>
<P>
"For the first time, international monitors are witnessing a
nuclear weapon state take weapons-usable uranium from its military
program and transform it into fuel for heating homes and lighting
cities," Energy Secretary Federico Pena said.
</P>
<P>
Pena told reporters here today that under the new procedure, an
initial three and a half tons of highly enriched uranium will be
diluted, or downblended, under the supervision of IAEA monitors.
</P>
<P>
The material is part of 174 metric tons of weapons-grade
uranium that President Bill Clinton declared in 1995 was beyond
U.S. defense needs. Pena said all 174 tons would eventually be
made available for IAEA monitoring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
