<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Protects Endangered Amphibian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region plans to establish a nature protection zone to
protect the Ranodon Sibiricus, a rare endangered species,
according to a local wildlife specialist.
</P>
<P>
The amphibian, found only in Xinjiang's Wenquan County, is
highly valuable for zoological research, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang placed the species under special protection in
1989. However, the population of the species declined sharply from
8,600 at the beginning of the 1990s to only 2,100 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Wang Lequan, a top leader in Xinjiang, said anyone harming the
species in any way will be subject to severe punishment.
</P>
<P>
The experts in the autonomous region has successfully conducted
artificial propagation experiments on the species. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
