<DOCNO> XIE19971202.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coal Mine Programs to Receive Assistance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Construction of new coal mines
in eastern and central China, like Shangdong and Anhui, will
receive development priority from the central government,
according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Coal-supplying bases in Shanxi, Shaanxi, western Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region and Guizhou will also be developed, a senior
State Planning Commission (SPC) official said yesterday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Coal resources are rich in these western provinces, which
transport coal to coastal areas, mainly by rail.
</P>
<P>
Li Hongxun, deputy director of the commission's Transportation
and Energy Department, said China is expected to produce 1.42
billion tons of coal this year, climbing to 1.48 billion by the
end of the century.
</P>
<P>
The construction scale, or the annual production capacity, of
State-owned coal mines is between 600,000 tons and four million
tons, Li noted. Meanwhile, the scale of open-cut coal mines is
three million to 15 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Outlined in the Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000), the
government allocates annually three billion yuan (360 million
U.S. dollars) to coal enterprises as low-interest assistance.
</P>
<P>
A sustainable development policy is being adopted within the
coal industry, in an effort to reduce ash and sulphur emissions.
</P>
<P>
Construction of power plants is being encouraged near coal
mines, coastal ports and railway hubs, according to Li.
</P>
<P>
China's installed capacity will be 290 million kilowatts and
electricity generation will be 1,400 billion kilowatts per hour by
2000, Li predicted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
