<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls Youth to Save Themselves from AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
called American young people to take measures to prevent
themselves from being affected by the deadly disease AIDS.
</P>
<P>
In a videotaped message to participants in a ceremony organized
by the Elizabeth Glaser Pediatric AIDS Foundation in observing
World AIDS Day, Clinton said the battle against AIDS shows some
signs of success, but HIV is affecting more and more young people.
</P>
<P>
"So this year let me send a special message to young Americans:
Only you have the power to keep yourselves safe," the president
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a conference on the impact of AIDS on developing
nations was held in Washington by the United Nations, the U.S.
Agency for International Development, the World Bank, and several
other groups.
</P>
<P>
A USAID report said the number of deaths resulting from AIDS in
Central Africa was so great that it was causing life expectancy in
that region to plummet to "medieval levels."
</P>
<P>
"Life expectancy, which has been steadily on the rise for about
three decades will drop to 40 years or less in nine sub-Saharan
countries by the year 2010 mainly because of this disease," USAID
administrator Brian Atwood said.
</P>
<P>
Carol Bellamy, executive director of the United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF), said that the observance of World AIDS
Day should focus on ways to protect the world's children from the
accelerating spread of the virus.
</P>
<P>
It was estimated that by the year 2010, as many as 40 million
children will have lost their parents worldwide to AIDS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
