<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First LPG Terminal Goes Into Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The first refrigerated
liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) terminal in China went into
operation yesterday in Taicang of Jiangsu province, a city near
the metropolis of Shanghai, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The LPG terminal, which consists of two 31,000-cubic-meter
refrigerated tanks, is expected to supply 500,000 tons of LPG
annually to the customers in the middle and down stream areas of
the Yangtze River and the coastal areas in east China.
</P>
<P>
In tandem with the country's rapid economic growth, China has
become the fastest expanding LPG market in the world in recent
years. Currently, 40 percent of its LPG demand relies on imports.
</P>
<P>
China imported 2.33 million tons of LPG in 1995 and 3.55
million tons in 1996. The figure is expected to be 6.83 million
tons by 2000.
</P>
<P>
The operator of the terminal is the Huaneng Amoco Clean Energy
Company, a Sino-US joint venture. Huaneng shares 52.5 percent in
the venture.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the LPG terminal was kicked off in
February 1996. Its total investment is 29.9 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The company has reached an agreement with Jiangsu Huayou
Changjiang Liquefied Gas Company, a special sales company
affiliated with China National Petroleum Corporation, to run the
business together, said Wang Shijun, general manager of the
Company.
</P>
<P>
The terminal imports LPG by large ships from abroad, and 70-80
percent of its volume will be loaded into vessels for distribution
along the Yangtze River, while the remaining 20-30 percent will be
loaded into trucks and bottles for distribution to nearby areas.
</P>
<P>
The company is expected to sell 300,000 tons in 1998, 400,000
tons in 1999 and 500,000 tons in 2000.
</P>
<P>
After additional investment, the company can enlarge its annual
capacity from its current 500,000 tons to one million tons.
</P>
<P>
The company is expected to become a leading LPG importer,
distributor and marketer in China, said Thomas King, deputy
general manager of the company. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
