<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Hits New High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar leaped to a
more than 5-year high against the Japanese yen Monday as traders
worried about more bad news will emerge from Japan's battered
financial sector.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currency advanced in early trading after Japanese
Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto told a parliamentary hearing
that Tokyo will do everything possible to protect bank depositors
and customers of securities companies.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto's testimony initially supported the yen, but the
dollar then jumped as traders began interpreting the remarks as a
harbinger of further failures after three Japanese financial
companies collapsed last month.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar settled at 128.91 yen, up
from 127.82 late Friday, after peaking earlier at 129.32. It was
the U.S. currency's highest level against the yen since 129.33 on
May 29, 1992.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also rose against mark and settled at 1.7771 marks
from 1.7645 late Friday, having reached its highest point since
October 22.
</P>
<P>
The dollar has gained 7 percent against the yen in last month
amid a serious slump in Asia's financial markets. It has exceeded
several levels once considered dangerously high by traders who
were worried that Japanese or U.S. officials would intervene to
halt the dollar's progress.
</P>
<P>
A stronger dollar exacerbates the countries' trade gulf by
making Japanese goods cheaper overseas and American products more
expensive in Japan. Traders said 130 yen now seems to be the
dollar's limit before government officials step in to sell dollars
and support the yen.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday:
1.4316 Swiss francs, up from 1.4263; 5.9475 French francs, up from
5.9035; 1,741 Italian lire, up from 1,727; and 1.4229 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.4233.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.6846 U.S. dollars, down from
1.6886 U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
