<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nazi Gold Conference to Be Held in London </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Representatives from some 40
countries will attend an international conference on Nazi gold in
London on 2-4 December to discuss unresolved issues on millions of
dollars of gold seized during the World War II.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day conference, the participants, including
diplomats, historians and non-government organizations
representatives, would focus on where the gold came from, what
happened to it and what steps taken to compensate victims.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook has indicated that Britain
wants a new fund established to assist needy victims of Nazi
persecution.
</P>
<P>
"Britain has proposed that the remaining gold be used to set up
a fund to compensate individual Holocaust victims and their
families, particularly those who so far have received little or no
compensation for their suffering," Cook was quoted as saying in a
Foreign Office statement.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that the conference will give a decisive push to our
proposal and that other countries will be encouraged to support
it," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Tripartite Gold Commission, set up in
1946 and run by Britain, the United States and France, has
restored most of the looted gold to its rightful owners and today
some 60 million U.S. Dollars worth of gold remains to be
distributed.
</P>
<P>
The Tripartite Gold Commission has always maintained that all
of the gold it is holding was looted from the central banks of
countries occupied by the Nazis. But Jewish groups have strongly
argued that between five to 10 percent of the gold belonged to
private victims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
