<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Supports Cyprus's EU Membership Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook said today that the divisions of Cyprus should not be
regarded as a barrier over the country's bid to join the European
Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Speaking in the House of Commons early today, Cook said: "We
want to see the maximum pressure for an end" to the 23-year-old
division of the island.
</P>
<P>
However, Cook stressed that Cyprus had a "very sound" case for
membership and ruling out its EU membership would weaken the
pressure that could be exerted for a settlement of the island.
</P>
<P>
The former British colony became independent in 1961 and the
island's Turkish and Greek communities have locked in fierce
disputes and armed conflicts over the past decades.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus is due to open negotiations with the EU next year after
Britain takes over the rotating EU presidency in January, but
leaders of Turkish-controlled northern Cyprus have expressed
strong opposition to the Nicosia government's application to join
the EU and even threatened to integrate with Turkey if accession
talks go forward.
</P>
<P>
In order to strike a balance, Britain has proposed to invite
all would-be EU members including Turkey to attend an
international conference on EU enlargement next year.
</P>
<P>
On Greek's opposition to inviting Turkey to the conference, Cook
said: "Fourteen EU member states have expressed no opposition. It
will not surprise members to know that Greece has reservations."
</P>
<P>
The British Foreign Secretary reaffirmed that Britain favors
the EU Commission's plan to open negotiations with Cyprus and five
east European countries -- Slovenia, Estonia, Hungary, Poland and
the Czech Republic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
