<HEADLINE> U.S. Calls Israel's Pullout Decision "Step in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The United States on
Monday called Israel's decision to withdraw its troops from more
parts of the West Bank "a step in the right direction."
</P>
<P>
"We view the Israeli government's decision in principle to
move forward with the further redeployment as a step in the
right direction," State Department spokesman James Rubin told a
regular briefing. "Now we are going to have to look at the
details and see how far it goes."
</P>
<P>
Rubin's remarks came as the Israeli government proposed on
Sunday to carry out one further redeployment in the West Bank
but the government set no scope or precise timetable.
</P>
<P>
According to agreements between Israel and the Palestinians,
Israel undertook to make three pullouts from mostly rural areas
of the West Bank before a permanent peace deal with the
Palestinians by mid-1999. The Sunday's proposal was the second.
</P>
<P>
But the Israeli government set up a list of conditions the
Palestinians must meet before even one soldier moves out.
</P>
<P>
Rubin told reporters that the United States always believed
that the agreements between the two sides "should be
implemented", which includes the further redeployments.
</P>
<P>
Asked by reporters if the Israeli proposal on further
withdrawal met with Washington requests, Rubin said he could not
go into details of something that remained the subject of
intensive consultations.
</P>
<P>
"The secretary of state (Madeleine Albright) has said she
believes there should be a greater sense of urgency on the part
of the parties to move the peace process forward," Rubin told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Washington has requested Israel to do something "significant
and credible" in pushing the peace process forward, which surely
includes the pullout of the Israel troops from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said what Washington was going to do was to "press very
hard behind the scenes and, when necessary, publically to make
clear the importance of the peace process, the importance of
moving."  
</P>
</TEXT>
