<HEADLINE> German Defense Chief Dismisses Reports about NATO's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 1 (Xinhua) -- German Defense Minister Volker
Ruehe today dismissed press reports that western allies are
seriously considering to move the headquarters of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) from Brussels to Bonn.
</P>
<P>
"There are no serious talks about the issue," Ruehe told
reporters in Bonn today.
</P>
<P>
According to an earlier report of the German news magazine Der
Spiegel, an increasing number of NATO members are pleading for a
NATO move to Bonn due to the worn-out NATO building in Brussels as
well as Belgium's failure to provide an appropriate additional
building for NATO in preparation for its planned enlargement in
1999.
</P>
<P>
The notion could be reinforced given the prospect that there
would be a redundance in office buildings in Bonn after Germany
completes its capital move to Berlin in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Der Spiegel also reported that NATO General Secretary Javier
Solana was expected to discuss the issue with foreign ministers of
NATO members even before Christmas and to make a decision next
Spring. 
</P>
