<HEADLINE> Dow Back Above 8,000 Mark Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 1 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks shot higher
today, pushing the Dow Jones industrial average back above 8,000
for the first time since October's overall slide.
</P>
<P>
Led by financial and technical shares, the Dow jumped 189.98
points to 8,013.11, still sitting nearly 250 points below its
record high of 8,259.31, set back on August 6.
</P>
<P>
Most broad-market indicators also posted big gains, with some
moving closer to record highs.
</P>
<P>
Wall Street opened higher after the Tokyo Stock Exchange and
other foreign markets showed new gains.
</P>
<P>
U.S. stocks drew an added strength from news that factory
activity remained brisk in November, but increased at a more
modest pace that could help contain inflation.
</P>
<P>
Advancers outnumbered decliners by a 2-to-1 margin on the New
York Stock Exchange. About 589.67 million shares changed hands on
the NYSE.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 19.37 to 974.77, less
than 9 points shy of record territory. The NYSE composite index
rose 8.63 to 507.73, moving within 7 points of a new high.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 30.17 to 1,630.72, but still
sits about 215 points from record territory.
</P>
<P>
Smaller-company shares failed to keep pace. The Russell 2000
index of smaller companies rose 4.24 to 434.16, and the
small-company dominated American Stock Exchange composite index
rose just 2.02 to 664.13.  
</P>
</TEXT>
